<HEADLINE>In at the cheap end</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROSS FINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>MOTORING</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863233</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ross Finlay dips into the budget range of cars available in Britain.
THERE is no clear definition of a budget-priced new car, and the best
that can be done to categorise these vehicles is to set an arbitrary
figure and look at what is available below it. Selecting a showroom
price of #5500 as the upper limit, three manufacturers cater for this
part of the market, and it is curious that they all take a different
approach.
One thing these makes have in common is that their ''budget'' cars are
built in Eastern Europe. Wage rates in the rest of the Continent make it
impossible for manufacturers in Britain, Italy, France, Germany, Sweden
or Spain to match such low ex-factory prices. However, the attraction of
these cars, for some owners, is not just price but also the fact that
they come with a full manufacturer's warranty.
Lada is usually thought of as the classic budget-level make. The
base-model Samara 1.3, in four or five-door form, just squeezes in under
the #5500 mark. It combines the modified Fiat-type mechanical units on
which all Ladas so far have been based, with a more modern body style.
The British importing company virtually dismantles the cars when they
arrive here, repainting them and upgrading the interiors, to make the
Samaras a little less rugged.
The Lada Riva may be outdated in every respect, but it is the cheapest
car on the UK market. Still a 1960s Fiat 124 lookalike, its sales
dropped sharply and then swung back upwards -- in the early part of this
year it sold half as many again as in the same period of 1994 -- as the
importers used their most significant weapon and held the price.
In the showroom the 1.5-litre Riva costs #3995, exactly the same as
the original Riva in 1985. The saloon, and the estate version at #4995,
must be the only vehicles on the market on which 10 years of inflation
has had no effect whatever. Servicing intervals on the Riva are quite
short, but the prices speak for themselves.
Renault has given up French manufacture of the one-time best-selling
5, but it is still on the UK market in the form of the Renault 5 Campus
Prima at #5478. In its heyday, the 5 was able to notch up annual UK
sales of more than 35,000 units. The rest of the range may have faded
away, but the Campus still sold 7353 examples here last year.
Production of the 5 has moved to Slovenia, the now-independent
northern part of former Yugoslavia which is not involved in any way in
the present Balkan war. Renault UK has never had a supply problem with
this car, which uses a 1.4-litre 60bhp engine, and is well enough
equipped as the bargain model of the whole extensive Renault range,
undercutting the entry-level 1.2-litre Clio by very nearly #1500.
Most modern of the budget car designs, and also the smallest, is the
jaunty little Fiat Cinquecento. There is a better equipped SX model, and
also a Cinquecento Sporting which is a real hoot on the road, but the
anchor car of the range is the Cinquecento S at #5450.
Intended mainly as a town car, the tiny 0.9-litre hatchback darts
around in city traffic, and copes with main road work better than you
might suppose. Built in a factory which Fiat equipped in Poland -- which
seems to work at more than 100% of its planned capacity -- the
Cinquecento accounts for nearly half of all European sales in the
mini-car market.
This is the kind of car which British buyers tend to approach rather
tentatively, but four in every five cars sold in this class here last
year were the little Fiats. They have obviously now got over some
original sales resistance to what is, in its own modest way, not only a
cheerful but also a slightly outrageous design.
</TEXT>
