<HEADLINE>The student room hunt gets hectic</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEWART FRASER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS HOMES,</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863234</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CARDS in shop windows. You see plenty of them, all over
Universityland. People looking for ''three girls to share flat'', or
''two men to share, plus share of bills'', or simply offering space at
so much a week or a calendar month.
The prices do vary quite a bit, you find. Anything from around #35 a
week to #70, from #160 a month to a surprising #320 -- the latter for a
family-size place, admittedly.
And this, of course, is the time when students really have to start
looking around for room to keep all their books and CDs and other gear.
What's on offer for them?
The universities as such have their formal arrangements. Halls of
residence and flats on campus take care of at least a proportion of
housing needs.
Strathclyde needs room for around 6000 students away from home. It has
Baird Hall on Sauchiehall Street, Clyde Hall down by the riverside.
Glasgow has Woolfson Hall on Maryhill Road. Caledonian has Gibson Hall
and the School of Art should be opening its own place fairly soon.
Typically, it is the first-year and overseas students who get first
chance, for a year at least. A second year may be balloted for.
At Strathclyde, housing officer Jennifer Gilmour deals with the
private rented sector. And it's not students that are her problem, she
says. It is more likely to be landlords offering accommodation but not
quite appreciating the financial viability of students in the current
economic situation.
''Students can only afford so much,'' says Jennifer. ''There's no
point in our taking on a flat that's going to be too much for them.''
It still leaves her with several thousand landlords on a
computer-based register. They stay on as long as there are no problem
areas seen to arise. And it leaves August-September as a pretty hectic
time all round. Term time is looming fast.
''The first thing we do is ask the students what they want,'' says
Jennifer. ''It may be self-contained, sharing with someone, sharing with
a family, whatever.
''Students can be very vulnerable. They are away from home, or have
come from overseas. We help them wherever we can. Advise them on
different areas of the city.
''Most of them prefer somewhere near at hand -- within walking
distance if possible. We limit our accommodation on offer to properties
within a three-mile radius of the university.''
Prices normally come within a range of #35 to #55 a week. A deposit of
#70 is typical -- and is repaid when agreed. A few landlords can forget
this is part of the bargain, apparently.
Family-type accommodation is also available, but in lesser numbers.
Here, a two-apartment flat could be available at just over #53 a week,
with #61 for a three-apartment.
Senior housing officer Ruth MacLennan sums up the Strathclyde
situation: ''Like all the universities, we need properties, but we don't
need problems. I suppose you could say it is a case of -- Look out. The
students should be looking out for suitable places now. And they should
certainly be looking out for proper contracts. You don't want to sign
anything unless it is exactly what you want.''
Sounds like good advice.
</TEXT>
