<HEADLINE>Christie decides he is fit enough to run in Zurich</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863235</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LINFORD Christie will run in tonight's Grand Prix meeting in Zurich
after all.
Christie lost his world 100 metres title in Gothenburg after suffering
a hamstring injury in his semi-final.
The British team captain did not compete in the 200m or the sprint
relay at the championships.
Later, after flying to Zurich for treatment, he admitted there was
also a cartilage problem.
British officials said they did not expect him to be back in action
before the meeting in Brussels a week on Friday.
But Christie announced last night after working out at the Letzigrud
stadium: ''I'm running.''
A spokesman for the circuit's richest meeting, which has a budget of
around #3m, confirmed it.
Christie, who still insists he is retiring at the end of the season,
joins a powerful line-up which includes the man who succeeded him as
champion -- Donovan Bailey.
He would clearly not have contemplated taking on such opposition if he
still felt severely handicapped by his problems.
Meanwhile, American Michael Johnson, who made history at the world
championships last week, could earn nearly $2900 a second if he breaks
the men's world 400m record at the same event.
Johnson, who secured a unique double in the 200m and 400m in
Gothenburg, has been paid around $62,000 just for turning up for the
meeting.
If the Texan betters compatriot Butch Reynolds' one-lap best of
43.29sec, set in the same Letzigrund stadium in 1988, he will leave
Switzerland with a further $50,000 plus one kilo of gold -- a total pay
day of around $124,500.
Zurich organisers have always refused to give specific details of the
appearance money paid to athletes. But sources said yesterday that
Johnson was one of the biggest earners at the meeting along with
Algerian world 1500m champion Noureddine Morceli, Kenyan steeplechaser
Moses Kiptanui, and Ethiopian 10,000m world record-holder Haile
Gebresilassie.
</TEXT>
