<HEADLINE>McDonalds on menu</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863236</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FAST-FOOD giant McDonalds yesterday joined the Premier League's
sponsorship family in a #7m deal, much of which will go towards
initiatives to boost match attendances among young people.
McDonalds have been awarded official restaurant status in the deal by
the Premier League, which gives them the right to use the league's logo
in all their marketing activities.
The agreement is worth #1.75m a year to the Premier League clubs and
is initially for two years, but with a further two-year option. Nearly
#1m a year will go towards the youth and family schemes.
Rick Parry, the Premier League's chief executive, said: ''McDonalds
has supported the Premier League with perimeter advertising since 1993
and is, of course, no stranger to football at the highest level through
its involvement with World Cups and European Championships.''
''This deal is particularly exciting for us because of the commitment
for the extension of facilities for families at Premier League grounds.
''I am genuinely delighted to have a name such as McDonalds associated
with us. It is an important deal for the further development of the
Premier League and another real vote of confidence in the quality and
reputation of top-class English football.''
</TEXT>
