<HEADLINE>Young brigade keep on course for the last eight. Under-21s show their big brothers the way to goal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863237</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Scotland 3, Greece 0
WATCHED by their senior brothers (closely, we hope), Scotland's
under-21 side did a fine job in disposing of the Greeks and maintaining
their strong challenge for a place in their European Championship
quarter-finals.
The Greeks had been reduced to 10 men before Scotland finally settled
matters but they were always the better team and, indeed, played really
well for most of the night.
The small crowd of 2517 at Rugby Park fully appreciated the skill and
willing work of the home side, who have two more home games to go in
their group, with the next game against Finland, at Broadwood on
September 6, looking like the decider.
The Scots were worth more than the single goal lead they held at
half-time, a goal scored by Dunfermline's Jackie McNamara, and were well
on top when Greek striker Ilias Sapanis was sent off for his second
bookable offence early in the second half.
Goals by Barnsley's Andy Liddell, a penalty, and substitute Simon
Donnelly, of Celtic, gave a far better reflection of their superiority.
It was their fifth successive victory in the group, after having lost
the opening tie against Finland.
With players of the calibre of Stuart Gray, Charlie Miller, Stephen
Glass, Liddell, and Neil McCann, they look well equipped to keep the run
going.
Not surprisingly, coach Tommy Craig could hardly contain his pleasure.
''I'm absolutely thrilled with every one of them, including those who
came on late in the game but if I had to single anyone out, Neil McCann
would be the one.
''I dropped him from the Toulon tournament and I left him out of the
original squad for this match because I didn't think he was tuned up to
be the player he can be. But he gave me a performance and gave us an
extra dimension.
''Andy Liddell also pleased me in his first game in this competition.
He is so unselfish.''
The one disappointment for him was that the booking of Pressley will
mean the Dundee United player will miss the game against Finland.
The Greeks seemed unconcerned about giving away corners but, although
nothing came from three in the early minutes, they didn't look all that
secure when a high ball landed in their midst.
But the goal the Scottish play had earned duly arrived in 16 minutes.
A clearance fell to McNamara on the edge of the box and his firm drive
deflected off a colleague and left the Greek keeper with no chance.
The keeper's team-mates didn't take too kindly to going behind, as
Kiassos demonstrated when he was booked after a wild lunge at Andy
Liddell.
There was always the risk of a breakaway from the Greeks and, indeed,
when one did come Pressley had to charge down a well-struck shot by
Providas.
Sapanis became the second Greek to be booked, for dissent at a
Scottish free kick.
Scotland began the second period in the same attacking vein, with Gray
robbing a Greek defender, surging forward, and hitting a shot that
landed on top of the net.
Greece came back, however, when Giannakopoulos hit a swerving
free-kick that touched the top of the bar before going out of play.
The Greek team suffered a blow in 53 minutes when Sapanis was sent off
after being shown the yellow card a second time. It was a very late
scything tackle on Miller that cost him his early bath and he could have
no complaints. Neither could Jamie Fullarton when he was booked for one
foul too many a minute or so later.
The second goal the Scots had worked so hard to collect came from the
spot in 57 minutes, and there was no doubt about its validity. McCann
went on a meandering run through a couple of tackles before the third
man in line tripped him inside the penalty area. Liddell made a sound
job of the award and Scotland were on their way.
They immediately replaced Fullarton with Neil Murray at the same time
as Greece took off Theodoridis and brought on Lakis. Four minutes it was
Simon Donnelly's turn to be called from the bench, taking over from
Steve Crawford.
The Celtic man was only five minutes in action before he headed in the
third goal at the far post after a well-flighted free kick from his
Parkhead team-mate, Gray.
Substitutes came fast afterwards. The Greeks put on a new keeper,
Georgiou, for Karkanis, and also took off defender Macheridis, bringing
on Grigoriou.
Scotland had to make a change, too, with Brian McLaughlin replacing
the limping McNamara.
he game as a contest was over which made Pressley's harsh tackle on
Providas, for which he was booked, seem a bit foolhardy.
SCOTLAND -- Stillie (Aberdeen), McNamara (Dunfermline), Pressley,
