<HEADLINE>Can they become just as pretty as this? Ruins to build your dream on</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEWART MACINTOSH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS HOMES,</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863238</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GRANNY'S Heilan' Hame is still a vital part of the urban dream. Most
of us live, work, and spend the bulk of our leisure time in towns or
cities. Yet our hearts are in the country. Owning a country cottage
offers the best of both worlds -- the social and economic advantages of
the city, complemented by the quiet charm of the countryside at the
weekends.
The only problem is that buying that dream cottage can become a
financial nightmare. Help is at from an unlikely quarter, however. The
Invercauld estate in Deeside is selling half a dozen properties at
prices from #12,000 to #35,000 -- prices that reflect the fact that they
need renovation or conversion (the estate has applied for planning
consent).
The disposal represents the second tranche of cottages and former
agricultural buildings put on the market by the estate via Savills.
Balintuim Bothy and Knockan Cottage, priced at o/o #20,000 each, will
each provide one-bedroom accommodation on a single storey. Balantuim
overlooks the Clunie Water, south of Braemar. The stone cottage has a
corrugated iron roof. Knockan Cottage is a former but 'n' ben at
Aberarder, close to Balmoral Castle.
Shenval is a former shepherd's bothy standing high in the hills above
the river Gairn. It is now very dilapidated, but comes with plans for
three bedrooms on two storeys and is priced at o/o #12,000. All three
enjoy open views to the magnificent scenery off Royal Deeside.
Balgairn Steading, just outside Ballater, is a former agricultural
building with plans to provide two reception rooms and kitchen on the
first floor, with three bedrooms, bathroom and double garage on the
ground floor. Offers for this, the most substantial of the properties,
are sought in excess of #35,000.
At Gairnshiel, adjacent to the A939 Ballater-Cockbridge-Tomintoul
road, is a group of three buildings . . .
Rinloan Garages (o/o #25,000) and Rinloan Kennels (o/o #20,000) have
planning permission for one- and two-bedroom residences respectively.
Rinloan Steading (o/o #5,000) has no planning permission but could
provide useful outbuildings to the buyers of the garages or the kennels.
All these properties are remote and need work and investment. Ruaraidh
Ogilvie, handling the sales from Savills' Brechin office, says interest
has come from all over Britain -- and from overseas. Most inquirers are
seeking second or holiday homes, but interest has also been expressed by
would-be refugees from the south-of-England rat race -- and writers or
craftsmen who can work from home.
''These properties are not everybody's cup of tea as they do require
total renovation and installation of services,'' he says, ''but for the
adventurous, they represent a great chance to acquire a property in a
beautiful, unspoiled area.''
</TEXT>
