<HEADLINE>Smith closes his cheque book after Salenko signs on</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863239</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RANGERS have finalised the signing of Russian international striker
Oleg Salenko, and manager Walter Smith conceded that his spending spree
is over for the moment.
Salenko's work permit was issued on Monday, and the player joined his
new Ibrox team-mates for training yesterday with the powerful suggestion
from Smith that he could be ready to play in the champions' opening
premier division game against Kilmarnock in 10 days.
''Oleg is a little bit behind the other players because the Spanish
season finished later than ours,'' said Smith, ''so he has had no real
pre-season work.
''That starts for him now and we would hope he could be ready for the
first league game. He is a proven goal scorer at the highest level and
we have needed someone of his ability to give us extra cover in that
area.
''There have been times when we have been stretched there because of
the injuries Mark Hateley and Ally McCoist have suffered in the past two
seasons.''
But Smith insisted that there is no way that Salenko's arrival will
mean a departure for either of the other two main front men at the club.
''The burden we have placed on Mark, in particular, has been heavy
over the last two years,'' said the manager. ''Both players are getting
older and we recognise that we required someone to join them.
''They are not on the way out, or anything like it. They are still
there and they will still make valuable contributions to Rangers, but we
knew they needed help and Oleg will give them that help.''
Salenko admitted that he had been influenced in his decision to join
up at Ibrox by his former Dinamo Kiev team-mates, Alexei Mikhailichenko
and Oleg Kuznetsov, who is now back with the Ukrainian champions.
He said: ''I talked to both my Kiev friends and they told me just how
big a club this is. I knew something of that but they told me more. I
wanted to change from playing in Spain and I am sure that this transfer
will be good for me.
Mikhailichenko, who acted as interpreter yesterday, added: ''Oleg is
ideally suited to the game in Scotland. He is brave, strong, and he is
fast. There are other things, too, about his game. He scores goals
regularly and he is a tremendous dribbler. I think that Oleg will be at
home with Rangers.''
Salenko, still just 25, is another player who will reduce the average
age of Smith's squad, something that the manager had been determined to
do this summer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
