<HEADLINE>Schumacher now wants Coulthard in Ferrari team</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863240</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE top two teams in Formula One, Williams and Benetton, are expected
to announce today their line-ups for next season, and anything less than
a studied look at the movements being discussed suggests misery for
David Coulthard, who is about to lose his place on the Williams Renault
team to IndyCar driver Jacques Villeneuve.
It appears the Scot will be moving to McLaren Mercedes, but it is my
understanding that Ferrari are considering a late, lucrative bid to
entice Coulthard into their team along with defending world champion
Michael Schumacher, who is about to confirm his move from Benetton
Renault to the famous Italian stable.
Ferrari would try to ease McLaren's anger by offering Gerhard Berger
in return for Coulthard, but it would be the second time the
Woking-based team would have lost out on the Scot. McLaren and Williams
took their dispute over Coulthard to the European Court in Geneva last
summer, but this time, McLaren believe they have secured their man.
Schumacher, however, is believed to have expressed a desire to have
Coulthard race with him, and one of Ferrari's main advisers, Nikki
Lauda, who won the championship for Ferrari in 1975 and '77, considers
Coulthard to have a future in grands prix despite the disparaging
remarks made by the 24-year-old's critics.
There are many who would take delight in seeing Coulthard's career
stall, and during the British Grand Prix last month, when it was
announced Coulthard, who was motoring well, had incurred a time penalty
for speeding in the pit lane, one or two English journalists were
jubilant.
Certain parties took an instant dislike to Coulthard, hailed as the
new golden boy of the circuits, who has rarely been given the benefit of
any doubts, and his departure from Williams will be seen as powerful
evidence of his inability to make it at the top of a demanding sport.
In his first grand prix season and just more than half way through the
course Coulthard, who finished second in Sunday's Hungarian Grand Prix,
is fourth in the drivers' championship and he is still learning about
life in the fastest lane.
Had he chosen to start with a less illustrious team, Coulthard would
not have been under so much pressure to produce the goods, and his
actions would not have been scrutinised so closely, but the legal case
caused him to be contracted to drive with Damon Hill. Team-leader Frank
Williams said there would be no team orders, but Coulthard has felt he
has not received the same treatment.
Minor errors, but ones which can make significant differences none the
less, seem to have been made more often by his back-up team.
He finished a distant second to Hill in Budapest, but said: ''My
performance over the weekend was compromised by a series of ridiculous
mishaps.''
For instance, after the first qualifying session he had secured a
place on the front row beside Hill, and later learned in debriefing that
too much fuel had been put in his car, which meant he was carrying more
weight than necessary.
In final qualifying when he felt he had timed to perfection the start
of his last run, with only four minutes remaining, no-one could find the
fuel and he couldn't go back out.
Yet he took second place behind Hill on the grid but again an error
cost him time early in Sunday's race. The blankets which heat the tyres
were set up wrongly and instead of his tyres gripping the track they
were melting.
Coulthard may have felt privately that too many mistakes were being
made and leaving Williams, with whom he is being paid something like
#500,000 for this season, will not be a wrench
McLaren and Ferrari, who believe they will have better machines next
year, are willing to pay him a salary in the region of #5m for a
two-year contract.
Schumacher would want Coulthard to help refine and develop the Ferrari
car, but although many would see this combination as the most powerful
on the grid, it might suit the Scot's purposes better if he were to go
with McLaren. With them he would be No.1 with Mika Hakkinen.
If he goes to Ferrari he will find Schumacher to be a most demanding
No.1, someone who must be given the best of everything. Johnny Herbert,
No.2 to Schumacher at Benetton, has suffered significantly because
everything is geared to keeping the German, who will be paid
approximately #25m to drive for the Italians, happy.
That will make Schumacher one of the highest-paid sportsmen in the
world putting him up there with America's big-name basketball players
and also the top heavyweight boxers. Jean Alesi is likely to leave
Ferrari and take over from Schumacher at Benetton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
