<HEADLINE>Victory for Brown's side would be tragic for Greece. Scots can take step closer to the finals</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER, CHIEF FOOTBALL WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863241</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE worries continued for Scotland yesterday as they attempted to
finalise preparations for one of the most vital international games in
recent seasons, against Greece at Hampden tonight.
Victory would push the Scots towards the finals of the European
Championships and, at the same time, effectively end the challenge which
Greece, dented recently after successive defeats from Russia and
Finland.
But while team-manager Craig Brown had hoped an early season game --
in fact a pre-season game -- would ease his perennial injury problems,
it has not worked out that way.
And now, this morning, Blackburn Rovers' defender Colin Hendry will
face a last-minute fitness test which will decide whether or not he has
shaken off the injury collected at Kilmarnock in a friendly last week.
Fortunately, however, Alan McLaren, of Rangers, yesterday worked out
with the squad and will be in place.
''Colin is doubtful,'' said Brown last night. ''He has been working
out with physio Eric Ferguson, and we will give him all the time he
needs but the odds are against him.''
Indeed, Brown is already looking at alternative strategies if the
blond Hendry fails to prove himself ready.
The versatility Brown has encouraged will now become crucial as he
juggles his players around to compensate for a Hendry absence, if that
becomes the case.
Motherwell's Brian Martin could go in as a straight replacement
without affecting the make-up of the rest of the defence. Or Tom Boyd
could go into the heart of the defence, a role he is now occupying with
Celtic.
And Stewart McKimmie, who ended up in that area in the game against
Russia in Moscow, could be asked to step in there from the beginning.
That would allow the impressive Craig Burley, of Chelsea, to take over a
wide, midfield role on the right.
Today will decide but Brown refuses to allow even this latest upset to
trouble him. The manager remained confident and stressed: ''I have not
even thought about anything other than a victory in this game. That is
what we need.
''I can recognise that if other results go our way, a draw might even
be enough -- but I don't want to consider that. And I don't want the
players to consider that either. This is a game where victory is so
important to this whole nation and that is what we want. We don't intend
to settle for any less.''
Brown has studied the Greek side, at first hand and on innumerable
videos, and he believes that even his depleted squad -- with Paul
McStay, Andy Goram, Duncan Ferguson, and John Spencer among those who
are out -- remain good enough to beat the Greeks.
''They will not be the team I would have expected to see here,'' he
said. ''The last two defeats will have affected them. Instead of coming
to Hampden looking for a point, as they must have anticipated a few
months back, they now have to get something more.
''The two losses will have upset them and changed their outlook. They
will be much more attacking than they would normally be away from home.
That, though, could help us. They will leave more gaps and we will be
able to exploit these openings from midfield.
''This area will be important for us and we do have form players
involved there. Gary McAllister and John Collins have been outstanding
for their clubs and I know that Stuart McCall and Billy McKinlay are
ready for this and looking good.
''If we can dominate there and keep possession then that could be
demoralising for them. I don't want any carelessness because they are
the type of team who can capitalise on one slack moment.
''The players have all been warned about that. We have to be patient,
pass the ball around, and frustrate them. I know that the fans will be
shouting for us to get the ball into their box, but I will tell them to
ignore the crowd. They have to shut their ears to all of that and
concentrate on playing the game and making passes which will eventually
count.
''That is very important.''
Even more important is that the Scots pressure the Greeks at every
opportunity. Patience is certainly a virtue in these European
circumstances but, there are times, too, when caution must be abandoned,
and when our natural instincts for attack are allowed to flourish.
To have that kind of old-fashioned approach may give all of us an old
fashioned Hampden night, one which has a meaningful victory at the end
of the 90 minutes.
Tickets for tonight's match, priced #12 and #14, will be on sale at
the usual outlets and also at the Hampden South Stand kiosk until
kick-off.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000009</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000009</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Geoffrey MacEwan, Glasite Meeting House</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CLARE HENRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863242</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEW life, new work, new venue. Geoff MacEwan's fortuitous move to
Majorca three years ago has pushed his paintings and prints from shadowy
complexity to high-key simplicity. A Miro Foundation award plus a spell
working with Ramon Liull, a top Spanish printmaker, has been productive.
His etching are now in Madrid's prestigious La Reina Sophia Gallery.
The pictures on show span a decade: from a Tom Philips-like Luther
exhibited at Edinburgh's old 369 Gallery in 1985 to Conquest of Love
1995, a set of four small but powerful and upbeat oils. MacEwan also
shows four impressive artists' books produced at Edinburgh Printmakers
in 1991/3.
This new venue, at 33 Barony Street, is perfect for MacEwan's work and
worth a visit in itself.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000010</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000010</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863243</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
* ABERDEEN defender Brian Irvine has bravely taken the first steps to
reviving his career.
Just a month ago the former Scotland player was told the news that he
was suffering from multiple sclerosis. But now he is back in light
training in his bid to be playing again this season.
Dons manager Roy Aitken said yesterday: ''Brian is undergoing regular
sessions of hydratherapy to build up his body strength so that he can
step up his training.
''We will do everything possible to assist him and everyone at the
club is pleased that he has able to make this progress.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000011</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000011</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bett's heartbreaker</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BROADLEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863244</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VETERAN Jim Bett has refused a new deal with Hearts -- news that has
alerted Dundee United and St Johnstone, who are both keen to acquire his
vast experience to boost their promotion challenges.
Bett, one of the most influential players of his era, said yesterday:
''Hearts offered me a three-month contract but I decided to wait for the
appointment of the new manager before making a decision.
''I spoke to Jim Jefferies and explained that the travelling from my
home in Aberdeen was now becoming a problem.
''I enjoyed my comeback to Scottish football with Hearts. They are a
good club and I wish them well.
''But I must do what I believe is best for me and my family at this
stage of my career.
''I will carry on playing if the right offer comes along.''
Bett also refused a new deal with Aberdeen 18 months ago because he
was disillusioned with declining standards in the premier division.
But Tommy Mclean enticed him to Hearts and Bett's midfield control
kept the Tynecastle side out of relegation trouble and steered them to a
place in the Scottish Cup semi-finals.
Now, it seems odds-on that he will move to Tayside for the final
chapter of an illustrious career.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000012</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000012</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ON THE ROAD OF THE KINGS</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS HOMES,</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863245</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
* NOT everyone likes the idea of a right of way across their land, but
Leithen Lodge comes with an impressively historical one. The medieval
kings of Scotland often crossed its site on an ancient route -- known as
the King's Road -- when they travelled from Edinburgh Castle to
Traquair, near Peebles.
The lodge itself was built in the last century -- where a former
gamekeeper's cottage once stood -- and was later substantially
redesigned by architect Sydney Mitchell.
Considered to be one of Scotland's finest houses in the Arts &amp; Crafts
style, it incorporates the Lochend Archway, built in 1684 for Sir John
Sinclair's house at Dunbar to the design of the classical architect
James Smith. The archway is believed to be one of the first Palladian
structures built in Scotland. It was re-erected at the lodge three years
ago.
Royalty no longer uses the ancient King's Road along the Leithen
Water, but the lodge is a gem in the Borders crown. Situated in a valley
in the Moorfoot Hills which lie between Edinburgh and the Borders, it is
an imposing and dramatic house with impressive facades and is built of
harled stone under slate and tile roofs, surrounded by lush green hills.
The main accommodation is laid out on three floors in the southern
section of the house. The main reception rooms, the drawing room and
magnificent music room, are on the first floor and linked by the
first-floor conservatory. The layout enables the doors to be opened into
the house, allowing the aroma of blossoms to pass through the rooms.
There are suites of rooms on the ground and first floor with a passage
of guest or nursery bedrooms on the second floor. The domestic quarters
are situated to the north of the house and are joined by a service flat
with its own access through the courtyard. At the back of the courtyard
are the former stables and coachhouse.
The house comprises: cloakroom, washroom, eight bedrooms, three
bathrooms, blue dining room, business room/study, green bedroom, China
pantry, kitchen, old kitchen, laundry room, library, study, organ room ,
drawing room, conservatory, and music room.
The flat comprises: utility room, sitting room, kitchen, dining room,
bathroom and two bedrooms. Leithen Lodge comes with 13 acres of gardens,
parkland, woods, and an original walled garden. Offers over #325,000 are
sought for it by estate agents Savills.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
