<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000014</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000014</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Change in line-up</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GORDON DUNWOODIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863247</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONLY three of the five-strong Scots side that dominated the last world
outdoor championships at Worthing in 1992 have retained their places in
the side for the Adelaide Championships next March.
Missing from the successful Worthing line-up are Angus Blair and
Graham Robertson.
Richard Corsie, Willie Wood, and Alex Marshall retain their places and
are joined by George Adrain and Kenny Logan.
Corsie, who lost out to Tony Allcock in the 1992 singles final gets
the chance to go one better and he and Alex Marshall will defend the
world pairs title they picked up at the Sussex resort.
In the triples, Logan lines up at lead, with Wood in the middle, and
George Adrain skipping.
The line-up in the fours has Logan and Marshall forming the front end,
with Wood playing third, and Adrain again skipping.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000015</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000015</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Driving ambition</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL CADGER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863248</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S top professional riders hit Glasgow today for round seven of
the city centre series and Sheffield's Chris Walker, the current leader,
will be going all out to seal overall victory and drive away with the
top prize of a car.
Walker, who races for Peugeot, will need to be firing on all cylinders
to beat off the strong challenge for the Glasgow Grand Prix, which
starts at 7.30.
Backing him up will be team-mates Shane Sutton and Neil Hoban. The
race is still wide open with fellow internationalists Mark Walsham and
Chris Lillywhite, who are lying second and third, sure to turn up the
pressure in this one-hour spectacular based around George Square.
There is a strong amateur representation in the big field and
Scotland's national squad of Roddy Riddle, Anthony Stirrat, Graeme Herd,
and Nicky Hall will be trying to ensure the pros don't get things all
their own way.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Heath's objective</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELSPETH BURNSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863249</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OBAN'S Martin Heath is hoping to follow in Peter Nicol's footsteps
when he launches the new season in this week's Singapore Open.
Nicol, the world No.4, has won the event for the past two years -- the
1993 triumph was his first major win -- but he is not defending as he
has geared his preparations towards the Hi-Tec Super Series and will
open his season in the Hong Kong Open in two weeks' time where he will
take on former British champion Paul Gregory.
Unfortunately, Nicol has had to give up his hopes of a third
successive victory in the European Champion of Champions in Monte Carlo
in October. The tournament clashes with the US Open -- another title he
is defending -- from October 19 to 22.
Heath, the world No.33, has split his summer's training between
Scotland and London, and Singapore offers the chance to boost his world
ranking and his World Open hopes.
If he can rise into the top 32 in the September list, he will be
seeded for the world qualifying in Cyprus in November and, therefore, an
improved chance of making his first appearance in the main event.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tyson can be better than the old model - trainer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863250</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOBODY should be surprised if an even more destructive and complete
fighting version of Mike Tyson takes its first bow at the MGM Grand in
Las Vegas on Saturday.
That is the anticipation of Tyson's newly-appointed chief trainer Jay
Bright, a long-time family friend who has seen the former world
heavyweight champion experience the highs and lows of a stormy and
successful career.
But Bright is not expecting to parade the finished article in phase
one of Tyson's high-profile comeback, even though Boston's Peter
McNeeley is not expected to last very long.
It will be a gradual rebuilding process, brick-by-brick, until
Fortress Tyson in ready to rule supreme again, visualises Bright.
''I think this Tyson could be better than the old one,'' forecasts
Bright, convinced that the Ironman has learned enough harsh lessons
about life during three years of incarceration to make him the
utterly-focused fighting man second time around.
''Mike has the ability to be even better because he's stronger
mentally, physically and now he's at his peak. It's going to take a
certain amount of time for things to come back, but that's nature, you
can't rush it.
''It's still there, it may have been buried, it may have been
submerged but it's still there. Whether the interest is still there? I
can't foresee that, but I believe it will.
''He does look a lot better than he ever has; his head movement is
very good, and so is his counter-punching. He's more aggressive. In
flashes he's quicker than he used to be.
''This fight really is the foundation of the house. You can't start
with the roof and the walls and the lovely wallpaper. You have to first
build that solid base.
''It's the real test, but it would be ridiculous to expect him to get
it all back in a couple of months. I'd rather have him concentrate on
his elusiveness, and technique and not just rely on power alone.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wanted: new homes for old</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEWART MCINTOSH, HERALD PRPOERTY CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS HOMES,</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863251</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE rapidly ageing population faces a dire shortage of custom-built
housing.Though Scotland scores better than the UK for the development of
sheltered and retirement housing, research into planning applications
over the last nine months shows there are only seven private schemes and
19 housing association projects in the pipeline in Scotland?
''This confirms my fear that the demographics of the retirement and
sheltered sector tell us one thing, but the industry is not confident
enough to build because of market conditions brought about by the
Government,'' says Howard Packman, managing director of Sheltered
Housing Services, an industry body which carried out the UK-wide
research.
''There should be huge demand as more and more people live longer and
move into the bracket of needing purpose-built sheltered
accommodation.''
Almost one million Scots are over pensionable age. At 17.8% of the
population, there are more retired people than schoolchildren. By 2001
the number of Scots over 75 will have reached 10%. Many of these people
will become frail or disabled, yet the gap between specialist housing
need and supply is growing.
''There is simply nowhere near enough retirement and sheltered housing
to meet the need,'' says Lucy McKenzie of Age Concern's Scottish Office.
The 911,789 Scots over retirement age are faced with a specialist
housing sector which provides accommodation for only 4% of households
where the householder is over retirement age.
Scotland can provide 30,839 sheltered houses for rent, plus 401 ''very
sheltered' houses (specially adapted for the frail and disabled) while
the need is for 15,000 of these. There are also 15,759 ''amenity' houses
-- a quarter of Scotland's requirement.
The private sector provides only about 2000 sheltered and retirement
houses, but as the UK's leading private-sector provider of housing for
the retired pulls out of the recession, three new schemes are under way
in Scotland. McCarthy &amp; Stone went through a bad patch two or three
years ago but is now getting back into its stride.
''But we're not building enough to meet demand,'' says Alan Gosland of
McCarthy &amp; Stone's Glasgow office. ''Having recovered from our difficult
period, we are now keen to meet a rapidly growing market. The
demographics are on our side -- but recently we haven't been able to buy
the land we need.''
After a showflat opened in his Corstorphine development last month,
sales went so quickly that only one flat now remains. Two other schemes,
at Giffnock and Helensburgh, are underway. But Gosland says his next
tranche of land deals will still come nowhere near meeting Scottish
demand.
Typical McCarthy &amp; Stone apartments cost around #60,000 for one
bedroom and #75,000 for two bedrooms. Service charges are from #20 per
week -- providing resident manager, 24-hour emergency call line,
maintenance, cleaning and gardening.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Anchor away - but Scots still lead</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDI ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863252</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ON THE second day of first leg of the Teacher's Round Britain
Challenge, the two Scottish boats were still holding the upper hand of
the 10-boat Five Nations fleet and leading overall on the water.
After slow progress overnight fighting the strong tide off Dover,
Glendronach, skippered by Oban's John Fitzgerald, overhauled the leading
boat, Dream Of Erin (David Harte, Ireland).
Fitzgerald and Chris Nichol, his first mate from Largs, had a minor
disaster overnight when their anchor line parted while anchored in dead
calm in a contrary tide.
''Suddenly, in the dark we realised the other boats were gradually
catching us, yet there was no evidence of wind anywhere. It became
obvious quickly that we were drifting backwards on the tide towards
them,'' said Fitzgerald.
By mid-morning yesterday the Scotland II crew held longer into an
offshore fog bank and were rewarded with the first of the forecast
south-westerly breeze which built steadily throughout the day. This
advantage allowed them to slip past the Irish boat, which was closer
inshore in less breeze.
By yesterday evening off Beachy Head by Eastbourne, Fitzgerald and his
crew were maintaining their three-quarter-mile lead, moving quickly
upwind in around 12 knots of breeze.
Paul Jeffes, skipper of the second Scottish boat, Lord Inverforth,
which lies third, was attempting to cover a move by the fourth and
fifth-placed Welsh boats skippered by Colin Lyons and Richard Tudor
respectively.
''So far we seem to have been able to find the better speed changes
with the varying winds, which is probably the result of spending a lot
of time tuning up our two boats together during last week,'' explained
the Scotland I skipper.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Racing</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863253</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DAVID O'Neill was banned for four days by the Folkestone stewards
yesterday for improper riding.
O'Neill, who finished second to Harding Brown on Zuiena in the BBC
Radio Kent Unbridled and Unrivalled Apprentice Handicap was found to
have used his whip with unreasonable frequency and force.
The stewards stood him down from August 24 to 27.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Graham would return to fold</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN BEATTIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863254</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GEORGE Graham, the former Stirling County and Glasgow prop and now a
rugby league player, has told The Herald that he would be interested in
coming back into the ranks of rugby union now that amateurism is set to
be quashed.
''I'd be telling a lie if I said that I wasn't very interested,'' he
said.
''At the moment I have two years left of my contract at Carlisle, but
my wife wants to come back to Scotland, and the club have always said
that if someone wants me to move, then they would look at the situation.
Now that it is possible to earn money at club rugby, I would want to
look at every possibility.
''I have been training very hard over the summer, and I feel as good
as I have ever done.''
The news has been greeted with barely disguised enthusiasm by his
former team-mates. Jim ''Muff'' Scobbie, Stirling's forward coach,
thinks that Graham would make a real impact in the 15-a-side game if he
were to return.
''George is a great player, and there's no doubt that we have missed
him since he went,'' he said. ''It would be fantastic to have him
back.''
Kevin McKenzie, the hooker with last year's championship-winning team,
also said he would like to see Graham in the red, white, and black of
his old club.
At the weekend, Jim Telfer, the director of rugby and now team
manager, said that rugby league would be the main sufferer when the
15-man game went professional, and the reaction of George Graham to an
innocent inquiry is perhaps an indication of how strongly many league
players feel about their own game.
League may be tougher and more physical in its demands of the human
body, but few of the converts from rugby union profess to enjoying the
game more when they move. The opposite is, in fact, the case.
Freddie McLeod has said that it remains to be seen just what the
outcome of the International Board meeting at the end of August means
for those league players who may want to come back to their original
game, and the question of whether league players who have never played
union would be allowed to join the ranks poses even more problems.
In my book, it would be good to see any league player who wants to
able to play union. Ally Tait, just one example, would make quite a
difference to the Scottish midfield.
Whether the amount of money on offer from our game would be enough to
entice these players back remains to be seen. Whatever, we should now
just let them back in.
The only trouble is that Wales would be a better team. I suppose there
has to be a downside to everything.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000022</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000022</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Meggetland effort to be first super-club. 'Muir brew a new deal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS,CHIEF RUGBY WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863255</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BOROUGHMUIR have signed a three-year sponsorship deal with Scottish
Brewers ensuring that the McEwan's logo, a fixture in Scottish rugby for
the past nine years before rivals Tennents came in this year to sponsor
the Scottish league and new Cup competitions, will still be around the
Scottish scene.
When Scottish Brewers bowed out of the national sponsorship scene
three months ago, managing director Collin Wood indicated that the
company would still be involved in the game but was turning its
attention to the grass-roots.
Yesterday's announcement is said to be the first of several
initiatives designed to aid club rugby throughout the season.
The deal is said by McEwan's to be worth a five-figure sum for each of
the three seasons that it will run.
Boroughmuir, who also are still in the running -- along with
Watsonians -- as recipients of the cash which Stirling Fibre millionaire
John Connor wants to plough into a club to create Scotland's first
super-club, are also hoping to profit from a #3.5m local authority
redevelopment at Meggetland.
The Meggetland playing fields, owned by Lothian Regional Council, are
due for a major overhaul and, despite objections by some local
residents, planning permission will be sought from Edinburgh District
Council this week.
The club have a staunch ally, well versed in local government
machinations, in the form of honorary president Eric Milligan, who is
convener of Lothian Regional Council and who was present at yesterday's
sponsorship announcement ceremony.
Lothian Regional Council intends a complete revamp of the local
authority changing-room facilities at Meggetland and the provision of a
running track and all-weather surface. If the development goes ahead,
and it may do so as soon as February of this year, then Boroughmuir
would benefit from a new clubhouse and greatly enhanced stand
facilities.
Wood said yesterday: ''Not only will McEwan's enjoy obvious commercial
benefits from sponsoring a club like Boroughmuir, but I am sure that our
team at McEwan's will be able to help the club meet their objectives
both on and off the pitch.''
Boroughmuir, Scottish champions in 1991, have also been busy during
the close-season, adding to their playing pool. They have signed up a
host of age-group internationalists, including Steven Wands from
Edinburgh Wanderers, Peter Flockhart from Stewart's-Melville, Craig
Hunter from Currie, and Graham Beveridge from Peebles.
Their most significant acquisition, however, is GHK flanker Fergus
Wallace, who most recently captained the Scottish development squad in
Zimbabwe this summer and who, according to Boroughmuir coaching director
Bruce Hay, was attracted to Meggetland by Derek Stark during the
Zimbabwean trip.
Hay said: ''The aim has been to build a strong squad for the new
leagues. I reckon that the demands are going to be so great, weekend in
and weekend out, that a squad of at least 25 is going to be an absolute
must if a club is going to be successful.''
Boroughmuir have an early opportunity to gauge progress since last
season, when they finished fifth in the championship, when they compete
in Euro Cup 95, a five-day tournament in Leiden, Holland, next week.
Other teams involved are Wasps, Blackrock College, Pontypridd, Leiden,
and the Belgian side Reveries.
* WESTERN Samoan rugby union star Fata Sini has joined Salford on a
12-month contract.
Sini follows international team-mate Mike Umaga into rugby league
after his move to Halifax and is Salford's second Samoan signing this
summer. They had already snapped up forward Lokeni Savelio from New
Zealand club Hutt Valley.
The 26-year-old Sini, who was also wanted by Widnes and Sheffield,
impressed League scouts with his two-try performance for Western Samoa
against England in the World Cup two months ago in South Africa.
</TEXT>
