<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Leiper can be the inspiration</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOSEPH DILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863259</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AFTER having missed out on the 1991 finals in Paris, Scotland return
to the European Nations' Cup in Dublin today, but any thoughts of an
easy passage have been dispelled.
In their nine-match build-up, Scotland managed only one victory, a 3-1
success against France, after having lost 4-1 to the French in the
opening game in a three-match Test series.
This is certainly not the form of potential medallists, but manager
Alistair Tait explained: ''We have not gone out of our way to play easy
sides in the course of our preparations.'' Those demanding assignments
against the likes of England, Ireland, Canada, and the USA could prove
decidedly more difficult than some of the teams they will play in
Dublin.
Tait, nevertheless, will be concerned by the absence of real class in
the side brought about by the withdrawals from the squad of eight
players, including Andrew Hay, Paul Doney, Derek Cunliffe, Alan Sword,
and Philip Webster through injury or unavailability.
Considerable pressure will now be placed on the shoulders of David
Leiper at full back, not just for his experience, but also for his
vision, composure, and expertise at set-pieces.
Their opening game tonight is against championship favourites Holland,
who have produced some flashes of brilliance in beating Ireland 5-0, and
England 5-1 and 5-2. Both these countries have beaten Scotland
conclusively, and so the signs are ominous.
It is likely to be a damage-limitation exercise against the Dutch but
in the following games -- against Belgium, Wales, and France -- the
Scots could pick up sufficient points to fulfil Tait's target of ''a
top-eight finish.'' Today's games:
Pool A -- Belgium v Wales, Spain v France, Scotland v Holland.   Pool
B -- Ireland v Belarus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lamb hits out at drunks</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863260</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALLAN Lamb blamed alcohol for sparking ugly crowd scenes that soured
yesterday's NatWest trophy semi-final at Headingley. Police and stewards
had to rush into the Western Terrace as fights broke out while Lamb's
Northamptonshire team were beating hosts Yorkshire by 87 runs.
''What makes me sad is that people come to watch cricket and then you
get behaviour like that,'' said Lamb. ''I think it is down to alcohol
because these things always happen later in the day. I don't know what
the answer is unless you ban alcohol.''
Yorkshire have promised to launch an investigation into the crowd
scenes. Several pieces of fruit were thrown at Northants fielders, but
Lamb made light of those incidents. ''Our boys were feeling a bit hungry
anyway,'' he said.
Fifteen spectators were arrested, with several others ejected from the
ground.
At Glamorgan, Dermot Reeve's Warwickshire waltzed into a third
successive NatWest final by beating the home -- and silencing a Cardiff
crowd that three weeks ago had hurled verbal abuse and dangerous objects
at them.
The Welsh county increased stewarding and policing levels to prevent a
repeat of yobbish scenes during last month's Sunday League game.
Warwickshire won by eight wickets after having bowled out Glamorgan
for 86, keeping alive their dream of emulating last year's hat trick of
titles. Tim Munton was man-of-the-match for his 12-over spell of two for
18. Scores:
At Cardiff, Glamorgan 86; Warwickshire 88-2. Warwickshire won by eight
wickets.
At Headingley. Northamptonshire 286-5 (R J Bailey 93no, A J Lamb 63);
Yorkshire 199. Northants won by 87 runs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000028</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Egg producers attack 'marketing con trick'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS, FARMING EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863261</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LOOPHOLE in European legislation is allowing imported eggs to be
packed and sold in this country as if they were home-produced, it was
claimed yesterday.
The Scottish Egg Producer Retailers Association, which is concerned
about the decline in numbers of eggs produced in Scotland is campaigning
to have country of origin printed on all pre-packed cartons.
Dennis Surgenor, secretary of the association, said he believed most
shoppers in Scotland wanted to buy home-produced eggs. However, European
regulations meant it was possible to import eggs from Italy, grade and
pack them in England, and present them on the Scottish market in a
pre-pack marked with a Scottish name and address.
It was also possible to have eggs packed in another EU member state
with a Scottish packer's name and address on the carton.
Members of the Scottish association took their campaign for
country-of-origin stamping to London recently, but found that the large
packers, represented by the National Egg Marketing Association, were
against the proposal.
Mr Surgenor said that he could only assume their opposition was based
on the large number of imported eggs they were handling. ''At present we
have in Scotland eggs imported from outwith the UK sold in a pre-pack
with a Scottish address, giving the impression that the eggs in the pack
are 'local','' he said. ''This is a marketing con trick and one way of
stopping it would be to mark all pre-packs with country of origin. It is
done for fruit and vegetables, why not eggs?''
In a small survey he found that purchasers used the address of the
packer as a means of determining the nationality of the egg. All those
who took part chose a pack with a Midlothian address as representing
Scottish produce -- but the eggs actually came from the Republic of
Ireland.
All pre-packs are stamped with a packing station number which
identifies the country of origin. These codes are not known to the
general public, however.
Mr Surgenor accepted that Scottish producers were at present meeting
only 65% of the home demand for eggs. A move to stamp country of origin
on packs could lead to a boost in Scottish sales and would give
producers the confidence to increase production, he suggested. ''We
would prefer Scottish eggs for Scottish customers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gary back in action at last</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS CHIEF RUGBY WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863262</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL scrum-half Gary Armstrong makes his comeback after a
16-month lay-off in a charity game in Edinburgh on Sunday.
Armstrong, 28, who made his last appearance in the Scotland game
against Ireland in 1994 when he tore tendons in his thumb before
suffering a devastating knee injury in pre-season training almost
exactly a year ago, has been working his way back to fitness since
receiving the all-clear from the medics three weeks ago.
The charity match at Bangholm is being hosted by Trinity Academicals
in memory of Dr Calum Guthrie, an Accies player who died, aged 29, from
a brain haemorrhage while on a skiing holiday in France earlier this
year.
Armstrong will be joined by a number of other Scottish
internationalists in the game between a Trinity Academicals-Scottish
Select and Edinburgh Royal Infirmary-Scottish select. The admission
charge -- #2 for adults and #1 for children -- is in aid of the Scottish
Orthopaedic Research Trust into Trauma organisation, the charity
nominted by Calum's parents.
Event organiser Allan McLeod said: ''Gary has benefited considerably
from SORT and is keen to show his appreciation.''
As revealed in The Herald, Armstrong has now recovered his appetite
for the game and is determined to force his way back into the Scottish
international side.
Yesterday, he said: ''It's been a long, hard struggle back to fitness.
I was four-and-a-half months off work and made scores of trips to
Edinburgh after the operation to put the left knee back together.
''I was invited to take part in the charity game on Sunday and it's an
ideal way to get back. I've been taking contact on the knee at training
and don't seem to have suffered any adverse effects.''
Surgeons used carbon-fibre material to reconstruct Armstrong's knee,
which was the same one damaged in a club game three years ago.
''I could have opted for the Sevens at Kelso or Selkirk but I don't
reckon that my match fitness is quite good enough to take part in a
sevens tournament. The charity game is ideal,'' he said.
Among the other internationalists who have indicated that they will
take part are Gavin and Scott Hastings, Ian Jardine, Graham Shiel, Craig
Chalmers, Peter Wright, Kenny Milne, Kevin McKenzie, Stuart Campbell,
and brothers Fin and Jim Calder.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000030</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000030</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Milk quota penalties</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863263</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UK milk producers who exceeded their quota in the ''milk year'' which
ended on March 31 will have to pay penalties totalling just over #48m,
the Intervention Board announced yesterday.
The levy will be #43.4m (30.45p per litre) for wholesale deliveries
and #4.7m (16.26p per litre) for direct sales. Across the UK wholesale
milk production exceeded quota by 152 million litres and direct sales
quota was exceeded by 15.4 million litres.
The levy will be paid by the purchasers of milk -- such as Scottish
Milk or Wiseman Dairies -- who will then collect the money due from
individual farmers who were over quota. Scottish Milk said it would be
issuing a statement to producers shortly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000031</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000031</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>We can beat Americans -- Gallacher</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863264</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RYDER Cup captain Bernard Gallacher yesterday backed his European team
to upset the odds and defeat the USA side that Lanny Wadkins has chosen
for the biennial clash in Rochester, New York, next month.
The United States have been quoted as 2-5 favourites to retain the
trophy at Oakhill Country Club on September 22 to 24, after Wadkins gave
his two ''wild cards'' to the experienced Curtis Strange and Fred
Couples.
But Gallacher said: ''I am not surprised by his choices and I don't
want to dwell on the merits of the American team.
''I believe there were a lot of good things for us in last weekend's
US PGA Championship and I am confident that we have the ability to win
the Ryder Cup back.
''There was a big European entry in the tournament and I was pleased
to see Miguel Angel Jimenez, Constantino Rocca, Sam Torrance, Jose Maria
Olazabal, and Nick Faldo all return sub-par scores.''
Gallacher singled out Scotland's Colin Montgomerie for special praise
after his play-off defeat by Australia's Steve Elkington at the Riviera
Club in Los Angeles.
He said: ''I am disappointed he didn't win, because he deserves to win
a major, but I believe he is the best player in the world at the
moment.''
The European team will be announced on August 28 and Gallacher knows
he faces selection problems.
With just this week's Czech Open and the German Open on August 24 to
27 to go before the team is finalised, Faldo, Ian Woosnam, Olazabal, and
Sweden's Jesper Parnevik are all outside the top 10 places in the Ryder
Cup points table which guarantee selection.
Gallacher said: ''There are up to five places in the team up for grabs
and it is up to the players to play themselves into the team.
''I believe it is a good situation for us, because it means that
players who force their way into the team will be in form at the right
time.''
Gallacher's biggest task will be choosing his two ''wild cards'', but
he added: ''It was difficult for Lanny Wadkins and it has always been
difficult for me. There is a lot to consider.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sheep scab publicity call</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863265</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CALL for the names of farms where sheep scab is found to be
published in the Veterinary Record -- the vets' professional magazine --
has been made by Terry Boundy, a Welsh vet regarded as one of the UK's
leading experts on sheep health.
Arguing for scab to be classified again as a notifiable disease, Mr
Boundy said: ''The country is in a mess with this scab and we, as vets,
do not know where it is. Publishing the names would be better than this
busines of picking up some whispered comment at the market. Farmers
would have to do something about it.''
Mr Boundy insists that when scab is discovered it should be eradicated
by a programme of treatment supervised by officials from the relevant
agriculture department.
Although opposed to compulsory routine dipping, he accepts dipping is
still the most effective way of combating the problem in large flocks.
In view of the various health scares arising from the use of
organophosphorous dips -- and the fact that some farmers fail to ensure
the sheep are totally immersed -- he advocates the use of trained
specialist operators.
A Scottish Office spokesman said that while scab was no longer a
notifiable disease it was still subject to welfare legislation and
farmers were obliged to treat it.
* AN Ayrshire dipping contractor, Hugh Blythe of Nether Culzean Farm
near Minishant, said yesterday that he had found it impossible to obtain
the type of gloves prescribed for use when handling OP dips. ''In my
experience they are just not on the market,'' he said.
Mr Blythe said the recommended gloves were supposed to be unlined,
made of PVC or Nitrile, half a millimetre thick and 300 millimetres
long. He had been unable to get any which met all of these
specifications and was using very thick, long rubber gloves -- ''but the
dip does eat away at them''.
A spokesman for the Health and Safety Executive said several companies
had imported gloves which met the specification. Anyone experiencing
difficulties should contact the HSE National Responsibility Group for
Agriculture at Stoneleigh, Warwickshire.
Part of the problem may centre on the definition of unlined. Some
gloves have protective material sprayed on to the cotton outer part.
These are not recommended because chemicals could seep down inside.
Others made from PVC or Nitrile may have a flock lining sprayed on after
manufacture. They are considered safe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots suffer a whitewash</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863266</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S recent domination of the girls' home international golf
series looks to be at an end after they suffered a 9-0 whitewash at the
hands of England on the opening day at the Northope Country Park
yesterday.
The Scots were never in contention after having lost all three of the
morning foursomes matches, although the final margin probably flattered
England a little.
Of the individual matches, three went to the eighteenth and four more
were not settled until the penultimate hole.
''We actually played some very good golf but on the day we were beaten
by a superb side and have no complaints,'' said Scotland captain Fiona
Rennie.
Scotland needed to make in-roads at the top of the singles order but
that never materialised. Laura Moffat was two down at the turn to the
English girls' champion Rebecca Hudson, and Heather Stirling went three
down to the big-hitting Gillian Nutter.
Hudson closed out victory by 3 and 1 while Nutter withstood a strong
comeback from Stirling before finally taking the match on the home
green.
Lower down the order, only Shona McEwan was ahead after nine but she
failed to maintain her advantage and also lost at the last, to Lisa
Walters.
Scotland will be looking to return to winning ways when they take on
Ireland in their second match of the series today.
However, that will not be easy, as Ireland also looked impressive in
an 8-1 victory over Wales. Results:
England 9, Scotland 0 (English names first) Foursomes: R Hudson and G
Nutter beat L Moffat and S McEwan 1 up: G Scase and L Wixon beat C
Hunter and L Mackay 2 and 1; L Walters and J Clingan beat H Stirling and
F Lockhart 2 and 1.
Singles: Hudson beat Moffat 3 and 1; Nutter beat Stirling 1 up;
Walters beat McEwan 1 up; Clingan beat G Melvin 4 and 2; Scase beat
Hunter 2 and 1; Wixon beat K Burns 3 and 2.
Ireland 8, Wales 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS HOMES,</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863267</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
* HERE is what a determined restorer can do. Originally three separate
dwellings, the thatched-roof Honeysuckle Cottage looks like a picture
from a chocolate box. Yet it too was a ruin until Edinburgh District
Council acquired the three parts for renovation in the 1950s. Nestling
under the Pentlands at Swanston only six miles from Ediburgh, the Grade
A listed cottage seems to have allowed the twentieth century to pass it
by -- though the city bypass is nearby. Accommodation comprises: a
living room with wood-burning stove, two bedrooms, kitchen and bathroom.
Langley-Taylor seeks offers over #135,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cecil's Lombardic holds appeal in Ebor</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WHITE GOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863268</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LOMBARDIC, groomed for a career over hurdles last season, can land a
big handicap on the Flat by taking the Tote Ebor today at York.
The Private Account colt, who showed useful form on the level for
Barry Hills in 1994, was sent to David Nicholson in the autumn of last
year to be prepared for a novice campaign, however, he cut little ice in
two outings.
Since moving to Julie Cecil's stable in the spring, Lombardic has
shown himself a tough and progressive animal -- just the type for this
#100,000-added race.
He began this campaign with a respectable fourth to Wishing -- who
reopposes here -- in a handicap over course and distance.
More forceful tactics paid dividends in the valuable Old Newton Cup at
Haydock next time, in which Lombardic beat the progressive Diaghilef.
Making all the running, he was asked for an effort with more than a
furlong to run and responded generously to fend off the runner-up by a
neck.
Bearing a 3lb penalty, Lombardic once again made all, this time in a
three-runner Rated stakes at York, beating Glide Path by threequarters
of a length.
Both victories were achieved by less than a length but that does not
mean Lombardic's winning run is about to end.
He is simply not the type to win races by wide margins -- a
contributory factor towards his lenient mark here.
The step back up to a mile-and-threequarters will suit the
four-year-old, as will the fast ground, and York's reputation as a
friendly track for front-runners makes Lombardic (12-1 with the
sponsors) even more appealing.
Of his 20 rivals, Michael Stoute's progressive Embracing may provide
the biggest danger.
This Reference Point filly attempts a five-timer after wins at
Hamilton, Sandown (twice), and Goodwood, and has been the subject of
quite an ante-post gamble.
* MONDAY'S meeting at Hexham has been thrown into doubt due to the hot
weather. The going at the course has been officially described as hard
and officials will hold an inspection at noon on Saturday to decide if
racing can take place.
</TEXT>
