<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sedgwick pays price of uncertainty on profits</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863270</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INSURANCE broker Sedgwick's chief executive Sax Riley seemed a little
uncertain yesterday whether he was issuing a profits warning. The City
certainly thought so and knocked 10p off the shares to a year's low of
127p.
That is a blow to a company which, because of its international spread
with just a third of its business in the UK and market dominance in some
areas, is of sheer necessity an essential player in the probable
reorganisation of the broking sector.
Mr Riley said the second half would not mirror the first which saw
virtually unchanged pre-tax profits of #63.1m.
The problem is that UK commercial rates have fallen by about 20% in
the last couple of months with property particularly affected. That
reflects both general over-capacity in writing business by British
insurers who are also faced by more and more larger companies
self-insuring while the Continentals find the UK an attractive long-term
place in which to do business and so are buying market share.
A weakening dollar knocked #3.5m off interim profits with another #2m
slippage likely if current exchange rates prevail. The United States
accounts for a similar proportion of business as the UK.
Sedgwick is cost cutting by amalgamating its Sedgwick Payne and
Sedgwick Europe businesses to increase its global coverage and
cross-fertilise product sale between commission business and consultancy
on matters such as employment and the environment.
It is possible it could do a deal with a High Street bank to sell its
insurance products but, like everyone else, Sedgwick is waiting for the
return of consumer confidence. At present, it is using independent
financial advisers.
Significantly, while it held #649m gross cash at end June, it refused
to say how much was client money and how much was directly owned and so
leading to conjecture about the size of the war chest.
Full-year profits look like slipping about #4m to #90m. The interim
dividend has been held at 3p but an increase in the final to 6.75p is
possible for an attractive 6.6% yield on a stock which has decided
speculative possibilities.
</TEXT>
