<HEADLINE>Course record beckons for first-round leaders</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SCOTT CROCKETT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863271</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GRANITE CITY CLASSIC: By SCOTT CROCKETT
A PROFESSIONAL course record which has stood for a quarter of a
century will be broken at Hazlehead today when the #12,500 Granite City
Classic tees off.
No pro event has been staged at the Aberdeen municipal course since
Peter Oosterhuis carded a three-under-par 67 during an exhibition match
in 1970 to herald the opening of the new clubhouse.
With three new tees in place since then, whoever returns the lowest
card in today's first round of the reduced Tartan Tour event will have
the honour of succeeding the Sky Sports presenter.
Originally planned as a 72-hole tournament, the event has had to be
cut to 36 holes, with the prize-fund similarly halved after proposed
funding from Aberdeen District Council did not materialise.
However, SPGA officials admitted pleasure at seeing the tournament,
even in its reduced state, returned to the Tartan Tour schedule after an
absence of nine years.
Sharing the joy will be Montrose pro Kevin Stables -- who will at last
get the chance to defend the title he won at Royal Aberdeen away back in
1986.
* BRITISH Amateur champion Gordon Sherry made a steady start to the
Canadian Amateur Championship at Toronto Golf Club yesterday, carding a
one-over-par round of 71 to trail first-round leader Mike Brewer by five
shots.
The Kilmarnock Barassie player, who controversially opted out of his
own country's flagship tournament in to play in Canada, recovered well
from a disappointing start. He ran up a double-bogey 6 at the 448-yard
third but hit back with a birdie at the eighth.
The 21-year-old birdied both of the par-5s on his inward half and is
well placed to qualify for one of the 56 matchplay places following the
final strokeplay round today.
* PALACERIGG'S Phyllis Gray achieved a last-minute success in the
Daily Express Glenmuir Women's Championship Scottish qualifying at
Dalmahoy yesterday.
The 48-year-old, who has been playing the game for only six years,
posted a two-under-par round of 66 across the West Course at the West
Lothian venue.
That proved good enough to snatch a late win from Elaine Wilson, of
Craigie Hill, by a single stroke. The 22-year-old three-handicapper had
held pole position all day with a one-under-par net score of 67.
Both competitors will now represent Scotland in the national finals of
the tournament at Palherio, in Madeira, in November. Leading scores:
66 -- P Gray, Palacerigg, (27). 67 -- E Wilson, Craigie Hill, (3).
</TEXT>
