<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>GA on lookout for acquisitions</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<FLAG>COMMENT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863272</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RECENT upheavals in the life insurance sector, such as the move to
full commission disclosure, have increased competition in the industry
and there are clearly too many players in the market.
Yet there has been little major rationalisation as yet. Indeed, more
companies have been established as banks and building societies have set
up their own in-house operations.
Yet it is inevitable that some of the smaller companies will find it
difficult to carry on. One, London Life, has recently closed its life
fund to new business and there are bound to be others which follow its
example or are taken over.
General Accident is keeping a close eye on the industry with a view to
making acquisitions, though chief executive Nelson Robertson yesterday
indicated expansion would also occur organically.
He sees opportunities arising as companies reposition themselves in
the market and as rationalisation gets under way. The search for
acquisitions is not limited to the UK. The group is also keen on the
Asia-Pacific region. Rex Parker, GA director for the region, explained
that there were a number of takeover possibilities, especially of
under-capitalised family run insurance companies.
GA itself is in good shape to make acquisitions, given low gearing and
a strong asset position, with the per share figure of 556p up 25% on the
end of 1994, and the improvement in its operating ratio (claims plus
expenses as a proportion of premiums) which now stands at a shade under
107%.
In the first six months to the end of June taxable profits jumped to
#256.3m, up 24%.
The insurance cycle is heading down and GA's second-quarter profits
were barely ahead at #143.4m but the trough will be shallow compared
with past experience. Bob Scott, head of GA's UK operations, is already
talking of a hardening in motor rates, which lead the market, by the end
of the year.
GA's UK motor rates were reduced by 5% at the beginning of the year
and generally have flattened out. Household rates are down 15% since
last autumn and are thought to have a little further to fall. Commercial
rates have only recently started to soften so will probably not bottom
out until next year. The group is concentrated in the smaller company
sector where competition is less fierce.
The rate declines being seen bear no comparison with the movements in
previous cycles, largely because the insurance companies now have access
to so much information on which to base their prices, as a result in the
explosion in cheap computer power availability of computers.
GA's present life side is trading well under the circumstances with
first-half profits up 13% at #29.3m. New UK annual premiums were down
22% but single premiums more than doubled owing to the success of a
guaranteed bond.
Second-quarter UK underwriting surplus dropped from #63.2m to #53.1m
with the trend likely to continue in the rest of the year, but this is
being offset by improvement in North America.
In the US, the first-half underwriting loss was trimmed from #68.3m to
#49.6m. and, while lower weather losses contributed much of this
decline, GA says there is an underlying improvement which will be
maintained.
The US side has finally got a handle on the involuntary motor
business. State authorities force all motor insurers to take on a
proportion of otherwise uninsurable drivers if they want to carry on
business in the state. GA's voluntary motor business is actually in
profit and Walter Farnam, who is in charge of the US operation, says the
volume of involuntary business is falling while premiums are rising.
Canadian losses were halved to #17.8m with the full benefits of
premium rises still to come. The European figures show no improvement
but GA said the underlying trend is more encouraging. A deterioration in
the second quarter was due to some large claims and additional reserve
strengthening. The Asia-Pacific business slipped into small losses
because reserves had to be strengthened in Australia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000040</DOCNO>
