<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Earning its wings</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEWART FRASER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>YACHTING BOATING</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863274</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A tour de force of a cruiser impresses Stewart Fraser.
LEAVING Largs boat haven, we head out at 330 degrees. Engine speed
1000 rpm. No need for trim tabs. The Seawings 277 purrs over a quiet
sea, past some boats with flapping sails.
''Like to open her up a bit?'' says Angus Scott. And with the blessing
of Euroyachts' director, off we go.
This modern sports cruiser, from Hardy Marine, is like chalk and
cheese compared with previous fisherman-style boats.
Moving the throttle forward brings a surge of power. Pushing the trim
tab button eases three tonnes of GRP on to the plane. The tabs are
variable hydraulic, with indicators.
The sterndrive has power trim and tilt, again with indicators. Pushing
a button is as much effort as you need expend on a craft of this style.
The engine registers 3000 rpm, a steady 20.1 knots on the electronic
instrument panel. The Largs ferry is out on port, heading for home. We
simply sweep by, well clear, and no worry for anyone.
Steering is from starboard. Navigation charts are under clear acrylic,
to port. We know where we're going. Past Rothesay Bay, up to the
narrows, on past Tighnabruaich, right round Bute and back to the marina.
An easy afternoon trip.
Angus opened up the unique sunroof before we left, like a T-bar roof
in a sports car. In good weather, you get all the sunshine. Come dark
clouds or rain, you're warm and cosy under a welcome hard-top.
The roofline can be extended right aft, over the cockpit table and
seats: al fresco if you wish, covered if necessary. It makes for an
all-year-round craft.
In fact, it's unashamedly a luxury and comfort cruiser. From wrap
around windscreen, with freshwater screen wash, to cockpit shower line,
hard work is not the issue.
The dinette table in the carpeted main cabin, is served from a galley
with laminated worktop and safety handrails. The stainless steel sink
has mixer tap, three burner gas hob, oven and grill.
Behind a curved wooden door is the toilet, shower and hand basin.
There's lighting, a mirror, a towel holder, even a toothbrush and glass
holder.
There has been some thought to make this a good family boat. Forward,
is space for a large double berth. Unusually, there is a good-size
fore-and-aft single on either side of the companionway.
Each single has dividing curtain, lighting and storage space. Peace
for the parents and privacy for the kids.
Then, preparing to catch up with some sailing boats -- and the
outgoing ferry -- at Colintraive, it's surely time for me to throttle
right back.
''Not necessarily,'' Angus reminds me. ''Look at the wake. And look at
the wash from that displacement boat.''
Sure enough, we're on the plane, displacing a relatively small amount
of sea. The smaller, and slower boat is making waves.
Pass the sailboats, without causing upset, and stop for the ferry. Our
27ft deep-V hull settles down decorously.
Check the surroundings, and we're off. Pause to admire the painted
Maids of Bute to port. Then the 200hp turbo diesel Volvo is asked to get
up and go. If you're in a hurry, top speed is 30 knots.
With contra-rotating propellors, there is increased power and
excellent directional stability. Going backwards, in a straight line, is
a pleasure. Just compare that with some boats you know.
The price of all this luxury living is something in the region of
#75,000. Are people buying? ''Certainly,'' says Angus. ''We've sold
three since February. This is a first-class family boat. You know you
can go where you want, in safety. It is good value for money and it's
great fun, too.''
Around 80% of Euroyachts turnover is in sailing boats, a long-lasting
relationship. With craft as well-turned out as the new Hardy range, it's
easy to see how people can be converted to a motoring life.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
