<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Embarquez-les, Theatre Workshop</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863276</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHAT kind of clowning is this? Nobody gets splatted with custard pies
or drooked with water. That's because this clowning (from France) is
closer to life. It's a sly catalogue of everyday frailties, given a
particular feminine spin, by the five white-faced women who lark about
like overgrown girlies, coveting one another's anything -- it doesn't
matter what, only that she's got it -- and being inventively petty in
the process.
Behind the zany plaits, the red noses, the chirrupings, and
mutterings, and odd apparel, lurks an array of all-too-human types,
whose failings are portrayed with hilarious delicacy and a kind of fresh
innocence that is moving as well as charming and funny.
Embarquez-les is obviously French for ''delicious fun''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000043</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000043</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Just Below The Surface, Gilded Balloon II</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863277</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO solos from the brilliantly fierce and talented Sian Williams,
solos that celebrate resilience, self-knowledge, and a renewed zest for
life.
Circuit Breaker gets another, welcome Fringe showing -- the circus
imagery of Judith Wilkinson's rueful poem of high-flying love is
stunningly captured by Williams's bold use of trapeze. There is
something utterly compelling about the way her tiny frame -- as graceful
and sinuous as a Siamese cat -- conceals such blistering strength.
At times, it's as if some unseen harness was holding her arcing limbs
mid-air. All this, and a spoken delivery of the poem while flying,
poignantly, towards despair in the sawdust.
Coupled with this is Upstart, a cracking display where Christina Hoyos
meets Tina Turner and the result is hot rock flamenco in a slithery,
sexy red rubber mini-skirt. Seriously electric.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Romeo et Juliette, Theatre Workshop, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARK FISHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863278</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ACT Five, Scene Three. The play begins. Romeo and Juliet are about to
die, and in death their love will be made eternal. But in Nada Theatre's
version, the two lovers can't bring themselves to commit that final act
of suicide and, after a hilarious series of failed attempts, choose
instead to go on a fantasy voyage to rediscover their love.
Such a concept could easily end up looking whimsical but, from the
company that brought us Ubu with vegetables, it is deliciously
theatrical. Whether it is the novel and downright quirky inventiveness
of re-enacting the death scene with two bare feet, or the visual poetry
of the sea of bubbles that ends the show, it is a magical production
that more than justifies your expenditure on that French language
refresher course.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>George Dillon's Hamlet, Assembly Rooms, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARK FISHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863279</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AND you thought it was Shakespeare what wrote it. Indeed he did,
though neither in the same order nor with the same disregard to everyone
bar the titular hero. This is a bizarre production that will infuriate
as many people as it inspires. I can't imagine what you'd make of it if
you weren't familiar with the original, story-telling taking second
place to a rigorous, physical showmanship and a cavalier disregard to
making the language understood, even though they make it crystal clear
when they choose to.
Dillon plays Hamlet like he was King Lear's Fool, bellowing one line,
whispering the next, which makes for dazzling speeches but little
variation across the show. If I add that Rosencrantz is played by a
glove-puppet puppy and that the score ranges from Noh-inspired
percussion to Another One Bites the Dust, you'll understand why you can
only go and make up your own mind.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ben Keaton, Assembly Rooms</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863280</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DURING the course of his hypnotic one-man demonstration of life's
propensity to coincidence and happenstance, Ben Keaton requires himself
to become two other people. He begins as a prosaic, poetry-loving booby
who mutates into an accidental tourist-terrorist.
He concludes as a regular bloke with an irregular and awful secret.
Ben also sings, revealing a beguiling voice redolent of David Byrne and
Lyle Lovett. His show is sometimes comic, sometimes chilling. And while
I'm not entirely sure of its philosophical conclusions, I do know that
Ben Keaton is one of the most expressive actors to whom you could
entrust some of your time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nick Revell, Assembly Rooms</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863281</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALONG with many other marvels, Nick Revell has created a keen and
tender elegy for the deathly surrender of his own youthful idealism.
Liberal Psychotic is a wise and subtle monologue about growing up;
becoming more reactionary and cynical; having the honesty to be worried
about one's increasing cynicism, and then becoming even more worried
when you realise that cynical is easier and more profitable.
Liberal Psychotic is confessional and compelling; frank and fiercely
funny, as well as genuinely revelatory. Liberal Psychotic also neatly
Molotovs pomposity, particularly as it relates to politically-flavoured
stand-up comedy of a self-righteous bent. It's insightful, incandescent,
and innately decent . . . just like Nick Revell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Holy Ground, Assembly Rooms, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARK FISHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863282</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is nothing startlingly original about the concept of this
monologue by Dermot Bolger, of Lament for Arthur Cleary fame. He's
certainly not the first to write a one-woman show in which a widow
reflects on a life at the mercy of the whims of a self-absorbed husband.
But what grace, what eloquence, what beautifully controlled command of
story-telling Bolger brings! And, delivered by an unshowy, rooted and
concentrated Mariah Neary, The Holy Ground becomes a work of tremendous
insight, revealing the bitterness, despair and desperation of a loveless
and childless prison of a marriage.
Capturing the tenderness and pride, the frustration and isolation of a
woman lacking the vision, resources or the power to escape her
extinguishing position of subservience, it is a subtly powerful and
absorbing piece of theatre.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mark Little, Assembly Rooms</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863283</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HIS new sticky-up hair gives him a distressing resemblance to Nigel
Kennedy, but thankfully Mark Little is a one-off. Mark's robust
amiability and quick-wittedness allow him to wring laughs ostensibly out
of thin air. He does a lot of apparently aimless barging about, thus
disguising the fact that he's actually training his satirist's gunsights
on a host of contemporary hypocrisies: Damien Hirst's alleged art, the
supposed benefits of Prozac, Quentin Capuccino's macho movie-making, as
well as the political apathy of us lot, his well-meaning leftie
audience, and his own undistinguished thespian past in Neighbours. Best
revelation? ''Today's held-in laughter is the tumour of tomorrow.'' Let
it out for Mark Little, no worries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Doin' It Right, Stepping Stones</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON KERR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863284</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOU'VE got to hand it to singer Suzanne Bonnar: despite the unbearable
heat of her venue, the late starting time of her set, and her
unforgivable, near unrecognisable treatments of various familiar songs,
the audience still whooped, cheered, and begged for more.
More of the lesser-known material like the lovely bossa nova-ish
ballad Wave would not have gone amiss. It worked because Bonnar sounded
natural; she managed to make it her own without causing GBH to its
melody as she had done to some of the standards, particularly her
disastrous opener -- Them There Eyes, less of a song and more of an
exercise in racing to get all the lyrics in before the end of each
phrase.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Some People, Traverse Theatre/Out of the Blue, Pleasance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARK FISHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863285</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF you want to save yourself a couple of hundred on a trip to New
York, you could do worse than check out these two one-man
multi-character shows from the Big Apple.
Surprisingly similar in format, Danny Hoch's Some People and Richard
Hoehler's Out Of The Blue take a handful of character-types from the New
York streets and present them in a series of vignettes, the purpose of
which is less to be funny than to celebrate the act of observation and
eavesdropping.
Both shows have their rewards, but it is Hoch who stands out as the
exceptional talent, taking us deep into the multicultural quagmire where
Spanish meets Polish meets English meets Caribbean meets Pigeon in a
furiously fast barrage of often incomprehensible language. It's hip,
contemporary, alive, often bewilderingly funny and -- like Hoehler's
show -- only wanes when the performer's talent starts to look more
substantial than his material.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rhapsodia in Clown, The Pleasance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863286</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE previous show had overrun by tens of minutes. The divine prospect
of eating something other than a sweaty sandwich was vanishing off the
schedule. I was not in the mood to laugh. Grrrrr!
But laugh I did. I couldn't help myself. Nor could the five other folk
scattered round the theatre. They all laughed, out loud, without the
security blanket of neighbouring ho-ho-hos. To get that kind of
uninhibited response argues quality clowning. Rhapsodia is.
This trio from Spain have a sure understanding of the incongruous, the
eccentric and the plain daft. An operatic diva has her feathers ruffled
by a vacuum cleaner. A dolorous folk singer makes a cake of himself when
he bows. Anything that smacks of pomposity -- including Spanish culture!
-- is gently spoofed. This is affable slapstick, strong on visual and
musical gags that easily skit over the language barrier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Avernal, Hill Street Theatre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863287</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE are in Hell. Hell, you should know, is a place where young women in
body-hugging costumes talk about outrageous sex in the kind of arched
tones usually heard declaiming, ''A-h-and-bag . . .''
The young women are Devils. God and religion are their con tricks on
humanity. We are, by now, most definitely in Hell. We are in that Hades
where bad plays squint and leer and torment their victims. Oh, the agony
as the cast pontificate at ponderous length on their wicked, lascivious
ways. Oh, the pain of watching a girl with clingfilm for a bra writhe in
a sham of sexual depravity. She is Beelzebub, Sex fiend. She is also the
choreographer. She has the same surname as the scriptwriter. Oh, Hell.
Avernal is self-indulgent posturing with a superiority complex. The
damnable thing is -- the company don't seem to know or care. Avoid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Something Rotten, Hill Street Theatre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARK FISHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863288</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS is the kind of play that people like to say the Fringe is all
about. Off-beat, imaginative, rough-round-the-edges, barely half-an-hour
long, and performed by an up-for-anything young transatlantic company.
It tells a Hamlet-like story of a son's attempted revenge on his uncle
for the murder of his father, a revenge made all the more pressing after
the uncle gives the young man's mother a toe-job at the funeral.
So far so straight-forward, but the Atlantic Crossing Theatre Project
turns it into an odd piece of stylised expressionism complete with
circus ringleader, murderous postal workers, and a stream of apparently
real newspaper reports. It's too brief to add up to much, but it's done
in the best of spirits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Big Book for Girls, Assembly Rooms</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARK FISHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863289</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOU know the score. Inter-war girls' public school. Institutionalised
racism, snobbery, and patriarchal British Empire values. A dash of
nascent homosexuality, teenage crushes and midnight feasts. And a load
of gags based on archaic turns of phrase and class-conscious tuck-box
language.
What makes Joe Richards's play such a joy, back in this National
Student Theatre Company production after pulling in the punters on last
year's Fringe, is the brisk and breathless performances, the constantly
inventive direction, and the delightful a cappella arrangements of Nick
Brace's songs.
It's wizard fun and -- just to salve your conscience after so much
inconsequential frippery -- there's even a last-minute moral twist that
powerfully, though rather casually, implicates the British ruling class
in the Holocaust.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Harry Hill, Pleasance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863290</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LAST year, in Pub Internationale, Harry and two assistants explored
the lure of the boozy singalong. Now he's back on his ownsome: Harry
Hill, the one and only king of the recurring non-sequitur! Prince of the
slightly-misheard top-pop hit-single lyric! Absurdist son of Mister
Magoo and Harry Worth! Bloke with a vast shirt-collar and an impressive
repertoire of non-verbal interjections and peculiar hand-gestures!
Harry's new show is called Savlon 2000. It establishes conclusive
links between Mother Teresa, Pulp, Blur, Oasis, Echobelly, Jimmy Savile,
and the aforementioned household antiseptic cream, Savlon. How? By means
beyond rational explanation. Just take my word for it that ''Harry
Hill'' is short for ''Harry Hilarious''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Spencer Finch, Collective Gallery</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CLARE HENRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863291</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE hundred pink pastel circles form a line around all the gallery
rooms, each sheet neatly pinned by its top corner. Every one is a
different shade or tone from peach to flesh, shocking to salmon, rose to
raspberry, coral to cerise and pearl. It's as though a make-up mad
teenager has made a blob with each of her lipsticks. Indeed, the
overwhelming effect here is of conceptual cosmetics rather than art.
The title, Trying to Remember the Colour of Jackie Kennedy's Pillbox
Hat, is, according to the catalogue, exactly what this American is
doing. Memory is paramount but often seen through a haze, a glass
darkly. It's as if the pink is on the tip of his tongue.
Previous projects include paintings of the Vienna ceiling above
Freud's couch and pictures of his studio walls at night. Till Sept 2nd.
Meanwhile the Collective has launced 50,000 copied of its new
bi-monthly gallery guide to Glasgow and Edinburgh. Excellent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bloody Mary and the Virgin Queen, Demarco Institute</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DANIELLE NAGLER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863292</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
392 years dead, two mannequin queens rise from the grave to do battle
for posthumus supremacy. Elizabeth and Mary (not the Scots one) Tudor,
alias Jill Dowse and Kate Joseph, though slightly sidetracked by
sisterly bickering, take advantage of historical hindsight for their mad
dash through their respective lives.
Tones of the twentieth-century Lady T add freshness to some slightly
cliched business, and on the whole the blend of fluorescent lycra with
ancient petticoats works well.
With Punch and the policeman firmly boxed up, Judy finally gets her
say, and more good lines than severed heads fly around in this
production.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lucky break for the scots tourist trade</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KIRSTY SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863293</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
In a bumper season for the Scots tourist industry, Kirsty Scott
explains plans to maintain its optimistic momentum.
IT WAS Wednesday last week that tourism officials in Fort William
experienced something they had not seen since the heady days of the
mid-1980s -- they ran out of accommodation.
A hasty radio appeal brought in enough new beds for the visitors, but
for the officials the glitch was a welcome one. ''It's not the first
time it's happened,'' said Fort William and Lochaber Tourism visitor
services manager, Winnie Dick. ''It happened quite frequently in the
eighties, in the boom years. At that time people had to sleep in their
cars and in their bus shelters. But that had not happened for a good few
years.''
After one of the bleakest years for the tourism industry, early
indications are that the 1995 trade is picking up in some areas of the
country, and while the weather has undoubtedly helped, officials hope it
is not just a reaction to the heatwave, but a real sign of underlying
improvement.
''The sun has helped, but that's not the main factor,'' said Dick.
''Lots of people book in advance. They come to see Scotland. If the sun
is here when they come then that's great.''
In Fort William's case, they believe that a mix of innovative
marketing techniques, a strong push for business at a conference in the
Hague, and the interest piqued by the Hollywood blockbusters Rob Roy and
Braveheart have helped boost the figures so far this season. They've
already counted 28,000 visitors to the town's Cameron Centre last week,
compared to 23,208 last year.
''Basically it's down to good marketing and just perhaps a change in
the fortunes of Britain,'' said Dick. ''The recession is diminishing a
bit and maybe people have a bit more money to spend on holidays. I'd
like to think so.''
Down in the Glasgow area, they've seen a similar upswing but they are
equally keen to play down the effect of the weather.
Greater Glasgow Tourist Board has seen bookings rise by 14% and 15% in
June and July this year compared to last year, with inquiries to the
tourist information centres rising by 4% and 9% respectively over the
same period.
''I think the key thing is that many people will have booked in
advance and the weather is what they get when they get here,'' said GGTB
spokesman Ken Walton. ''There is no doubt that it has to have an effect
on the way people are moving within the area, but I think there are much
more longer-term issues and much more basic issues at work here in terms
of how people are taking breaks.''
Walton said a six-month marketing campaign, extolling the virtues of
the short-break was paying dividends. ''The responses we have been
getting are extremely encouraging and I think it's that kind of focused
activity that's possibly helping to improve things to a great degree.''
Over in Edinburgh, they don't have exact figures yet but all
indications are that with the Tall Ships, the Festival and the Phantom
of the Opera coming in October, it will be a healthy season. They have
already had a problem with accommodation and expect similar No Vacancy
signs to go up in September as well.
''Business has definitely improved on last year and has been good
since the Tall Ships,'' said tourism spokesman Gordon McCulloch. ''In
Edinburgh the percentages have gone up every year and it looks like they
are going to go up again this year.''
Again, McCulloch was reluctant to give the heatwave too much credit.
''I think it's a drip, drip effect on so many fronts. We've done a lot
of press trips and word of mouth is going out about how good it is and
not just Edinburgh, it's Scotland as a whole. It's not something that
you can always put your finger on but you just hope you are doing
something right.''
In Dundee, however, tourism officials say bookings are down on last
year but there appears to be an increase in the number of visitors to
the town.
The Scottish Tourist Board, meanwhile, launched a new publicity
offensive yesterday to extend the tourist season and will release
figures for the first six months of this year later in the month.
Spokesman Graham Birse said that the first three months of 1995 were
looking healthy for Scotland as a whole, although some areas, including
the Highlands had not performed so well.
They were encouraged by the signals, but warned against predictions of
a bumper year. ''1994 was a pretty bad year and consequently we would
want to see an improvement on 1994 whatever the weather,'' he said. ''We
would like to see it coming off the bottom as it were.
''There is no doubt that the arrangements put into place last year
have taken effect this year in terms of more resources being made
available from the Scottish Office for marketing, and the launch of
special niche marketing programmes.
''What we want to try and get away from, however, is the boom and bust
and peaks and troughs. What we are really looking for is consistent
long-term growth; for '95 to be better than '94 and for '96 to be better
than '95.''
However, niche marketing and focused campaigns notwithstanding, the
STB is still willing to give credit where credit is due.
''We have to be quite frank,'' said Birse.''The weather is a boost.
It's a shot in the arm for a season which had already begun to look
good.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000060</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000060</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pitfalls of the power game</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICHOLAS BUDGEN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863294</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nicholas Budgen believes individual agendas are behind the Labour
Party's bickering.
MAKE no mistake there is a crisis in the Labour Party. I know this
because I can recognise the similarities between my party and the Labour
Party, and I can see how misunderstandings arise.
It starts from the beginning. Because we have an unwritten
constitution, it is easy to misjudge where power at any one time lies.
The newspapers assume that the leader of a party is all powerful. When
first an idea or a policy is put forward, it has to be done with energy
and self-confidence.
The leader also has the assistance of a body of spin-doctors and
advisers who suggest the way in which the subject may be commented upon.
Only the more sceptical of scribes will wonder what opposition will come
from the leader's own party.
The old election meeting, in which you questioned your personal
candidate, is dead. Now the local candidate is often seen as no more
than a potential minor employee of the party leader. ''Don't worry
Budgen. We're voting for Major on Thursday.''
Well it's all coming apart for Mr Blair. I'm not saying that we, the
Tories, will win. That is, as yet, uncertain.
Recently Blair has been taught two lessons about politics which no
leader should forget. You cannot treat Parliament and your ordinary
party workers with contempt and get away with it forever.
Let us remember that a Government is responsible to Parliament and not
for Parliament. The Labour Party has an understandable hunger for power.
Every party has its mixture of characters. There are the careerists.
There are the subservient party men. There are the administrators. Such
men would be No 2 in the Ministry of Drains for any government at any
time. There's not much difference between a cautious conventional Tory
Attorney General and an equally cautious and conventional Labour
Attorney General.
So there have always been plenty of sound men of business in every
party. In recent years the Tory Party has been taken over by the career
politicians. The career politician does not resign, if at all, until at
or near the ceiling of promotion. The career politician sees politics as
terms of office and not in terms of ideas.
It is now plain that Blair is a Tory not only in his ideas, but also
in his attitudes. He aspires to be a career politician and is prepared
to support any views that lead him towards office.
What is now emerging is that some people in the Labour Parliamentary
Party want power but power for its own sake. They want the salary and
the Rover all right, but they want them in order to support, as they
would put it, the needs of the disadvantaged and the dispossessed.
The Labour Parliamentary Party are beginning to show that they are
more interested in ideas than in gaining power. This means trouble for
the future.
So as we move towards the General Election I suggest that it would be
as well to look at the views of individual candidates as well as the
party leaders. There are Parliamentary problems ahead for Blair. Of
course there will be sticks and carrots to manage the Labour Party. Some
councillors will be bought off with a job on a quango. Others will be
frightened by the threat of being suspended from the Labour Party.
But never forget politics is, most of all, a voluntary activity for
people who feel strongly about how their country should be governed.
The core of the Labour Party is the people who trudge round the
streets knocking on doors and collecting small subscriptions without the
hope of reward or patronage.
The genuine voluntary worker in the Labour Party remains committed to
the interests of the poor and the working-class and he believes in
improvememt through state expenditure of other people's money.
The Labour Party will, in former Dagenham MP Bryan Gould's words, only
be united in a shared ideology and vision. So I say talk to the Labour
man in your street in Glasgow. He is more likely to tell you what a
Labour Government will be like than will that nice Mr Blair.
* Nicholas Budgen is Conservative MP for Wolverhampton South West.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Opening minds to another side of American history</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALLAN LAING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863295</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Allan Laing meets the director of an acutely observed new film which
portrays the cynicism of the FBI's clandestine attempts to neutralise
the Black Panther movement of the sixties.
ACONTROVERSIAL new film by black actor and director Mario Van Peebles
claims that J. Edgar Hoover enlisted the help of the Mafia to flood
America's black ghettos with heroin in the late 1960s.
The paranoid and racist FBI director, fearing that the activities of
the Black Panther movement could actually spark off a revolution,
believed that the availability of drugs would serve to pacify a
troublesome Afro-American population.
Because of his unwillingness to compromise his polemical storyline,
Van Peebles was shunned by the Hollywood studio establishment. The men
with the fat cigars and pink faces, though initially keen on the idea,
insisted that he introduce a major role for a white actor, ''like Tom
Cruise or Brad Pitt''. He refused.
After nine years of attempting in vain to raise US finance for the
project Van Peebles, who is one of the most successful of Hollywood's
new breed of black directors with movies like Free Jack City and Posse
to his credit, had to turn to Europe for his budget. The money was
eventually provided by the UK-based Working Title and the European
entertainment conglomerate Polygram.
The result is Panther, at once a taut political thriller and a
powerful film about the evolution of the Black Panther movement and its
effects upon the American nation. It was shown this week at the Drambuie
Edinburgh Film Festival and will go on general release later this year.
The movie was directed by Van Peebles and written and co-produced by
his father, Melvin, a distinguished film-maker in his own right and the
man who is recognised as the godfather of black cinema in America.
The Black Panther Party for Self Defence was formed in Oakland,
California, in 1966 by two angry young men, Bobby Seale and Huey Newton,
as a response to the harassment and violence suffered by the black
community at the hands of the local police. Under its black power
banner, it grew to become a potent force for the advancement of civil
rights. Armed and fully prepared to counter violence with violence, its
members were a darker, more sinister, counterpoint to Martin Luther
King's peace movement.
If there is one abiding pictorial memory of the Panthers then it is
American athletes Tommie Smith and John Carlos delivering, live on
television across the world, the clenched-fist black power salute after
winning medals in the 1968 Olympics in Mexico City. The white
establishment feared and loathed the Panthers' radical policies and
their perceived revolutionary stance. Almost 30 years later, the
movement is still regarded by many Americans as a force which threatened
to destroy the very fabric of the white-dominated society.
Panther, arguably the most significant black movie in many years, has
been criticised in America for being historically inaccurate. It is
unapologetically one-sided, certainly. The entire Oakland police force
is branded as brutal and racist. Indeed, almost every white character in
the film is portrayed as brutal and racist. It stars black actors Kadeem
Hardison and Bokeem Woodbine and also features Joe Don Baker, Richard
Dysart, M. Emmet Walsh, Robert Culp, and Dick Gregory.
Van Peebles, in Edinburgh with his father to publicise the film, said:
''When people are medicated, they don't cause trouble. The FBI realised
that. Hoover didn't really employ the Mafia, he just instructed the
local police authorities to leave them alone; don't police certain
areas. Of course, he categorically denied the existence of the Mafia
because they were blackmailing him over his homosexuality.''
For Van Peebles there are two kinds of history. There is popular
history and then there's unpopular history. ''Popular history tends to
be those kinds of things which make us feel a little better. Take
Schindler's List; the Nazis did some terrible things and it makes us
feel warm and tickly when we see this good guy helping Jews.
''But we don't see films about the way refugee Jews, fleeing from
Germany, were turned away from America -- and they were -- because that
wouldn't make us feel all warm and tickly. The history books are always
written by the winners. That's why the heavyweight champion of the world
might be Ali or Tyson but Hollywood makes him look like Rocky.
''And that's why they asked me to find a role for Tom Cruise or Brad
Pitt as a nice white student who helps the Panthers. That sounds like a
weird idea but, when you think about it, it's no weirder than getting
Kevin Costner to come along and help the native Americans in Dances With
Wolves. Again, this nice white guy makes us feel all warm and tickly,''
he explained.
Van Peebles was clearly grateful for the finance provided by Europe
but he added: ''The thing is that, when you're in Europe you can stand
back and look at someone else's dirty shirts.''
Melvin Van Peebles, who based his screenplay on his novel of the same
name, claims that Hoover's plan backfired on him and, indirectly, it may
have led to America's current drugs problems.
''The drugs were supposed to be contained in these problem areas but,
thanks to their own racial prejudices, they overlooked the fact that
black culture is the one which is most emulated throughout the world. So
the drug problem overflowed and the Mafia eventually lost control of
it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Military coup</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863296</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SAO TOME: Rebel military officers stormed the presidential palace in
the western African island nation and seized President Miguel Trovoada
in a bloodless coup. Forces led by young, Cuban-trained officers said a
new, military-led government will now rule the twin island country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Charges fears</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863297</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LAGOS: Bill Clinton and John Major have telephoned Nigeria's military
ruler to express concern over the fate of 40 people convicted on coup
plot charges, their aides said on Tuesday. The United States considered
the charges to be ''without merit and we're very concerned about the
condition of those who are currently being held'', White House spokesman
Mike McCurry said in Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Protesters held</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863298</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BEIJING: Police led away leaders of Greenpeace in Tiananmen Square
yesterday seconds after they unfurled banners demanding China end its
nuclear tests. The protest was timed to coincide with rumoured plans
that China will hold a test in the next seven days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cancer findings</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863299</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WASHINGTON: Scientists reported they have been able to detect genetic
abnormalities at the earliest stages of precancerous changes in the
lungs. The findings could lead to ways of identifying people at risk for
lung cancer and perhaps to preventive therapies. Dr Yosuke Kishimoso and
associates at the University of Texas Southwestern Medical Centre in
Dallas extracted genetic material from precancerous areas of patients
with non-small-cell lung cancer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rubble barney</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863300</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MOLDOVA: A man blew up his house in the former Soviet republic rather
than see his ex-wife recieve it as part of a divorce settlement. The
man, who had been drinking vodka after a row with his wife, turned on
the gas in the kitchen and lit a match. He emerged from the debris
bruised but without serious injury.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Not guilty pleas</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863301</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OKLAHOMA CITY: Timothy McVeigh and Terry Nichols pled not guilty
yesterday to last April's Oklahoma City bombing. They were indicted last
week on 11 counts related to the April 19 attack that killed 167 people.
McVeigh, 27, and Nichols, 40, face the death penalty if convicted. A
third suspect, Michael Fortier, 26, pled guilty last Thursday to aiding
a bombing plot and is awaiting sentencing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000068</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000068</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Aids child attacked</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863302</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BUCHAREST: Romanian villagers stoned an eight-year-old Aids victim and
her family and tried to drive them from their home yesterday. The girl
had been diagnosed when she returned to her parents from an orphanage in
June.
Dr Constantin Barabolski told Reuters from the north-eastern city of
Iasi that the girl's mother has now asked for her daughter to be allowed
back to the orphanage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>150 feared drowned</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>FERRIES,BANGLADESH,SHIPPING ACCIDENTS,</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863303</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BANGLADESH: Nearly 150 people were feared drowned yesterday after a
ferry capsized during a rainstorm, police said.
The ferry, the Basanti, went down in the Chitra river, 10 miles from
the town of Jessore.
''So far no casualties have been found and local officials believe
many onboard the Basanti could have swum ashore,'' a police spokesman
said.
Witnesses said the ferry was heavily loaded with passengers and goods.
''It listed on one side immediately after being caught in the storm
and sank in minutes,'' one said.--Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863304</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BRITON kidnapped in Colombia in June has been found dead, the
Foreign Office said yesterday.
Mr Trevor Catton, who was a resident of Colombia, South America, is
believed to have been killed by his captors.
The Foreign Office said the kidnappers were understood to be criminals
with no political motive.
A spokesman said: ''Mr Catton's family had been dealing with the
kidnapping direct.
''Since the kidnapping our embassy in Bogota have maintained close
contact with Mr Catton's family and the relevant Colombian authorities.
''We condemn the killing of a British citizen and express revulsion at
this act of violence. Responsibility for this wicked act rests with the
kidnappers and no one else.''
The Foreign Office was unable to supply Mr Catton's age, occupation,
any details on the cause of death or details of his family.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chechens lay down arms</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863305</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GROZNY: Facing threats of renewed war from the Kremlin, Chechen rebels
yesterday agreed to start laying down at least some of their guns.
If the disarmament takes place as scheduled today, it will be the
first step toward implementing a military accord signed on July 30.
The peace pact calls for Russia to withdraw some of its troops in the
breakaway republic and for the Chechens to give up their weapons.
Neither has so far taken place so far.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Action against crews in Iraq shoot-down</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863306</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington
THE Air Force announced today it has grounded two fighter pilots and
three radar plane officers and rebuked two generals involved in the
accidental 1994 shooting-down of two US helicopters which killed 26
people in Iraq.
General Ronald Fogleman, Air Force chief of staff, said that besides
the groundings of the junior officers, he has also given them and the
two generals in charge of the operation performance-failure letters.
Other defence officials said those letters will likely end their
careers.
The episode in which 16 Americans and 11 officials from allied
countries lost their lives, took place over northern Iraq on April 14,
1995.
The two F-15 pilots patrolling a no-fly zone set up to protect Iraqi
Kurds after the 1991 Gulf War misidentified a pair of US Blackhawk
helicopters as Iraqi craft and shot them down, killing all on board.
The other officers punished were aboard a radar control plane running
air operations. They failed to detect the mistake and warn the attackers
away from their target.
''Lives were lost,'' Fogleman said in a videotaped message to all Air
Force members. ''Our people did not meet Air Force standards. Now we are
holding all involved accountable.''
Defence Secretary William Perry called an Air Force report on the
actions the first response to an order for a review of shootdown
punishments.
He said he and Deputy Defence Secretary John White are waiting for
reports from the Army and Joint Chiefs of Staff and will ''decide if
additional measures are necessary''.
The new Air Force punishments follow criticism from relatives of those
killed and members of Congress who felt that the Air Force let those
involved get away with what had amounted to wrist-slaps.
Bitter relatives had urged Congress to investigate why only one
officer was court-martialled.Captain James Wang, was acquitted in June.
Wang, a crew chief on the Airborne Warning and Control Systems command
plane, accused the Air Force of making him a scapegoat rather than
taking action to prevent such accidents from recurring.
Wang was among the officers whose grounding was announced today.The
others were radar-plane officers Joseph Halcli and Ricky Wilson, fighter
pilots Lieutenant Colonel Randy May and Captain Eric Wickson.
Senior officers receiving rebukes are Brigadier Generals Jeffrey
Pilkington and Curtis Emery.--Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Execution deadline passes in silence as India stands firm over Kashmiri prisoners. Agony wait for hostage families</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863307</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE fate of two British hostages, held in India by extremist
guerrillas who have already beheaded a fellow captive, remained
uncertain last night as a deadline threatening their execution expired.
Indian authorities were still refusing to free 15 jailed comrades of
the Al-Faran Kashmiri separatists who are holding Britons Paul Wells and
Keith Mangan, an American and a German.
A fifth hostage, Norwegian Hans Ostroe, was found decapitated two days
ago, with a note from the guerillas threatening to execute the other
captives unless their demands were met by today.
The Indian Government has considered mounting a rescue raid but warned
it would put the hostages' lives at risk.
Mr Tim Devlin spoke for Keith Mangan's parents Charles and Mavis
Mangan when he said that the family supported any moves by Indian
authorities to release the hostages by force.
''We had a long conversation about it and the view they take now is
that they would rather something was done, even though they know it is
enormously risky,'' said Mr Devlin.
He said they were shocked and horrified at Mr Ostroe's barbaric
murder.
''Up until this gruesome discovery, they had rather hoped that this
was a benign group seeking publicity,'' said Stockton South Tory MP Mr
Devlin.
''But they are coping remarkably well considering. They are hoping
that something will turn up and they are trying to keep their spirits
up.''
The father of Paul Wells also spoke of the agonising wait for news.
''We are coping as well as we can, basically. I just want those four
chaps out of there quickly and as safely as possible,'' said Bob Wells,
50, who works for Debenhams.
He told the Lancashire Evening Telegraph it was time for a rescue
operation.
''You can't really sit back. I think it's getting so dangerous up
there now.''
He said his son was a ''stable chap''.
''He used to have quite a temper when he was a young teenager, but he
is now quite a calm character.
''I think he can ride things out quite easily and adapt to situations
quite quickly.
''But my fear is that, if he knows what happened to Hans Ostroe . . .
I shudder to think what he's thinking about.''
Meanwhile, Kashmiris expressed their outrage at the execution by
planning a strike for tomorrow, claiming the killing ''violates the
Kashmiri spirit''.
Mr Mangan, 34, an electrical contractor from Middlesbrough, Cleveland,
and Mr Wells, 23, a photography student from Blackburn, Lancashire, were
abducted at gunpoint six weeks ago from their camp 60 miles east of the
Kashmiri capital Srinagar.
The kidnappers claim Mr Mangan is in a critical condition after a gun
battle with soldiers, although the Indian authorities deny it took place
and suggest a photo of him in bloody bandages may be a hoax.
Indian officials said they had the support of the three Western
nations whose citizens were being held captive in remaining firmly
opposed to any deal with the militants.
''The diplomats have agreed with our strategy of negotiating rather
than releasing any militants,'' a spokesman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Simpson mistrial threat</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863308</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Los Angeles
JUDGE Lance Ito said today he may have to declare a mistrial in the O.
J. Simpson double murder case if prosecutors call his wife, a Los
Angeles police captain, to testify.
The threat that the seven-month-long trial could collapse came after
the defence argued they need to introduce audio tapes in which former
police detective Mark Fuhrman allegedly made disparaging remarks about
Ito's wife.
''Just when you thought things couldn't get any crazier,'' Ito said,
inviting arguments from attorneys on what he saw as a conflict of
interest.
Prosecutor Marcia Clark told Ito on Monday she might call his wife to
testify and Ito replied today if that happened, he would have to
disqualify himself from the case, causing an automatic mistrial.--Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wind of change swept away by 100mph gusts</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863309</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
St George
BERMUDA'S referendum on independence from Britain, planned for today,
was postponed as Hurricane Felix lashed the islands with high winds and
rain.
The international airport was shut and no government offices opened.
The referendum is to take place tomorrow.
Cabinet Secretary Leo Mills announced the delay in the vote in a radio
broadcast. He said it was ''considered unwise to expose voters to danger
from the weather''.
The islands were pounded by heavy rains and 100mph gusts that sent
huge waves crashing into beaches. No deaths or injuries were reported
but two-thirds of Bermuda's homes were left without power and the
second-largest town, St George, was cut off for hours by damage to the
1000-yard causeway connecting it to the mainland.
The independence referendum will be the first in the history of
Bermuda, Britain's oldest colony. The chain of 138 islands and islets
came under the British crown in 1684 and achieved internal
self-government in 1968.
Thousands of residents and tourists were ordered to evacuate two North
Carolina islands today as the hurricane headed towards the US mainland.
Pounding surf thundered along the East Coast as far north as Cape Cod
and Maine. Three people had died in the surf since the weekend.
The unusually wide storm was moving toward the west-northwest at about
14mph. It was feared that it could hit the Outer Banks, a chain of
coastal islands, around sunrise tomorrow, with the eye making landfall
around sundown, said Steve Harned of the National Weather Service in
Raleigh.
The hurricane warning area extended from South Carolina to northern
Virginia. A hurricane watch -- a less severe form of advisory than a
warning -- was in effect for coastal areas of South Carolina, Maryland,
and Delaware on either side of the warning area.
The storm was packing wind blowing at a steady 80mph and
hurricane-force wind extended up to 140 miles out from the centre, the
National Weather Service said. Tropical storm-force wind extended up to
290 miles out.
Residents and visitors on North Carolina's coastal Ocracoke and
Hatteras islands, part of the Outer Banks chain, were ordered to
evacuate this morning. As early as yesterday, water had washed over
Hatteras' main highway at Rodanthe at high tide.--Reuter
''By law, we cannot physically force anyone to leave,'' Dare County
spokesman Charlie Hartig said. ''We hope the word 'mandatory' connotes a
certain severity to what we're talking about.''
In Virginia, navy warships from submarines to aircraft carriers began
streaming out of the Norfolk Naval Base in Virginia to ride out the
hurricane at sea and avoid being battered into piers and each other.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tests confirmed listeria in cheese, court told</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863310</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE court battle over the gourmet Lanark Blue cheese yesterday heard
evidence from a biologist who carried out tests on batches suspected of
being contaminated with listeria.
A food hygiene expert from the Scottish Agricultural College in
Ayrshire gave detailed evidence of the nature of the tests involved,
which highlighted a high level of listeria in some batches of the
cheese.
Clydesdale District Council is bidding to have 44 batches of producer
Humphrey Errington's cheese, worth #27,000, destroyed and dumped in a
landfill site.
Several separate tests were carried out on 50 batches of the cheese in
February at the SAC lab, the court heard.
The results and test procedures were made available to a food expert
who was representing Mr Errington.
Mr Stephen Crawford, 38, a specialist in microbiology at the college,
said: ''We did not need to divulge our methods.
''But we decided it was in everybody's interests to show the results
to a representative of Mr Errington.''
Mr Crawford said Mr Errington's expert representative agreed with the
results of the tests which showed the presence of, in some cases, high
levels of listeria monocytogenes.
The tests were carried out after samples from all batches of the
cheese were individually bagged, sealed, and numbered to prevent
cross-contamination.
Clinical tests revealed the listeria, results which were later
confirmed by carrying out controlled checks.
Further tests were done in less clinical conditions -- the listeria
was not isolated and had to compete with other organisms for growth on
plates.
Mr Crawford said a blue-grey sheen developed, indicating the presence
of listeria.
He told Clydesdale's QC, Mr Neil Brailsford, that an extra test had
been carried out, introducing the organism into horse blood.
''The organism has the ability to break down blood,'' Mr Crawford
said. ''The bacterial colony will grow while the blood there will break
down and form a clear area.''
Mr Brailsford: ''The bacteria has destroyed the blood cells, in crude
terms?''
Mr Crawford: ''Yes.'' He added that, in his opinion, 37 samples showed
listeria, 14 of which were of a ''pure type''.
On the validity of the results of the 14 samples, Mr Crawford said:
''If I was a betting man, I would put a year's wages on it.''
Of the other ''suspect batches'' he said: ''I would put an each-way
bet on it.''
Mr Errington, 50, who produces the cheese in Dunsyre, Lanarkshire,
claims the type of listeria found is not harmful.
The batches of cheese tested are still in cold storage at his Dunsyre
factory farm.
The hearing, before Sheriff John Douglas Allan, continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000077</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000077</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Detergent war forces Hickson to cut payout</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863311</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HICKSON International is still bearing the scars of the recent
detergent war and the company said yesterday it has decided to cut the
half-time dividend from 2.85p to 2p a share. This follows the reduction
in the previous year's final payment in March by 3p to 2.15p as the
first blow from the loss of a Unilever contract was felt.
The company made a manganese catalyst used in Persil Power which was
hard hit in the public relations war waged by arch rival Procter &amp;
Gamble. The contract was worth more than #8m a year in profit.
In the first six months, Hickson, whose chairman is James Hann,
formerly of Scottish Nuclear, saw pre-tax profits plunge by #6m to #6.1m
on overall turnover little changed at #207m. But fine chemical sales
were well down, not only because of the Unilever contract but also
because of a major fire in 1993 which has still to be made good.
Detergent manufacturers have also been slower than expected to
introduce their high-power compact detergents which need Hickson's
unique technology.
Timber protection saw a sales gain but the combination of higher raw
material prices and a sluggish US construction industry saw divisional
profits fall back.
Mr Hann is encouraging shareholders by saying he anticipates a
stronger second-half performance. The shares responded by easing 3p to
115p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hanson on target as profits rise 22%</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863312</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HANSON'S share price was little changed at 216p as the conglomerate,
which just over two weeks ago made an agreed #2500m cash bid for REC
Eastern Group, sailed in with third-quarter operating profits well
within market projections.
At the pre-tax level, they fell 11% to #264m, lower than expected
because exceptional charges of #72m in the quarter for the USI demerger
were higher than anticipated by analysts.
But, after stripping out exceptionals, they emerge at around #336m, up
from #297m, which compares with a market range of between #290m and as
high as #350m. Ahead of exceptionals and interest, operating profits
rose by 22% from #306m to #372m. Overall operating profits for the nine
months are up from #659m to #1034m. The quarterly dividend is unchanged
at 3p.
Chairman Lord Hanson immediately struck a positive note on the bid for
Eastern, the benefits of which some analysts regard as questionable on
the grounds that the company is paying too much, growth prospects are
modest, and cash flow benefits appear minimal. Added to this, of course,
there are also political and regulatory risks to the income.
However, Lord Hanson said it would bring in a new major business,
adding: ''We expect this to be earnings enhancing immediately with
considerable potential for growth outside its regulated electricity
distribution.''
The company also indicated it would go ahead with the bid even if
there was a monopolies referral for the whole of the electricity sector,
though clearly it feels there are no competition grounds for an Eastern
referral.
So far as Hanson's profits are concerned, the group's core operations
spanning chemicals, minerals, and tobacco were ''performing in line with
expectations''.
The figures were spearheaded by the group's Quantum Chemical Unit
which rose well ahead of the previous year. Most of the other businesses
also contributed useful growth with SCM Chemicals, tobacco, aggregates,
material handling, and coal all up. On the downwside, as indicated at
the half-year, propane and forest products showed falls, the former due
to mild winter weather and the latter because of lower lumber prices.
Corporate development director Chris Collins said that earlier in the
year Hanson was comparing recovery with recession but now it was
comparing recovery with recovery.
However, at their present level, the shares are only a few pence above
their low for the year and, indeed, their 1995 high stands only at 253p.
Hanson may have its appeal as an income stock on a yield of 7%, but it
has clearly been under-performing for some time. And there seems to be
little market enthusiasm for it now.
The proposed takeover of Eastern Group has certainly not lit up the
market with enthusiasm, and yesterday's nine-month figures clearly did
not inspire much enthusiasm with analysts still generally downbeat about
the likely progress of the shares in the short term.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Laporte buys German firm for #35.6m</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863313</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITISH speciality chemicals company Laporte is buying 95.6% of the
shares of Chemische Werke Brockhues for #35.6m.
Laporte said the purchase would expand its pigments business.
Brockhues, through patented technology, is the world leader in the
manufacture of Granufin iron oxide pigment granules.
Payment for the shares will be made in three instalments between
September and June next year, with the outstanding 4.4% of the shares
remaining in public ownership.
For the year ended September 1994, Brockhues reported operating
profits of #5.5m on sales of #29.3m.
Laporte said senior management of Brockhues intended to stay with the
company after transfer of ownership. -- Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shareholders are asked to provide #117m</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863314</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHNSON Matthey yesterday asked shareholders to stump up #117.4m to
finance a major US acquisition.
It is buying Advance Circuits in a #106.4m deal. ACI is a leading
supplier of hi-tech printed circuit boards to the electronics industry.
''The acquisition of ACI will extend the product range of Johnson
Matthey's electronic materials business and will also provide an
attractive opportunity to achieve a leading position in the emerging
markets for plastic laminate packaging,'' the group said.
The vehicle catalytic converter specialist is offering investors one
new share for every eight already held at 500p each to raise the money
for the acquisition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>De Beers and Russians face gem price war</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863315</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is increasing speculation that a diamond price war could break
out between De Beers and Russia in a market over-supplied with small
uncut stones.
If a conflict does break out, it is not expected to bring down the
price of a ring because the retail mark-up is so substantial.
Last month, De Beers reduced the price paid by its Central Selling
Organisation subsidiary by up to 15% for small diamonds. But it also
increased those on larger stones by a small amount.
The problem is that while Russia has contracted to supply 26% of all
CSO purchases amounting to about $1100m annually, it is selling a
similar amount outside the CSO which traditionally has run the industry
though the world's best organised international cartel, accounting until
very recently for about 85% of all primary diamond production.
Uncertainty as to whether the Russians will renew their five-year
marketing contract at the year end has depressed prices.
A meeting has been scheduled between De Beers chairman Julian
Ogilvie-Thompson and the Russians for next month. That could well be a
tense affair as the Russians are reportedly angry about De Beer's
price-cutting while believing that the original terms were too
favourable to the purchaser.
That is a totally new phenomenon in the industry as De Beers' policy
has always been to support rough diamond prices in difficult times.
The increase in prices for better quality stones will benefit
primarily De Beers own production in South Africa and its associates in
Botswana and Namibia which produce a higher proportion of these
categories than all other mines.
In the first six months, De Beers raised pre-tax profits by 11% to
$497m (#318m) on sales 2% down at $2540m. Profits were helped by De
Beers own production which is higher margin being supplied to meet a
shortfall from other producers although that position is expected to
reverse in the current six months.
The interim dividend has been held at 25.6c (16.4p). De Beers shares
firmed 18p to 1606p.
</TEXT>
