<HEADLINE>Alpha loses bite of BA apple</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863316</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JUST a week after Alpha Airports announced the $122m (#75.8m) proposed
acquisition of the DynAir airport services company in the US, it had to
reveal yesterday that British Airways will not be renewing its flight
services contract with Alpha at New York's JFK Airport.
The contract, which expires on September 30, was worth around #7.5m
annually, compared with total flight services sales for the group of
#220m. As a result of the BA decision, Alpha now fears its US operations
will not be profitable this financial year.
JFK has consistently been a problem for Alpha with the operations
there having lost #400,000 in the past financial year, partly because
the kitchens were too small. In April, chief executive Paul Harrison
said the problems had been resolved.
There is some consolation in that it has been recently awarded
contracts at JFK with KLM and VASP. And it continues to service BA at
all UK airports except Heathrow.
The DynAir acquisition, which is being partially funded through a
placing and open offer on the basis of one new share at 126p for every
nine held, will give Alpha experience of services such as baggage
handling and loading, de-icing and re-fuelling.
Longer term, while DynAir is largely Americas based, it will be able
to tender for European airport work once de-regulation takes effect.
The move will be earnings enhancing immediately and make a substantial
contribution in 1996, boosting income per share by perhaps 10%.
The shares reacted to the BA news by falling 7p to 142p.
</TEXT>
