<HEADLINE>Sterling rises on back of dollar as Fed action pushes US currency higher. Pound makes sharp gains against mark</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E DUNDAS, CHIEF FINANCIAL EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863317</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STERLING has posted its highest level against the German mark since
early March after rising sharply yesterday on the back of a rampaging
dollar.
Wave after wave of intervention by the US Federal Reserve, operating
on both sides of the Atlantic, the Bundesbank, the Bank of Japan, and
the Swiss National Bank drove the dollar sharply higher against the
German mark and the Japanese yen.
Earlier, the dollar had been boosted in Far Eastern trading by
official figures showing an unexpectedly large fall in Japan's
customs-cleared trade surplus in July.
The Bundesbank's willingness to sell marks and buys dollars was the
crucial factor in boosting market confidence. It was the first time that
the US, German, and Japanese central banks had engaged in concerted
intervention in support of the dollar since May 31.
The difference was that this time the central banks were trying to
push the dollar in the same direction as the market was taking it,
whereas in May they were attempting to buck the trend.
The pound joined in the fun and gained 3.76 pfennigs to DM 2.2952, its
highest closing level since March 3, while losing 1.79 cents to $1.5556.
Sterling has staged a significant recovery since it hit an all-time
low in May just after the Chancellor of the Exchequer, Kenneth Clarke,
and the Governor of the Bank of England, Eddie George, first fell out
over interest rates.
But its international value as measured by its trade weighted index,
which rose yesterday from 84.4 to 85.0, is still 4% below its level at
the end of last year. On May 9, the day after the bank holiday weekend,
sterling plumbed the depths with the index closing at 82.7. At that
point, the pound had lost 6.6% of its international value in a little
over four months.
Last night, James Capel's Adam Cole said: ''We are not far from the
point when the Bank of England would say we had reversed most of its
fall and a rise in rates would not be needed.''
The pound's fall from grace earlier in the year has been the major
factor behind repeated Bank of England calls for higher rates. The Old
Lady of Threadneedle Street was also concerned about the pace of
economic activity, but this has subsided to a near sustainable rate.
The inflationary implications of a weak pound were evident in Monday's
producer price figures for July, which showed core factory gate price
inflation at 5%, its highest level since May 1991.
However, a further recovery in the pound, which would diminish
inflationary fears, is dependent on the dollar continuing to make
headway on hard currencies such as the mark, the yen, and the Swiss
franc.
Currency dealers were taken aback yesterday by the extent of the
dollar's gains of about three yen and four pfennigs. It ended European
trading at DM1.4730 and 96.75 yen with many Continental centres closed
for the Assumption Day holiday.
Bulls of the dollar, which has been recovering steadily since the
Japanese government announced a package of measures to encourage
institutional investors to invest abroad, are speculating that it will
quickly advance to DM1.50 and 100 yen.
The catalyst for yesterday's drama on the foreign exchange markets was
a drop in Japan's politically sensitive trade surplus to $9430m in July
from $12.25bn in the same month a year ago. The surplus with the US
shrank to $3870m from $5620m a year earlier.
The figures showed that the strength of the yen was eating into
Japan's exports, especially to the US, and the trend is expected to
continue.
Japan's trade figures are posted in dollars but, if the figures are
translated into yen, it has been evident that the surplus has been in
decline for some time. The recovery in the dollar will accentuate this
trend.
</TEXT>
