<HEADLINE>Hitting the bottle to dam the sea of silver</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARA VILLIERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863318</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MY head's a mess. Not metaphorically I hasten to add. No sirree, none
of that gestalt-therapy, narcissistic, self-obsessive, navel-gazing,
namby-pamby wanky Yankee nonsense for me. I'm just a straightforward
Scot with the usual hangs-ups, ones I'm quite content to leave well
alone -- ye gods, who knows what demons could be unleashed otherwise.
No, when I say my head's a mess I mean it quite literally; I suspect
my roots are showing. Okay, not exactly a heart-stopping,
hold-the-front-page-guys kind of crisis, but certainly a predicament
which plunges me into a regular philosophical dilemma; when my grey
matter wrestles with the grey matter I am forced to face up to the
hideous monster of my personal vanity and, worse, oh, much worse,
confront a stiffled terror of mortality.
The merest glimpse of grey sparks off a chain of association and a
nightmare parade of images which ultimately conclude in a worm-ridden
casket. Like I said, the usual hang-ups.
Best to keep thoughts of imminent decay at bay by attempting to dam
the sea of silver. Sure I think grey hair is like, really dignified. In
fact it can be cool.
It's just that it doesn't quite fit in with my image, viz desperately
clinging on to any semblance of youth. Each time I ponder whether to dye
or not to dye I decide that it's time to grow old gracefully. Then I
panic and take the cowardly Clairol way out.
There's no shame in it. Anyone who uses as much slap as I do is not
going to get her Janet Reger's in a twist over admitting to interfering
with what God intended. However, while it's deemed perfectly acceptable
for women to hit the bottle, men tend to be more coy about colourants.
Thus, a whole culture has evolved around conferring cool on the
grey-haired man, invariably referred to as ''distinguished.'' And women,
charitably, find him sexy. Men who succumb to the salt-and-pepper peril
have the examples of the greying Richard Gere, Jack Nicholson, and erm,
Philip Schofield.
Few men feel pressurised into covering up the grey -- although I
suspect that this is because they're usually pathetically grateful that
they have any locks left The spectre of being a slaphead is far scarier.
But I also reckon it's because men, who have only just mastered the
art of moisturising, would be defeated by the step-by-step procedures of
the home colourant kit, simple though they are. It all looks too
suspiciously fiddly and girlie for them. They haven't evolved
sufficiently to overcome successfully the first obstacle -- putting on
the little plastic gloves.
You doubt me? Have you ever seen a hospital drama where a doctor put
on his own surgical gloves without nurse's help? Have you ever seen a
chap popping on a pair of Marigolds? The only kind of gloves men can
cope with is big green gardening ones, butch suede or leather ones, or
silly driving ones. The only thing that could get them wriggling into
tight plastic gloves would be the prospect of kinky sex.
Men's placid acceptance of grey hair is a nightmare for hair-colour
manufacturers, forced to come up with ever more inventive ways to give
guys a complex. A hysterically funny, although unintentionally so,
advert is currently cheering up my sma' hours televisual viewing,
promoting the miracle properties of a hair dye, Just For Men, targeted
at blokes (sic). Dusting down the archaic before-and-after marketing
ploy, the cheesy campaign justifies Just For Men's efficacy on the basis
that in surveys eight out of 10 wives preferred the after version.
I searched high and low for this new product in Boots. It wasn't in
the hair colourant section, where the shelves groaned under the weight
of diverse boxes bearing the saccharine smiles of glamorous, successful,
greyless women. Nope, hair colourants for men are tucked away with the
discreetness normally reserved for Durex, tactfully arranged under the
catch-all ''Men's'' section, alongside all the shaving paraphernalia,
ready to be hidden in the shopping basket under a giant can of Gillette
foam.
For any man tempted into the kind of vanity and falsehood which comes
naturally to us chicks, the various brands are convincingly macho. While
female hair dyes have names like the blatantly false Simply Natural or
the gushy, gooey Colour Confidence or Loving Care, the male products opt
for scientific nuance, like the infamous Grecian 2000 or Restoria or the
magnificently named Formula 16, a quite-inspired moniker with its twin
allusions of laboratory gravity and Brands Hatch machismo.
While brands like Loving Care twitter on about lustrous, silky locks,
Restoria and Formula 16 go for hard-hitting facts; ''over time all hair
colour fades as we produce less Melanin'' they pompously inform. Feel
discomfited to learn that I am inadequate in the Melanin department.
But I've had time to get used to it, having spotted my first grey hair
at the tender age of 17. Actually, I didn't spot it, a so-called mate
did, plucking it from my head with vicious glee while I shrieked ''that
means another 10 grey hairs will grow back in its place'', tried
unsuccessfully to stick it back in my head, then hurtled down to Boots
for a packet of Glints and a lifetime of chemical dependency. And it
ain't time to shake the habit yet. Now, where did I put those plastic
gloves?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
