<HEADLINE>The art of talking</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CLARE HENRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863319</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Clare Henry revels in Edith Simon's chatty approach to portrait
painting
EDITH SIMON stopped me in mid-sentence at a National Galleries party
with the question: ''Does columbine mean anything to you?'' I looked
vague. It rang no bells. Was she thinking of the Italian commedia
dell'arte figure, Harlequin's sweetheart, or the flower? Several months
later, again in passing, she asked me the same question, adding, ''Have
you still got your black and silver jacket? I'd like to do your
portrait.''
And so last Christmas I posed in her Edinburgh studio, standing, as is
my habit, pen in hand. As she drew, she asked another question. ''Can
you monologue? It keeps the face alive. Animation makes an enormous
difference to the look of a person. That's why I always ask my sitters
to keep talking. Otherwise you mustn't move!''
The main drawback was that Simon didn't want to hear anything
interesting; anything she might want to listen to. That would distract
her. I found it surprisingly hard, indeed almost impossible, to talk
about nothing, and tailed off now and again. I was also dying to ask
questions. Although I knew her work, I knew little about her.
She wouldn't let me see her drawings of me. (She draws superbly,
''It's the foundation of everything.'') I had to wait months till the
picture was completed -- and I was thrilled with the result. The
columbines, (flowers from her sister's garden it transpired) which fill
the foreground are indeed my kind of flowers in exactly my favourite
colours. How did she guess?
And like others who have sat for her: Tim Clifford, Lord Keir Fraser,
the Bellanys, Lady Rosebery, Andrew Brown, Virginia Izzo and new Fringe
director Hilary Strong, I too can say I recognise me very strongly in
the picture.
My portrait, along with that of Strong, Clifford, Sir Anthony and Lady
Wheeler, her small grandaughter and others, is now part of her Festival
exhibition in the Engine Shed, St Leonard's Lane. It's her twentieth
Edinburgh Festival show; and there's new work for a new venue. For years
she was a regular at the Chambers Street Centre where I first met her in
the 1980s. Then her catalogues said ''Not subsidised by the Scottish
Arts Council'', later, ''Still not subsidised by the Scottish Arts
Council.''
''I'm a maverick -- and I do like to do a bit of tightrope walking. A
maverick doesn't run with the herd, it stays away from the corral and
fits into no pigeonhole. It has to blow its own trumpet, knowing that to
be unclassified is to be suspect.''
Her daughter, Antonia Reeve the photographer, says: ''My mother has
suffered because she chose to work outside the mainstream; didn't want
to be part of the gallery system but organise her own exhibitions.
You've got to be driven to do that. I admire her.
''She's been a great role model. Very disciplined.''
Despite this she's made quite a niche for herself with her unusual
''scalpel painting'' using a difficult and unique technique of paper cut
invented by Simon herself.
With her blonde wig, theatrical clothes and blue glasses, Simon is a
colourful figure. Outspoken, (''one feels obliged to come out with a
definite comment sometimes''), a brilliant draughtswoman, she has the
added talent of being highly articulate, as her audio-visual
presentations demonstrate. No surprise when you learn that she was a
professional writer for 30 years with 17 books, non-fiction as well as
novels, to her name.
''I started my career as an art student at 15 at the Slade. But I
didn't stay. It was as though the Impressionists had never lived. I felt
I couldn't learn anything there. I was summonded by the principal. He
said I was obviously a rebel. Then I went to the Central School. I guess
I was opinionated but I soon made a lot of older friends so I dropped
out to become a founder member of the AIA along with Roland Penrose,
Misha Black, and James Boswell. I did all my learning in a practical
way.''
The AIA (Artists International Association) began in 1933 as an
important radical left-wing force. Members included Henry Moore, Piper,
Pasmore, John Berger, and Carel Weight. Simon's group portrait of the
first AIA committee was exhibited in their 1934 show. Boswell
remembered: ''She was very young then and had not begun writing.'' The
AIA had a social focus too. Simon and 30 others shared a 1938 holiday on
the Ile de Re where they painted a mural for their favourite cafe.
Aged just 23, Bodley Head published her first book. Even then she
tackled big subjects: Moses, Luther, behaviour and motivation. Although
still painting and printmaking on the side, she decided: ''At that time
my essays in art were somehow undirected, haphazard, floundering.
Writing was what I most wanted to do. I loved it. Art was a secondary
back-up occupation helping recharge the batteries when stuck. In the end
I managed to live on my writing.''
One novel was based on Edinburgh University's department of genetics,
which her husband helped found after the war. Dr Reeve still works
exhaustively, being editor of a new Encyclopedia of Genetics. ''Eric has
always been very supportive of my work -- thank heavens!''
Antonia, one of three offspring, remembers her mother ''writing all
the time''. She was extremely successsful. Her book on Frederick the
Great was translated into German. She still gets royalties. But she
managed to give us kids lots of time. She loves children. She would have
had 10 if she could.''
Even then Simon admits: ''People, their make-up, reactions and
relationships being my chief interest, I never could resist doing
portraits: interpretations of character in visual shorthand.''
About 1970 or so Simon went back to art. ''A moment came when what I
had to say could be better said pictorially. If you no longer want to do
it, to push a pen becomes the hardest thing in the world. Art's very
powerful. It's the most serious thing in my life.''
One of her strengths is her readiness to explain. Her videos are a
model of clarity and information. Why did she make them?
''It seemed called for. Learning to see and analyse is the most
difficult thing there is.'' She is also happy to explain her intricate,
complex technique of cutting through seven or eight layers of different
coloured paper to make her portraits.
Hilary Strong, the new Festival Fringe director, also has her portrait
in Simon's exhibition. ''It's very theatrical and theatre is part of my
psyche. I really love my portrait. It's glamorous and show-bizzy.
Edith's managed to catch the mix of theatre and administration that is
my life. And I'm tickled to see that I'm worth more than Tim Clifford!
He's a snip at #1300. I'm #2000!''
Simon says: ''For the six-week duration of the work I will love my
subjects with an absorbing passion, warts and all. Sometimes my empathy
includes a form of X-ray. I don't stay on the surface.'' Sure enough my
columbine did turn out to be prophetic!
Having hung 70 pictures for her Festival show, you would expect her to
take a break. Not at all. She has three works on the go: a portrait
commission, a male nude plus carnival mask plus a Marriage at Cana on
the easel in the Engine Shed -- so she can demonstrate. In an age when
art often seems to specialise in alienation, Simon is that rare
creature: a true communicator.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
