<HEADLINE>Let women follow suit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANNE SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863320</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Adapting comfortable men's clothes to accentuate the female figure
long ago sold the fairer sex on the practicalities of suits and
trousers. Anne Simpson finds modern-day masculine lines can add of sense
of masqerade to a woman's life.
EVER since Eve swiped the fig leaves from somewhere under Adam's nose,
women have been plundering the male wardrobe shamelessly. Bertie
Wooster's sports jackets, Astaire's baggy pants, Chandler's slouch
coats, Napolean's breeches, the cavalry's great coat, Glen Miller's
tuxedo, and every gentleman's club waistcoat, bowler, tie and brogues .
. . the inventory is endless. In women's hands these are not the
underground spoils of cabaret but flagrant daytime stuff.
When, some years ago, Calvin Klein adapted Y-fronts for wear by women
a man might justifiably have asked if anything remained of his attire
that was exclusively masculine. And from the depths of the wardrobe
would have come the reply: ''Nothing, except perhaps the monocle.'' Why
crossover dressing should be so infinitely popular among women concerns
the special ease and practicality of male clothes. Pants are
comfortable, pants are liberating, and today when dress designers try to
kill them off in a flurry of new skirt lengths the market responds with
closed chequebooks, demanding that they think again.
Common sense, of course, is only part of the story. The real seduction
lies in the unexpected. As with so much of fashion the lure is
masquerade.
Coco Chanel was the first to understand the style potential of a great
male robbery when, in the early twenties, she cut up a man friend's
casual clothes, transforming them into an irrestible trouser suit for
women. It took a brave woman to attempt anything so reckless (one
presumes, for the sake of friendship, that she never dared to do it
twice), but that act of creative wantonness demonstrated Chanel's genius
for sensing what women wanted a split second before they knew it
themselves.
And so Chanel changed female dress forever, making her, in the eyes of
George Bernard Shaw, one of the two most influential women of the
twentieth century. The other, he said, was Marie Curie.
At the core of such skill was the ability to avoid straightforward
plagarism or any foray into transvestite parady. Instead, Chanel used
masculine lines to accentuate the feminine, and every woman who,
allegedly without thinking, robs a man of his shirt now knows the value
of that particular trick. Outsize clothing on a woman achieves an
enticing paradox; a sort of worldly vulnerability epitomised by Diane
Keaton as Annie Hall, and still maintained in her eighties today by that
marvellously sophisticated waif, Katharine Hepburn, ambling through
Central Park in moleskins, parka and barrow boy cap.
But 10 years ago designers contorted the mannish theme by foisting on
career women the look of an overpaid bouncer: pushy walk, grim
countenance, shoulders solidly padded for crashing in the door of a
rival drugs den. Now, five years off the new millennium, macho woman is
down and out, the world tired of her over-bearing manner and cumbersome
rig-outs.
In her place, the urbane free spirit glides through the city, a
creature coolly poised in slender trousers of lightweight, pastel tweed,
next-to-nothing smoking jackets, or the Dandyish elan of cravats and
stock tie blouses, frockcoats and abbreviated redingotes.
With such clothes a woman affirms that it is still smart to wear
almost everything a man does, but only in versions scaled to her
physique. However, that state of grace perishes the moment she
carelessly mimics the way men stride, stand or sit. Here the rule
remains that old Chanel dictum about emulating a man rather than
imitating him.
But a woman in man's clothing should also pitch for surprise by
selecting memorable accessories: a lace camisole beneath a hacking
jacket; pearls dipping inside the incline of a waistcoat; earrings which
add some classy sparkle to severity; and a brooch that hints at drama
with perhaps one of those jewelled arrows piercing a lapel.
In her day Marlene Dietrich took to pants with a panache that no other
female star could muster, using crossover dressing to demonstrate a
mysterious quality, something provocative, intelligent, contradictory
and amusing. For Dietrich it was independence of spirit that mattered.
She was the nihilist of glamour and, in that sense, the compadre of
Chanel.
Two women subverting fashion with such careless chic they could
pretend clothes simply didn't count at all.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
