<HEADLINE>Randi Stene, Queen's Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863321</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Music
I BET that Scandinavian mezzo-soprano Randi Stene, who yesterday
opened the Queen's Hall series of morning recitals at this year's
Festival, was relieved when the ordeal was over.
If the first half of her recital was, at best, indifferent, then it
was only partly her fault. Distractions and extraneous noise were flung
at her from every direction. Worse than that was the dogged insistence
of the near-capacity audience to applaud every single thing she did.
As with Jessye Norman earlier this year in Glasgow, the effect on the
singer's concentration, to say nothing of the flow of the recital
programme, was utterly destructive. (Pianist Havard Gimse chewed grimly
and played on.) Whereas big Jessye, however, had intervened and told the
audience to stop applauding in the middle of linked sets of songs, Randi
Stene soldiered on. Or attempted to.
Through Schubert, through Brahms and through Zemlinsky, the mindless
clappers persisted. The girl -- who has a polished, gleaming voice,
though she is weak at extremes of her register -- was obviously
intimidated. Her concentration was all over the place (as were her
eyes).
In the second half, she took things into her own hands in a Dvorak
cycle, plunging into the next song before the deadly hands could be
brought together. She relaxed, she salvaged it, and there was some real
quality singing in her final Grieg selection. And I thought these
audiences were sophisticated. Ha.
</TEXT>
