<HEADLINE>Image change is only 'half the job'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863323</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CALL for substantial investment to boost jobs in Edinburgh's Wester
Hailes housing estate was backed last night by local councillors.
District councillor Willie Dunn, who has represented South Hailes
since 1992, said: ''To me they have done nothing to create jobs. That's
the bottom line.
He claimed the Urban Partnership had done ''half of its job''.
He said there was more poverty in his ward, with an unemployment rate
of about 30%. ''The one thing the partnership has achieved is that the
image of Wester Hailes is not as bad as it was.''
Ms Lynne Main, chairwoman of Wester Hailes Representative Council,
said: ''The first five years have really looked at the physical
regeneration of the area. They have made great strides with that. The
area does look nicer and we are pleased with that.
''Overall, peoples' circumstances haven't really changed. No great
inroads have been made into unemployment. People have somewhere nice to
live but they don't have a job.''
Responding to their comments, Mr William Docherty, chief executive of
the partnership, said that their job was only half done.
''We recognise that most of the efforts in the next five years will be
directed towards economic development, improving the economy and
reducing unemployment levels.''
The researchers said the percentage of expenditure devoted to
improving the area's human assets must rise significantly in the next
phase.
The partnership objectives included halving the gap between the Wester
Hailes unemployment rate and the substantially lower rate for Edinburgh
over five years.
</TEXT>
