<HEADLINE>Better times for a scheme that failed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863325</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHITFIELD was Dundee's idealistic answer in the sixties to the need
for slum clearance.
Communities bred in the Victorian tenements of Lochee, the Wellgate,
and Hilltown, with their shared outside toilets, were to be replaced
with high-rise communities.
The maisonettes and multi-storey flats with bathrooms and spacious
accommodation made Whitfield attractive to many young families in the
sixties.
However, the community, which was to grow to 12,000 -- larger than the
population of Forfar -- lacked the amenities of a tiny village, let
alone a modest county town.
Most critically of all, the town planners did not envisage the
consequences of Dundee's industrial decline, the return of mass
unemployment, and the growth of a drug culture.
Whitfield, the socialist dream, became more of a nightmare, and
families queued up to leave.
The transformation in the estate is all the more remarkable, given
Whitfield's notorious status in Scotland as a ''problem scheme''.
Since 1982, #55m of public money has been spent on rehabilitating the
area.
It has achieved a surprising success. More than 1600 of the old
unpopular houses have been demolished; 550 new houses have been built;
330 homes have been modernised, and security improvements have been made
to a further 900 houses.
Last night, Ms Kate McLean, Labour leader of Dundee District Council,
said: ''The district council has worked closely with the community for
many years and this latest recognition of the Whitfield success
demonstrates that results can be achieved by working in partnership with
other agencies.''
</TEXT>
