<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Russian sizzler</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863328</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WILLIAM RUSSELL feels the heat of Russian film-making in Burnt By the
Sun and finds The Neon Bible a thumping bore
HIGH summer in 1936. Life in the country dacha of Sergei Kotov, hero
of the Bolshevik Revolution, his young wife, Maroussia (Ingeborga
Dapkunaite) and their enchanting little daughter, Nadia (Nadia
Mikhalkov) seems sweet in Nikita Mikhalkov's Oscar-winning film, Burnt
By the Sun. The illusion of high comedy, that this is a tale of smiles
of a long summer's day, is created only to be shattered at the end. The
film is a tragedy, a tale about people burnt by the sun of revolution.
The delightful daughter Nadia plays games and wheedles favours from
everyone, Kotov, his parents, and the inevitable hangers-on one finds in
those extended Russian families familiar from Chekhov. They squabble and
make up, while outside the countryside life unfolds as it has done for
centuries.
The family eat huge meals, go for a picnic, swim, while a lorry driver
with a load of furniture, unable to find his destination, drives about
the countryside in ever-decreasing circles, the peasants, harvesting the
corn, turn to Kotov (Nikita Mikhalkov) for help when a military exercise
threatens to send tanks over their crops, and are busy building a
mysterious structure whose purpose is not quite clear.
But the comedy, the manifest happiness are just an illusion for this
is a world without foundations ruled over by a monster, Joseph Stalin,
who is about to lay waste to everything.
A good-looking young man, Dimitri (Oleg Menchikov), Maroussia's lover
before she met Kotov, arrives unexpectedly, and is welcomed into the
family with joy, a prodigal returned. He tells Nadia fairy stories,
which clearly mean more than she understands, flirts with Maroussia, and
engages in wary exchanges with Kotov. He turns out to be the Angel of
Death.
This brilliant, marvellous film, impeccably performed, superbly
directed, breaks the heart. It is quite simply a masterpiece.
Unmissable.
Terence Davies The Neon Bible is based on a book by John Kennedy Tool
about a young boy (Jacob Tierney) growing up in an American Bible-Belt
town in the 1940s with his bullying father (Denis Leary), his
downtrodden, sensitive mother (Diana Scarwid) and his gutsy Aunt Mae
(Gena Rowlands), a bar-room ''chantoose'' of uncertain years whose
career is going nowhere for obvious reason -- she sings pretty
dreadfully.
The boy dreams of escape, Aunt Mae encourages him, his father bullies
him, his mother suffers in silence, and the soundtrack is laden with the
popular songs of the period. Sounds familiar? We are, of course, in
Terence Davies Land, that country of the past he made his own in the
undeniably marvellous Distant Voices, Still Lives, and to which he
returned with diminishing effect in the sequel, The Long Day Closes.
Translated from working-class Liverpool to the American South, Davies
proves less assured and his tricks, the use of music, the way the camera
glides from a realistic setting into a highly stylised one, the
fascination with strong, but rather louche women are becoming over
familiar. He is a fine film-maker, but he needs to extend his range, not
plough the same old furrow, which is what he has done here.
Rowlands warbles in a whisky voice and creates an endearing, sad
loser as Mae, while Tierney is fine as the boy but ultimately it is all
terribly inconsequential. The press audience booed it when it was shown
at Cannes, a cruelly unfair verdict because it is not a bad film, just a
rather disappointing one from a director of such high talent. Try fresh
fields and pastures new, Mr Davies, or you risk becoming a Johnny One
Note bore.
* Burnt By the Sun (6.45pm, Cameo 1, and tomorrow 7.30pm GFT) The Neon
Bible (9.30pm, Cameo 1).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
