<DOCNO>GH950816-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mixed reports on poor estates. Partnership initiatives score some success</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863330</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PARTNERSHIP schemes to regenerate four of Scotland's most deprived
housing estates received mixed reports yesterday.
Whitfield in Dundee emerges as the outstanding success in interim
evaluation studies carried out by research teams from Glasgow and
Bristol universities for the Scottish Office.
Ferguslie Park in Paisley, Castlemilk in Glasgow, and Wester Hailes in
Edinburgh were judged less well but with some achievements in specific
areas.
The Scottish Office launched the partnership schemes in 1988 as part
of its policy New Life for Urban Scotland.
They were an attempt to harness local communities and public and
private sector bodies to combat poor image and poverty of the estates
and develop housing, employment, facilities, and the environment.
Of the four, Wester Hailes got off to the worst start. A new estate,
it had gone into decline before it was even completed.
''The choice of Wester Hailes as a partnership area was interpreted by
many parties as primarily a political decision, located as it was in the
constituency of the then Secretary of State for Scotland.
''In any event, relationships between the local authorities and the
Scottish Office were difficult at the outset,'' the researchers said.
The key area of creating jobs for people has not been a resounding
success. Although #60m had been invested over five years in Wester
Hailes, some of which was new money, less than 5% was in areas of
employment, training, and business development.
''Poor educational experiences, the consequences of long-term
unemployment and related social disadvantages mean that a substantial
investment is required to link local people with employment. This cost
is consistently underestimated in regeneration initiatives,'' the
researchers said.
Similarly in Castlemilk, employment targetting had been disappointing,
particularly involving local people in construction projects.
Ferguslie Park fared better on jobs: numbers registered as unemployed
fell by 40% in six years and the main cause in the reduction was due to
economic regeneration work by the partnership.
At Whitfield, unemployment was double the Dundee average in 1988 but
it fell faster on the estate than in the city, particularly in the early
years.
The approach to housing and effective collabaration of residents and
outside bodies is identified as the principal trigger for transforming
Whitfield from a ''dreary, squalid, and unsafe council estate, which
most residents wished to leave'' into a ''mostly attractive residential
area''.
Castlemilk also reversed its poor image so that ''a real, if fragile,
local housing market involving municipal, social landlord, and private
ownership is emerging''. Requests to move into the area doubled between
1988 and 1992.
The Scottish Office put a positive gloss on the research. It said
unemployment had fallen by 20% and more than 2000 new homes had been
built on the estates. The proportion of those satisfied or very
satisfied living on them had risen from 54% to 71% and those wishing to
leave had fallen from 40% to 23%.
Mr Raymond Robertson, Scottish Office Minister responsible for urban
policy, said the findings were very encouraging.
Mr Fergus Ewing, SNP business spokesman, said: ''The problems of
long-term unemployment, drug addiction, and crime have not been properly
addressed. One part of the answer is a budget for jobs and that's what
the SNP will deliver.''
Deputy Shadow Scottish Secretary John McFall said Labour supported
partnership schemes because they allowed communities to take decisions
for themselves.
''However, it would appear from these schemes that the issue of
economic development has been missed out. Only a proper approach on a
long-term basis in this area will be effective in reducing unemployment,
poverty, and alienation'', he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
