<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The poisoned groves of academe</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL FRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863332</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SINCE we are in a period of particularly depressing political trivia,
I do not hesitate to hail as one of its more important events the
commencement next session at Edinburgh University of classes in
nationalism by my old friend and sparring partner, Tom Nairn.
He thus resumes a career which for most of his academic generation
ended in more or less honourable early retirement some years ago. They
have all been put out to grass while he, a portly but otherwise youthful
63, is just getting into his stride round the second lap.
He did occupy a teaching position once, but quit it in 1968. The date
is significant: what Daniel Cohn-Bendit was to the Sorbonne, and Rudi
Dutschke to the Free University of Berlin, Tom was to Hornsey College of
Art. I can no longer remember what exactly happened in Hornsey to make
it for a while the focus of the seething revolutionary aspirations of
the working class. No doubt it involved Tariq Ali, Vanessa Redgrave, and
a cast of thousands. In any event, Tom found himself afterwards without
a job, and has never held another.
Where are they now, the blithe spirits of the heady summer of 1968?
Dutschke is dead, Cohn-Bendit is that most parasitical of creatures, a
Euro-MP, while Ali and Redgrave carry on a life of shameless
self-indulgence. For all the excitement of those years, little of their
legacy has proved permanent, and the generation that lived through them
has turned out to be one not so much of vipers as of slow-worms: blind,
harmless, and easily trodden upon. But among its few solid achievements
Tom Nairn's thinking and writing ought to be numbered.
Equally, I am sure he is and will remain more considerable than the
academic cohort from which he then parted company. The 1960s saw a huge
expansion of British universities, which had its benefits but also
filled them with third-rate players of the system who happened to be in
the right place at the right time. They matured into dead wood which has
only with difficulty been cut out in the Thatcherite era, and not
completely yet. Among the ill consequences has been, till now, to keep
in limbo a patently meritorious mind like Tom Nairn's.
That casts the Scottish universities especially in a bad light. Full
marks to Edinburgh for having taken Tom on, though with his intellectual
pedigree it can hardly be counted a bold move. It does register that
something has been happening in the country of sufficient importance for
even the universities to take note of, but certainly not before time.
A frequent complaint against them is that they are agents of
anglicisation, and in some senses that is obviously true. I would still
put it differently and deplore their utter, voluntary subjection to the
state.
They entered into it on an assumption that the state would always be
run by people from the same class as themselves and amenable to their
wheedling, but have since found out that he who lives by patronage dies
by patronage.
It is not as if, under this regime, British universities have exactly
enjoyed a golden age. On the contrary, they have acquired the usual
characteristics of agencies of the state, notably a penchant for order,
regularity, and boringness. In Scotland especially this has reinforced
the pussy-footing respectability, the commitment to authoritarian
mediocrity, which is a besetting, and very traditional, national sin.
One of its aims is to exclude people like Tom Nairn.
For two or three decades, after all, we have had going on in Scotland
a complex of phenomena -- in politics, in literature and other high
arts, in popular culture, in historiography -- which in total can
reasonably be called a national revival.
Its origins are hard to explain, and perhaps posterity will never rate
it as high as I am doing here. But there can be no mistaking the
outburst of confidence behind it, a confidence scarcely seen in the
country since before the First World War.
Yet for too long all this was more or less ignored in the
universities, as too difficult and not respectable enough. To take just
the field in which Tom Nairn specialises, political scientists have
themselves ruefully acknowledged the very meagre upheavals in Scottish
politics, the rise of nationalism in particular. Nearly all the best
work has come from outside, from Tom himself, and from others involved
in the real world, where they do not have to worry about sticking their
necks out and ruining their scholarly reputations.
Nor is politics the only subject to be straitjacketed in this way.
There were always exceptions, and their number has grown, but in general
universities have shared the metropolitan assumption that Scotland is a
small-time dump where nothing, at least nothing worthy of study, ever
happens.
It is impossible to imagine that, say, the American system of higher
education would close its eyes to developments in the society round it.
On the contrary to keep up with them, almost with every passing moment,
is one of its obsessions. That the system is decentralised and
half-private, needing to deal with students' actual interests, may not
be unconnected with the obsession. We, by contrast, run a system which
makes universities forever gaze at their own navels. So, far from having
academic freedom to defend, they become merely protectors of their own
privileges.
It would be too much to say that Tom Nairn's appointment can change
any of this. He may, of course, himself be changed. He has an unrivalled
capacity for being magnificently wrong, but that is often true of
important thinking, and I should hate to see him lose it. If ever he
starts to get things right, I shall advise him to forsake the poisoned
groves of academe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
