<DOCNO>GH950816-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scandal has put efforts in shade</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863335</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EFFORTS to regenerate the Paisley housing estate of Ferguslie Park
have been overshadowed in recent months by scandal.
Last month, the Scottish Office announced an independent audit into
the use of urban aid programme funds by Ferguslie Park Community
Holdings Ltd. That move followed controversy over the running of the
community business's subsidiary company, FCB Enterprise Security Ltd,
which is being investigated by police and Renfrew district councillors.
The security company has denied strenuously any allegations against
it.
What no-one would deny is that the area has borne a crippling burden
of social problems for many years.
Built as a slum clearance area, Ferguslie Park's population declined
from more than 12,000 in 1971 to just 5000 in 1988. In that year, note
the authors of the interim evaluation report on the partnership, 82% of
households had total annual incomes of less than #5000. Skill levels
were low and educational qualifications minimal. Half of the land area
was more or less derelict.
The report records substantial improvements under the partnership.
Several hundred homes have been built and the district council has
modernised hundreds of existing properties. A community park, a sports
centre, a police post, and the multi-purpose Tannahill civic centre have
been completed.
On economic regeneration, the authors say that emphasis on improving
the skills and self-confidence of job seekers has achieved
''considerable success''. The number of people on the unemployment
register fell by 40% between 1988 and 1994, and 1479 job placements were
recorded by the partnership between January 1989, and March 1994.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Castlemilk residents happier to remain so</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863336</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CASTLEMILK, one of Europe's largest housing estates, presented an
extremely bleak picture when the partnership began.
High unemployment, low skill levels, unpopular housing in poor
conditions, inadequate shopping facilities, a poor health record, and
high crime levels -- these are just some of the characteristics
described by the authors of the interim evaluation report.
So what progress has been made? Among the successes highlighted in the
report are improvements in the housing stock and choice.
More than #110m has been spent or committed to social housing and #20m
private-sector investment has been made. A third of the dwellings have
been improved and six housing associations and co-operatives have been
formed.
''Castlemilk is perceived more favourably by residents and there has
been an increase in the numbers of people wishing to stay in, or move
back to, Castlemilk,'' notes the report.
With little prospect of attracting major employers to the estate, the
partnership has concentrated on improving the skills of local people and
access to job opportunities elsewhere.
There have been more than 1800 job placements and more than 500
training places from the Castlemilk Economic Development Agency (CEDA),
one of the bodies in the partnership.
However, long-term unemployment continues at high levels -- more than
15%, compared with the Glasgow average of less than 14%. Incomes remain
low and dependence upon benefits was actually higher last year than in
1990.
On a brighter note, the report points to environmental improvements,
innovative practices in education, health, and community care, and a
drop in crime rates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
