<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>In search of Scottie's kilt at the Perth conference</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>DIARY</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863339</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is, of course, a serious subject, not to say ''a serious problem'',
and there is every chance she'll hate us for bringing this up once
again, but are we right in detecting an ulterior motive in the campaign
launched by the SNP's Roseanna Cunningham yesterday to bring more
international film-makers to Scotland?
Consider: the MP for Perth and Kinross is a noted science-fiction
movie aficionado, so much so that she even shares a home with a
life-size cardboard cut-out of Mr Spock (highly realistic, at least when
compared to certain of the party's leading figures). Consider, too, that
the Nationalists are ever keen to promote proper representations of wir
modern cultural identity n'that, unlike the somewhat dodgy old versions
advanced in Rob Roy and Braveheart, even if Ireland's contribution to
the making of the latter happens to have prompted the SNP's campaign.
Given that the warped factor on the Diary is always fairly high, and
that the Nats are seeking opinions and constructive ideas from all
quarters, the Diary therefore looks forward to Star Trek XV: The Search
for Scottie's Kilt, the searing parable of one man's Scottish accent
boldly going where no Scottish accent has gone before, shot entirely on
location at the Perth conference.
A nation, Jim, but not as we know it.
Up in the air
LIKE many of you, no doubt, the Diary is in receipt of a communication
from those very relaxed people at Transcendental Meditation Regional
Headquarters (Edinburgh and Glasgow) offering a free video.
As is customary with the followers of the Maharishi Mahesh Yogi, the
man immortalised by John Lennon as ''Sexy Sadie'', remedies are promised
for just about everything -- stress, obesity, irritability, tumours,
heart disease, rotten relationships, flat feet -- though no mention is
made of how much it actually costs to learn TM's ''very simple
technique''.
What we don't get -- and this, like most things, may very well be our
problem -- is the absence of any mention of what ought to be the
organisation's unique selling point. In other words, not a word is
offered on the wonderful art of ''yogic flying''. This is odd.
True, cruel sceptics have in the past pointed out that TM's
contribution to aeronautics bears more than a passing resemblance to
bumping along the ground on your backside while maintaining a fixed grin
-- on your face, naturally -- but to our knowledge the meditating types
have yet to agree.
So what's the deal? Why bother to ''spontaneously'' develop a better
lifestyle, cure insomnia, or ''unfold your full potential'', even in
mixed company, when you could be cutting out the middle man on your next
package trip to Benidorm or jetting down to the pub for some in-flight
refuelling? Incidentally, TM ''requires no change in beliefs''. This
must be handy for those who'll believe anything.
Conflicting beliefs
OUT of the Mouths of Babes. It may not be the best question a child
has asked about the Balkans conflict, but we couldn't answer it. If
everyone has taken to referring routinely to the Bosnians as
''Muslims'', how come the peace-loving Serbs are never described as
Christians?
Take it as read
HAVING recorded something of a bogey ourselves by giving loyal readers
the chance to enjoy a splendid article by Raymond Jacobs twice, we may
be the last to talk. Nevertheless, we are no match for Edinburgh's
Evening News, a publication so proud of its work that it has taken to
printing entire pages more than once in the same edition and, if you
follow, on more than one occasion.
This points to one of two conclusions: either the News is determined
to ensure its readers don't miss those crucial hot stories, or staff
have taken a lead from the public and given up actually reading their
own paper.
Naturally we incline to the former theory, awed as we still are by the
immortal headline that appeared in the tabloid not so very long ago:
''Headline Goes Here''.
Campaign support
WELL, that's that. Festival over for another year. Two hours spent
snarling, misdirecting tourists -- ''Princes Street, sir? Certainly,
sir. Bottom of Leith Walk and turn right'' -- and handing out leaflets
marked ''Sod Off'' to wandering Fringe performers before we settle back,
content in the knowledge of a job well done.
Before we retire, however, there's still time for one shameless plug
for an event at the Fruitmarket Gallery Cafe tomorrow night. This has
nothing to do with stand-up comedy, in fact it isn't very funny at all,
but does feature Tom Leonard, Sandie Craigie, and James Kelman, not to
mention some live music.
Organised by Artists in Solidarity and the Scottish Bookfair of
Radical, Black and Third World Books, the night is a benefit for the
Stephen Lawrence Family Campaign. It will be followed by a similar event
in Glasgow, at Caledonian University's Queens College on Friday.
Why do we bring it up? Some of you might remember Stephen Lawrence: a
black English teenager brutally murdered two years ago whose case,
according to what the police told his family in March, was closed. The
Crown Prosecution Service also refused to accept new evidence and said
it would take no action.
Thus it was, and despite all official obstacles, that the boy's
parents were obliged to pursue a hitherto unheard-of private criminal
prosecution. Four men have now been charged with murder and committal
proceedings will take place next week. Hence the family's need for
support.
The Diary points all this out for no better reason than it somewhat
argues against the apparent conviction of Sir Paul Condon, the man who
runs the Metropolitan Police, that muggings by black teenagers are the
only sort of crimes worth bothering about. And if you still feel in need
of a proper, Festival-type laugh, console yourself with the thought that
despicable racist assaults never, ever happen in friendly Scotland.
The lost chord
FINALLY, the question on everyone's lips: is Jerry Garcia still
grateful? If not, why not?
</TEXT>
