<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000106</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863340</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIFTY years ago yesterday Emperor Hirohito broadcast to the Japanese
nation for the first time. He said that the situation had not
necessarily developed to Japan's advantage and told his subjects that
they must ''endure the unendurable and suffer the insufferable''.
There was a last flurry of resistance as die-hard officers tried to
prevent the record of the emperor's speech reaching the studio. They
failed (32 were killed in the palace grounds), and the Imperial Japanese
Army and the people bowed to their fate.
The actual surrender took place aboard the battleship Missouri, in
Tokyo harbour on September 2. It was a theatrical event, stage-managed
by that most thespian of American generals, Douglas MacArthur. Just as
the Japanese Minister, dressed formally in a morning suit, drew himself
up after signing the instrument of surrender, a huge fleet of American
planes swept across the bay, dead on time, to demonstrate the power of
the United States.
The end of the war marked the birth of the modern world, after a
period of accelerated history: MacArthur, the general who commanded all
American forces in the western Pacific as the atomic era began, had, as
a child, been besieged in a fort by Indians armed with bows and arrows
in the American west. MacArthur's father was then an Indian fighter and
later a hero of the Union Army in the Civil War.
In one lifetime, America went from the Stone Age to the Atomic Age.
Two generations on, and the country shows but muted interest in the VJ
Day anniversary.
For VE-Day in Europe there were parades, memorial services, and a
universal celebration of the memory of the last good war, when we were
liberated from a dreadful tyranny. The Americans barely noticed.
President Clinton went across the river to Arlington Cemetery to lay a
wreath on the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier, and made an unmemorable
speech. Then he hopped in to a plane and flew to Moscow and boycotted
the military parades there as a gesture of disapproval of Russia's
Chechnya involvement. And that was it. There were no public
commemorations worth noting, no parades, no festivities, no
acknowledgement that America played a decisive part in defeating the
Nazis.
Now comes VJ Day, and once again there will be no fireworks, no
parades, nothing of any note. Mr Clinton will attend a ceremony at Pearl
Harbor, on the spot where George Bush commemorated the attack on the
50th anniversary, on December 7, 1991. Another anti-climax.
In contrast to Clinton and VE-Day, President Reagan made an immense
production of the 40th anniversary of D-Day, and the commemorations and
attendant festivities were a huge success, and delighted America. A
decade later, Bill Clinton tagged along behind the British and French
celebrations, and marked the end of the war hardly at all.
Perhaps his youthful opposition to the Vietnam War has left him with a
settled antipathy to all things military, to the extent that he cannot
even pretend to any enthusiasm for America's last ''good war''.
Partly, perhaps, it may be the natural resentment of the young at
their parents endlessly harping on their own victories. The notorious
libertarian streak of the 1960s was largely generated by youth's
reaction against the smug complacency of the Second World War
generation. Clinton and his cohorts had freed themselves from that
mindset -- and apparently are still firmly of the opinion that war
stories are boring when they are not evil.
The debate over the morality of Hiroshima has played a large part. The
revisionists have bombarded the newspapers and television with their
argument that dropping the bombs was a crime. They have not won the
debate (it still rages fiercely) but they have perhaps succeeded in
putting abroad the notion that to celebrate VJ Day means celebrating the
destruction of Hiroshima and Nagasaki.
But most central of all is the sad fact that the United States is not
the self-confident, proud, optimistic country that it was in the 1980s
when Reagan announced it was ''morning again in America''.
A more imaginative president than Clinton might have seized the
anniversaries to restore a little optimism to the American public. But I
suspect that under it all, Bill Clinton, too, suffers from the fin de
siecle malaise that afflicts so much of the country. It's more than a
little worrying when the British, of all people, can still work up
enthusiasm and public jollity, a general manifestation of national
self-confidence -- and America can't.
</TEXT>
