<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Drugs put prisons to the test</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES FREEMAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863341</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Following a cocaine seizure at Shotts, James Freeman considers the
case for mandatory testing in Scottish jails.
IN HIS report on Scottish prisons last year, the then chief of the
prison's inspectorate used the evocative phrase -- in relation to
visiting in jails -- ''the long, dark shadow cast by the drugs world''.
That shadow fell over Shotts Prison earlier this week with the
disclosure of a seizure of cocaine, albeit a relatively small quantity,
an event which raises a number of serious issues for a prison system
currently enjoying its lengthiest period of stability for years. The
major question has to be whether the latest disclosure strengthens the
case for an early introduction of random mandatory drug-testing in
Scottish jails and whether the Shotts seizure has hastened that day.
There are persuasive arguments against random testing; it does not,
for example, address the primary problem which is, that drugs are being
taken into our prisons, mainly if not exclusively at visiting times, and
on a regular basis. And, while it might be popular with some sections of
the public and with some sections of the populist media, it would almost
certainly prove highly unpopular with prisoners at a period in history
when the rejuvenated Scottish Prison Service has expounded the theory of
the responsible prisoner being provided with the opportunities to better
himself.
Would any gains accruing to the public -- the paymasters and the major
''customers'' of the prison system -- be outweighed by a decrease in
stability in the jails, or by damage to the better-quality relationships
which currently -- to the outsider at least -- appear to apply between
prisoners and staff?
There is a persistent feeling within the criminal justice system here
that random tests -- on the model being ironed out and debugged in
England and Wales at the moment -- are not that far away if for no other
reason than that it is an option available in Scotland under the last
Criminal Justice Act and that its introduction south of the Border,
under the present experimental basis, was associated with the then Home
Office Prisons' Minister, Mr Michael Forsyth.
The Home Office is coy about the results of the first six months of
random mandatory testing for drugs in the eight English jails where the
scheme is being piloted, but the early figures have been made available
in Parliament.
These showed that 36% of prisoners tested at random between February
and April tested positive, 32% of those having used cannabis, 1% heroin
and 1% tranquilisers. In the same period, Parliament was told, when
prisoners strongly suspected of having abused drugs were selected, 62%
of them tested positive.
The Home Office says that the mandatory urine tests did not lead to
any adverse reaction from prisoners in the eight pilot establishments --
Lindholme, Wakefield, Feltham YOI, Stoke Heath YOI, Pentonville,
Bristol, Holloway female prison and Weyland -- although it has to be
remarked that none of these institutions has the volatile reputation of
a prison such as Shotts with its high density of long-term,
high-security category criminals.
The obvious conclusion which can be drawn from the two sets of English
figures is that there is a more effective way of catching drug abusers
in jails than by random testing and that is by using the unique know-how
of the staff at the sharp end.
It may, of course, be wrong to prejudge Mr Forsyth's intentions. He is
known to be deeply interested in the Scottish Prison Service, a legacy
from his Home Office experiences, and he is known to be cautious about
the pace of the English rush towards private prisons and outside
participation through market testing.
His views on that may become clearer in the next few weeks but it
would not be surprising if it was closer to the idea of a healthy,
achieving public service delivering meaningful and productive custodial
regimes for the benefit of all of us.
There is another element, also political, in the argument and that is
that the prison officers -- who would have to administer compulsory,
random urine sampling -- would almost certainly be against it. Medical
and nursing staff refuse to have anything to do with compulsory sampling
on ethical grounds.
Mr Eddie Hunter, the chairman of the Scottish Prison Officers'
Association, said: ''I am not sure random mandatory testing would be
beneficial for anyone. I imagine by elimination it would establish who
the drug users are but in reality a good prison officer using his
knowledge of the prisoners is just as likely to be able to pinpoint the
most likely suspects.
''From my own experience in Shotts I would say that by far the great
majority of prisoners do not take drugs of any description. To impose
random testing on these men is bound to get an adverse reaction. There
is little to be gained.''
Mr Hunter also advocates caution in relation to the noises coming from
England in the wake of the Whitemoor Report on general toughening up of
visits procedure. Prisoners in Scotland have become used to a better
quality of open visiting which the majority do not abuse, he believes.
He is also pragmatic about the problems.
''As long as there is big money involved inside the prisons then the
sumggling in of drugs is going to be practically impossible to stamp out
totally. But as long as our members continue to be vigilant I am happy
with the situation. Very little gets missed,'' he said.
The real loser from any random testing programme in Scotland would be
the ground-breaking voluntary saliva-testing programme which, since
1991, has created for scientists, health officials, the social services
and the SPS itself an unrivalled picture of HIV incidence and injecting
and other high-risk behaviour inside Scottish prisons.
The survey work led by Dr Sheila Gore and Dr Graham Bird has been
widely praised; eight programmes have been carried out and of the 3564
prisoners, men and women, available to be tested, 82% volunteered.
The results broadly show what happens inside prison reflects what
happens in the communities from which the prisoners are drawn. Of the
volunteers, 27% said they had injected drugs at some time and 56% of the
adult men had injected drugs in prison at one time or another.
But yesterday Dr Gore (a researcher with the Medical Research Council
Biostatistics Unit at Cambridge) said the mass of data provided had
allowed the SPS to devise better informed, better designed drug
intervention programmes.
''It should be borne in mind that the man who gave the political
go-ahead for this voluntary saliva-testing programme in 1991 when it was
totally new was Michael Forsyth and everyone should be grateful to him
for that. It was a courageous act the wisdom of which has been
demonstrated.
''The SPS has followed through with a series of drug reduction
programmes but the fact is that there is a waiting list in the prisons
of men who want to get help. These men come forward and say they have a
problem which they want to tackle.
''The real problem is that the prison service does not have sufficient
resources to run enough of these programmes to meet the need,'' she
added.
The crunch could be that this enlightened and clearly beneficial
programme would be crippled by any imposition of mandatory testing on
prisoners here. In England a punishment tariff has been introduced along
with the swoops, 14 days loss of remission for having cannabis traces in
the urine, 21 days for a Class A drug.
NACRO, the English prisoner resettlement organisation, says that it
has had cases where prisoners have lost accommodation fixed up in
advance because their release date has been put back -- a
counter-productive side effect. Helen Edwards, NACRO's director of
communications, said: ''There is a lot of concern about drugs misuse in
prisons but random mandatory testing is not an answer. What is really
needed is more positive programmes to reduce demand inside.''
What has yet to emerge in England is the true monetary cost of
testing, although the first obvious cost is the #1680 needed to keep
someone inside for another month as a punishment for testing positive.
One informed source gave The Herald an estimate that random mandatory
testing is currently being shown to eat up around half the available
health care budget in any jail.
By the same token, a properly staffed drug reduction programme would
come in at about half the cost of random testing. The message from
England would therefore appear to be to avoid at any cost what looks
like another ''magic bullet'' solution from the endlesss Home Office
supply, and stick to the home-grown Scottish approach which may yet
bring longer-term benefits for our communities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
