<HEADLINE>There are two prisoners here</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863343</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CASE NO. 2: Margaret Wilson and her husband Sonny.
THE first thing William ''Sonny'' Wilson did when he came out of a
coma three years ago, was to ask Margaret to marry him.
A year later she did, knowing that her husband would be totally
dependent upon her for the rest of their life together.
Sonny, a painter and decorator who was never off sick a day in his
life, suffered an aneurysm at the age of 52. He has been left
wheelchair-bound, almost completely blind, with impaired hearing, his
speech affected, and brain-damaged. Perhaps the hardest thing for his
family to bear is the change in his personality.
Margaret, 58, who gave up her job as a manageress of City Bakeries to
care for Sonny, says: ''My husband wakes me up in the morning and the
first thing he says is 'I love you', and I get a wee song in the
morning.''
But there are times, too, when his frustration is taken out on the one
closest to him and life is anything but sweet words and kisses.
When Margaret was expecting her eighth child her husband left her. She
and Sonny started going out together and he helped her and her children
through the hard times.
''I married him because he had nobody else to look after him. There
was no way I would see him put into a hospital, and he was good to me
when the kids were young,'' she said.
When he was lying in a coma and she prayed for him to get well enough
even to be in a wheelchair, she had no idea what life as a full-time
carer would be like. The worst was when he first came home to her.
''When he got out of hospital they took me into a wee room and said he
would be getting all the help in the world. If I needed a respite they
would take him in. The first day I got him out he took an epileptic fit.
The hospital just said to put him on his side, but with the size of him
I couldn't move him. I never got anything,'' she said.
With the help of her local MP Mike Watson -- she lives in Govanhill --
she eventually got Sonny into one of the Scotcare rehabilitation units
near Wishaw -- but he came out disappointed he still could not walk.
The Princess Royal Trust for carers provides a centre that Sonny can
go to through the day, Monday to Friday, which has provided him with an
interest in life and a more regular pattern to his day.
''If I ever win the lottery, that's who I would give the biggest part
to. If it was not for them, I am telling you straight, I would not be
sitting here just now,'' she said.
In the past year, thanks mainly to Sonny's occupational therapist
Heather Bunting, Margaret has been able to put Sonny into respite care.
There are some positive moves, however. She now receives the
independent living allowance for carers and support from the Princess
Royal Trust carers' network. And there's the respite.
''I have seen me, before I got this week off now and then, smashing
plates off the wall, and then whoever comes in next gets my anger.''
She has started getting panic attacks and has been on
anti-depressants.
''There's not one prisoner in the house, there are two prisoners. If I
am out anywhere he panics. I am the only one he will let put him on the
commode,'' she said.
''I do feel bitter,'' said Margaret.
''I see couples about our age that we used to go about with, and you
say, 'That's no right'. We should be enjoying ourselves just now. I have
had eight children and I have my ninth now. He's like a wee bairn,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Isolated reality of always being there</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863344</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CASE NO. 1: Isobel and Dave Allen and their daughter Susan.
TOTAL dependence on her parents means that Susan Allan can never be
left on her own or she will hurt herself.
She has Rett Syndrome, a rare disorder which affects one in 12,000 of
female births and causes profound mental and physical handicap. She can
smile and vocalise, but the most distressing symptom is that she is
violent towards herself.
During the week she goes to Langlands School in Govan, although she
will leave next year when she turns 16, and five or six times a year she
goes to a respite unit. While she's at home she needs constant attention
and stimulus.
''The way we know she's wakened is we hear the thumps of her fist
hitting her face. That's her communicating that she's distressed,'' said
her father Dave Allan, an electrician who lives in Cambuslang.
Susan's mother Isobel is a trained counsellor who works with other
carers. It is something she developed as a means of coping with her own
frustrations of having to live with someone who was violent and
unpredictable.
Part of her work involves speaking as a carer to nurses as part of
their training and her most heartfelt plea is for professionals,
particularly doctors, to provide better emotional support for carers.
She feels that professionals need to understand some of the day-to-day
problems that carers face -- like the fact that if Isobel wants to go to
the toilet, she has to take Susan with her because she can't be left on
her own; like not knowing whether she will be able to finish the cup of
coffee or the meal she has made.
Even when respite does come, it can take a couple of days to wind down
to a more normal pace of life, by which time the person being cared for
is back home.
A lot of long-term problems suffered by carers stem from the fact that
the initial support in the early days was not there, Isobel said.
''You carry that bitterness with you. If there's another life, I am
coming back as director of education and health. I want to insist that
professional staff have to be highly skilled in human relationship
skills,'' she said.
Nurses, doctors, and social workers too often have problems dealing
with carers' feelings, particularly their anger, so they label some
carers as ''aggressive''.
Those less able to assert themselves tend to fall into the trap that
if they are offered any facilities, they should be grateful, even if
they are not what they need or want. Instead, they should feel they have
the right to say thank-you, but we need something different, she said.
The Allans are anxious to impress upon people that their life,
although problematic, is still blessed.
''We are just so fortunate that we have so much going for us. Dave's
got a job, we are still together and have been married for 27 years. We
have a house with a garden. We count our blessings and there are many of
them.
''We would never have had so much richness in our lives without Susan.
Susan does not have all her health, but when she is happy I think she
has got everything,'' said Isobel.
Her husband added: ''When you listen to people moaning about ordinary
things in life you smile to yourself and think 'You are lucky'.''
But they both accept that with Susan's care their main priority, they
cannot always be there for their two sons, Stephen, 25, and Scott, 20.
''If one of our sons phones us with something really important, we
cannot always be there for him. Our boys have had to find their own
coping levels. We have been open and honest with our sons, but it has
not been easy for them, especially in the years when Susan did not
sleep,'' said Isobel.
Ironically, just before Susan's disorder was diagnosed, the Allans had
been accepted by the social work department to provide foster care for
handicapped children on a weekend basis. The aim was to give the foster
children's parents respite.
Almost 15 years on, just when they need such a service, it does not
exist. If handed a magic wand, that is exactly what Isobel would provide
-- a community-based respite network.
''There have been real changes in the past 10 years, in a positive
sense. Carers have a higher profile, but there are still horror
stories.''
But the professionals still need to learn to be more human, she feels.
''I don't want people to take care of me, I want them to care for
me.''
</TEXT>
