<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stabat Mater, Usher Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863345</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AFTER Yo Yo Ma's four-hour marathon with Bach on Monday, last night's
90-minute Dvorak epic seemed like a snip. But in fact the Stabat Mater,
written by Dvorak in a period which saw the death of all three of his
children, is an epic: 10 movements, almost all of them slow, a huge arch
of intensity -- from darkness to light -- relieved by a relaxed musical
radiance in the middle.
In truth, the Stabat Mater is an uneven work, some great music which
occasionally flags, is over-extended, and has some moments of plain
gaucherie. That its performance last night was so gripping and
concentrated was down to the glorious singing of the Edinburgh Festival
Chorus, a superb set of soloists, and the conductor John Eliot Gardiner.
The Philharmonia may be London's finest band, but last night,
accompanying this lot, they were not on their best form. Whether it was
down to Gardiner's direction or not, there were too many tentative or
even splodgy entries to be wholly convincing. (A few of these glitches
found their way into the chorus, too, though not quite to the same
effect.)
Gardiner, with immense conducting gestures, found a balance between
austerity and lyrical expression in the work that completely avoided
sentimentality -- a typical coolness from this man, though the sheer
melodic qualities that stream and soar through the work were luminously
highlighted. It may have been slow; it didn't feel like it.
From the Edinburgh Festival Chorus he drew a huge range of dynamics
and colour, from the threshold of audibility to a blazing, full-throated
roar. Their singing in the flowing central movements, which came as a
sort of pastoral relief from the solemnity of much of the work, was
smooth, creamy, and gorgeous. In the last movement they were unleashed,
beginning subdued, then blossoming through a huge crescendo into the
inimitable EFC at full power, a unique sound.
The world is full of starry soloists, but Gardiner's team -- who have
mostly worked with him before -- were brilliant, individually and in
ensemble: Judith Howarth, the shining young soprano, the incomparable
mezzo Anne Sofie van Otter, and the flawless old (young) hands: tenor
Anthony Rolfe Johnson, weightless and floating, and the sonorous bass
Alastair Miles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000112</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000112</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Who cares about the carers?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>COLIN WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863346</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE quite rightly care for people who are profoundly handicapped, sick
and infirm.
The need for such care is obvious but much less obvious is the need to
support those family members who carry the main burden of caring at
home.
Carers are everyday members of the community. They do their shopping
in local supermarkets, often hold down a job, and will have a chat with
friends and neighbours whom they meet casually while out shopping.
But as Carers they are invisible -- yet there are 700,000 of them in
Scotland.
They may care for:
* A newborn child who has severe disabilities;
* A loved one injured in a car accident or who has had a stroke;
* An ageing partner whose behaviour suddenly becomes bizarre;
* A partner who is no longer able to reciprocate your love and care.
Whatever form the caring takes it is a responsibility seldom shared by
others. Little practical help is given to ease the emotional, financial
and practical problems faced by carers.
The Princess Royal summed up the position of carers in our society
when four years ago she agreed to create a new Royal Trust -- The
Princess Royal Trust for Carers.
She said: ''In the course of my work I have often come into contact
with charities which help people who are sick and disabled. But what
about the people who care for the people who are sick and disabled --
the carers? They do not yet have a real identity, so they are often
overlooked and receive little support.''
One of the principal aims of the trust is to provide much needed
practical assistance for carers who without access to respite care or
other practical or emotional support may eventually find that they
cannot continue to perform their caring role.
The Princess Royal Trust for Carers has set a target of establishing
at least one centre for carers in each local authority area in the
United Kingdom.
The centres are the main vehicle of the trust's services to carers.
They provide:
* Information and advice on all issues affecting carers -- benefits,
respite and support services, aids and adaptations;
* Emotional support by providing opportunities for carers to share
their problems with volunteers and professional staff who understand
their situation, thus helping to alleviate isolation and stress;
* Carers centres may also offer help with shopping, transport or
laundry, and access to care attendance schemes or voluntary sitting
services.
In rural areas the centres may also provide mobile advice units and
home visiting.
The trust works in partnership with local authorities and other
statutory bodies, acting as a catalyst to provide the funds needed to
establish a centre which is managed by a local voluntary agency.
Normally for every #1 committed by the trust the statutory bodies
contribute #2. Funding is guaranteed for three years.
Since the trust was formed it has raised more than #5m throughout the
UK. In partnership with Scottish local authorities and health boards the
trust expects to have up to 20 centres established in Scotland by the
end of this year -- all managed by local voluntary agencies.
The cost of each centre varies but the trust often puts up #25,000
annually for three years in order to establish a new centre.
In Scotland there are already Princess Royal Trust Carer Centres in
Glasgow, Edinburgh, Aberdeen, Perth, Orkney, and the Borders. Others
will open soon in Falkirk, Stirling, Dundee, and Lanarkshire.
Raising money to fund carer centres is one of the trust's principal
aims. The other aim is to raise awareness so that there is a greater
understanding of the contribution carers make and of their need for
practical support.
Until recently there was little reference to carers in most documents
prepared by statutory authorities, but thankfully this has now changed.
Carers are beginning to be accepted as people with needs in their own
right.
Any of us could become a carer at any time.
Carers are the backbone of care in the community. They deserve our
recognition and support.
* Colin Williams is Director of Carer Support, The Princess Royal
Trust for Carers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
