<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Playing footsie</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976863347</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MARY BRENNAN bones up on a challenging piece of dance-theatre
THERE are a lot of personal challenges at work under the surface of
Clyde Unity's latest production, Bone. For choreographer/dancer Rosina
Bonsu there's the challenge of speaking lines. For playwright John
Binnie the challenge came in creating a script around a character who is
mute. And for the rest of the company -- actors Stephen Docherty and
Mari Binnie -- there was the prospect of learning not just lines but
choreography. So why make all these difficulties for one another?
In part, it's to do with Binnie's desire to keep Clyde Unity fresh and
forward looking, not merely resting on the formula of past successes.
A company-led community project in Drumchapel some 18 months ago
introduced him to Rosina Bonsu and alerted him to the strength of
movement-based theatre. John Binnie recalls: ''There were these kids
running about all over the place, and Rosina just spoke so quietly and
the next minute they're all going in the same direction. And everything
just came alive. It was wonderful.''
When he started playing about with ideas for Bone -- it's about the
interaction between a lonely, reclusive woman, a grieving widower and
the mute child (a boy) who comes into their lives -- it seemed logical
to make gestures be as significant as words. Enter Rosina, not just as
choreographer but as performer.
''Everyone assumes, of course, that as I'm the dancer, I'll be doing
the silent child,'' says a thoroughly tickled Bonsu: ''But I'm not. I'm
the woman.'' The little boy is, in fact, played by Mari Binnie. The day
I dropped in on rehearsals she was clambering over a rocky outcrop --
composed of bodies: Stephen Docherty's and Rosina Bonsu's to be exact.
Using people instead of inanimate scenery lends a curious uncertainty
to how she scrambles, where she places her feet, her hands. It makes it
look more natural than choreographed.
''Exactly'' chorused John Binnie and Bonsu at the same time . . . ''We
wanted it to look as if the movement was just growing out of the
action'', he continues: ''Not, 'here's a wee dance' and everything just
stops.'' No choreographed set pieces, then, but instead a use of
movement that has been encouraged by daily warm-up sessions before
rehearsals. ''They do body warm-ups with me, I do a voice warm-up with
them'', says Bonsu. ''I'm the director so I just sit back and watch!''
says  John Binnie.
Speaking on stage isn't completely new territory for Bonsu. She has
used text in some of her recent solo performances. But the crucial
difference lies in speaking someone else's words, taking on someone
else's character. ''At first I couldn't see anything about this woman
that I could identify with. But when we were talking about the play, and
what it meant, I found myself thinking, 'Yes. That could be me'''.
She cares passionately about her work, too passionately probably and
I can relate to that. Remembering lines? (She grins here.) ''It's not
like dancing, where if I forget a step I know how to cover myself. I
think we'll all know if I forget the lines.'' She breaks off, miming
panic, mouth open, making gagging noises, no words until she and John
Binnie collapse in fits of laughter. ''Och, Rosina'', he says, ''you
wanted a challenge.''
* Bone alternates with A Little Older at Theatre Workshop until
September 2.
</TEXT>
