<DOCID>GH950816-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A human tragedy is played out in rape and murder as the circle of misery turns full circle. How an ethnic vision became a nightmare</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MLADEN GRBIN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863350</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
In his bloody pursuit of an ethnically-segregated Greater Serbia where
''all Serbs shall live in one state'', Slobodan Milosevic is being
pursued by the outcome of his policy. Mladen Grbin, research associate
in the Institute of Russian and East European Studies, Glasgow
University, reports on the bitter fruits of a violent programme.
THE medium-sized industrial town of Tuzla in the North West part of
Bosnia Hercegovina, together with Sarajevo, are probably among the most
inaccessible places in the world.
The roads into Tuzla have for the last three years or so either been
cut off by besieging Bosnian Serb forces or washed away by the rains.
Only essential goods reach the population of some 700,000 of the
besieged area and, like the dirt tracks, the graves of the 71 young
people killed in the central square are fresh.
Tuzla Airport with the longest runway in former Yugoslavia has
recently received thousands of women in flight from Srebrenica and Zepa.
Encircled by razor wire, with UN soldiers standing guard, they are
scattered across the muddy fields surrounding the airport, and cry for
their menfolk who have been left behind, as they wash and dry the
clothes from the previous night's torrential rain, for the orderly rows
of tents are pegged straight into the muddy fields.
All anxiously await the announcements on the Tannoy with the
occasional name of a male returnee from the hell of Srebrenica.
Most refuse to leave the area so long as there is any hope of their
men returning.
Many however, will be waiting in vain and, according to a report by
the US State Department, there is evidence of mass graves of their
menfolk killed by Karadzic's Serbs with estimates of up to 3000 buried.
A further 12,000 are still missing.
Some who could not endure the waiting game ended the agony by hanging
themselves on the nearby trees.
In his bloody pursuit of an ethnically-segregated Greater Serbia where
''all Serbs shall live in one state'', Slobodan Milosevic of Serbia is
being pursued by the fruits of his policy which is now knocking hard on
his own door.
It all started in the latter part of 1990 with Croatian Serb
barricades in the Krajina region of Croatia and the forcible expulsion
of the Croatian minority in that area, and later it turned into
wholesale destruction of property, mass expulsions in the Baranja region
and Eastern Slavonia, where the city of Vukovar was devastated, and the
Croatian port of Dubrovnik with the whole hinterland of that ancient
city torched to ruins.
From there on to Bosnia Hercegovina, starting with the north eastern
region in the towns of Bjeljina, Zvornik, then further to the South to
Foca, Visegrad and westwards to Brcko, Derventa, Prijedor, Kljuc,
Bosanski Petrovac and many many others.
The method used was to let paramilitary groups, often led by the
infamous Zeljko Raznjatovic, to reign havoc on the civilian population
through murder, rape, and forcible removal, to prepare the ground for
the mopping up operation by the then Yugoslav National Army.
The self-fulfilling prophecy of Milosevic's vision has come home to
roost to his own brethren in Croatia in the recent military victory of
Croatian forces in the successful drive to reintegrate the territory
lost to the rebel Croatian Serbs.
Tens of thousands of civilians and soldiers, streamed out of the
Krajina region in long columns of tractors, cars, carts, laden with
possessions, heading for Bosnia Hercegovina and Serbia proper,
continuing the circle of misery and tragedy.
Despite the continually repeated assurances to the Croatian Serbs by
the Croatian government, only a handful chose to remain in their homes,
some indoctrinated by the propaganda of their own politicians, some in
genuine fear of reprisals, and some with guilty consciences, leaving
behind them their homes and devastation.
During some four years of self-rule, most of the non-Serb property has
been destroyed; churches either razed or desecrated, graveyards
bulldozed, individual graves ransacked.
In Otavica, the birthplace of the Croatian sculptor, Ivan Mestrovic --
one of the original 'Yugoslavs' -- the mausoleum in his honour and the
gallery were ransacked and his coffin opened up and looted.
Judging by what was left behind, there is a sense of an almost
temporary intention to remain.
Factories and industrial plants were also devastated, without which
the local population could not meaningfully think of their future there,
even if they succeeded in their attempt to secede from Croatia.
Some 160,000 of the victims in the newest bout of refugees are now
populating the town of Banja Luka in Bosnia Hercegovina, and are
beginning to settle in towns and villages in Serbia proper and the
former autonomous republics of Vojvodina and Kosovo, which is now
already triggering off another bout of 'ethnic cleansing' and enforced
migration, in this miserable, never-ending circle of suffering.
The document produced by the Serbian Academy of Arts and Sciences in
1986, called the ''Memorandum'', spelling out the necessity for a
homogeneous Serbia, and invoking the myth and legend of the history of
the Serbian people, implied a final solution to the Balkan problem, and
represented the foundation for an ethnically segregated arrangement for
the former Yugoslavia.
The tenets of the Memorandum were eagerly adopted by Slobodan
Milosevic, riding on a nationalist ticket in his pursuit of political
power in an attempt to harness and manufacture the goodwill of his
fellow-countrymen in the creation of the new state of Greater Serbia,
offering this new state to the international community to act as the
guardian of the gate to Europe.
However, instead of being a force of stability in the Balkans, this
faltering notion became unsustainable and the cause of monumental
instability in the middle of Europe, resulting in four million
displaced, more than 300,000 dead, and the potential for further mayhem.
Some 700 Croatian Serbs have been sent to Kosovo, a region of 90%
Albanians, administered by some 50,000 Serbian police through virtual
apartheid, where Albanians have no access to schooling, work or medical
care.
The attempt by Milosevic to repopulate Kosovo with the refugee Serbs
will further inflame an already tense situation, with the potential of
involving Albania proper and some 22% of the Albanians in the former
Yugoslav republic of Macedonia.
In the Machiavellian machinations of the strong man of the Balkans,
the latest refugees are becoming victims of the pursuit of power.
In his effort to legitimise his policy of territorial expansion,
Slobodan Milosevic has exposed his own people to a number of years of
sanctions, to pariah status and, finally, to the status of refugees.
One day, no doubt they will realise that all along their enemy was
within.
</TEXT>
