<DOCNO>GH950816-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Envoys launch peace initiative</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863351</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
American envoys launched a new peace initiative for Bosnia on Tuesday
as separatist Serbs renewed their campaign of ''ethnic cleansing''.
US Assistant Secretary of State Richard Holbrooke met Croatian Foreign
Minister Mate Granic near the Adriatic port of Split and was due to hold
talks with Bosnian Foreign Minister Muhamed Sacirbey.
It was the first meeting between senior US officials and
representatives of the warring sides since Washington devised the new
peace plan after a crushing Croatian victory over Serb rebels last week
in the neighbouring republic of Croatia.
Washington has said the rout of the Croatian Serbs, which sent more
than 150,000 refugees streaming across ex-Yugoslavia, might present an
opportunity for settling the three-year war in Bosnia.
Holbrooke planned to meet Croatian President Franjo Tudjman on
Wednesday and was expected in Belgrade on Thursday for talks with
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic.
He was stopped by fog from landing in the Bosnian capital Sarajevo.
There were no immediate plans to meet Bosnian Serb leaders until they
showed a willingness to negotiate, US officials said.
The latest US proposals had won support from European allies but were
running into criticism already from Russia and Sarajevo.
Russia welcomed the new US efforts to settle the conflict but said
Washington's peace package contained a military element unacceptable to
Moscow.
In London, Bosnia's ambassador, Muhammad Filipovic, poured cold water
on the plan, saying it had no chance of success.
Warring factions are fighting again in central and southern Bosnia and
Bosnian Serbs have begun expelling Croats from their Banja Luka
stronghold.
Fighting appeared to slow in central Bosnia, with reports only of
small arms and machine-gun fire around Donji Vakuf. A major Bosnian army
offensive has been under way in the region.
Croatia threatened war against Serbs in Bosnia on Tuesday if they did
not stop bombarding the area around the historic Adriatic seaside town
of Dubrovnik.--Reuter
</TEXT>
