<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000123</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000123</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Railtrack launches 'mole-hunt'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES MCKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863357</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RAILTRACK executives last night ordered an investigation to unearth
the mole who, for the second day in succession, had leaked sensitive
documents highlighting potentially dangerous shortfalls in the company's
safety procedures.
The original document had warned of another Clapham disaster and
yesterday's pointed to the need for an urgent review of safety policy in
11 key areas, including Railtrack's drugs and alcohol policy.
It questioned whether outside contractors were competent enough in
railway safety methods to be allowed loose on the network.
As the debate raged over safety, Railtrack executives ordered an
urgent review on how sensitive papers were distributed in future, in
addition to instigating the mole-hunt.
The Labour Party was revelling in the embarrassment the leaked
documents has caused both the Government and the company.
Deputy Leader John Prescott seized on them as a new weapon to attack
the Conservative Party's privatisation policy.
''We believe the Government has chosen the wrong priorities in
providing hundreds of millions of pounds to introduce privatisation,
rather than bring in safety improvements,'' he declared.
The growing revelations over lax safety could, he said, lead to the
collapse of its plans. The private sector would be reluctant to invest
in the railways with grave doubts now being raised on the safety issue.
The latest document leaked to the Labour Party makes intriguing
references to a former assistant project manager employed by Railtrack's
Major Products Department in Glasgow.
It also destroyed the company's attempt to dismiss the initial leak as
being merely the personal views of one manager, said Shadow Transport
Minister Henry McLeish.
''Today's report shows the depth of the disarray in Railtrack.
''Project managers operated without full knowledge of the safety
rules, Railtrack is unsure of who is even in charge of private
contractors working on the line, and no-one knows whether Raitrack is
employing competent safety staff,'' he said.
''We are now seeing a shambles within Railtrack. Control is vague and
responsibility is confused.''
Before issuing copies of the second leaked documents to the press,
Labour Party officials had carefully obliterated the name of a project
manager employed by contractors Alistair Graham Associates.
Mr McLeish said the individual's name had been deleted for reasons of
confidentiality.
The Herald has since identified the person involved as Mr Archie
Burleigh.
Mr McLeish declined to elaborate on a paragraph in the report which
said Mr Burleigh had previously worked for Railtrack's Major Products
Division in Glasgow.
The paragraph concluded: ''The circumstances surrounding his departure
from Glasgow are not clear (officially).''
The important message had nothing to do with individuals, Mr McLeish
said. It was to do with overall safety on the rail network.
The memo followed an investigation into a relatively minor incident at
Hitchen, in May last year, when an empty train brought down an overhead
line.
It said that, at the time of the incident, the precise relationship
between Railtrack and outside agencies was neither clear nor available.
''This area of doubt would become a significant and embarrassing issue
in the event of a major rail accident if railway operational matters, or
negligence on the part of agency personnel, caused or contributed to,
the accident,'' the report declares.
''Also, any lack of competence on the part of agency personnel
prevents Railtrack from complying with its Railway Safety Case.''
Among the 11 matters requiring urgent attention was the legal
relationship between Railtrack and agencies, and the competence in
railway operational safety of personnel provided by agencies.
Conservative Party chairman Dr Brian Mawhinney, who until five weeks
ago was Secretary of State for Transport, dismissed the Labour Party's
views as scaremongering.
''The safety regime for British Rail was put in place in 1988,'' he
said. ''Since then, people have worked to improve that safety record and
I believe, as recently as yesterday, Railtrack reassured Ministers, yet
again, that safety was paramount.''
The report leaked to the Labour Party was an indication of just how
seriously Railtrack was concerned about safety.
It was a point adopted by Mr Gil Howarth, Railtrack's major projects
division director. He told BBC radio news that the latest leaked
document was quite rightly a review of an incident that happened in May
last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Death-wish and dogmatism</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863358</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOPEFULLY there are many thoughtful people who do not belong to a
particular political party but who have a strong belief in democracy and
who are concerned with a system which produces 16 years of single-party
rule. The emergence yet again of the death-wish of some Labour
politicians is a depressing sign of the shortsighted nature of political
dogmatism.
With respect to the smaller parties it is apparent that there are two
main blocks of voters who cannot be persuaded to change their allegiance
from right or left and in order to break the current run of victories
which the Tories have enjoyed it is essential for Labour to convince the
centre ground that they have both the ability and the stature to govern.
Under the late John Smith they almost achieved this and with his
tragic death and the succession of Tony Blair at last their time
appeared to have arrived. It is a fact of British politics that the
votes of the uncommitted put in the winning party.
How sad it is then to hear the voices of dissent before there is
anything to argue about. Whatever ideals these objectors may hold they
are wasting their energy without the reality of power.
Whatever they may think of Tony Blair as their leader he has the
respect and the regard of the middle ground and will lead them into a
fairer and more caring society than could ever be achieved by a
right-wing government exhausted by its years in office and emasculated
by 11 years under the leadership of Margaret Thatcher.
Merrik M Burrell,
6 Lewis Drive,
Old Kilpatrick.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pools collector faces #2.3m charge</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE MCKAIN, LAW CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863359</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A COUPON collector is due to stand trial on a charge of depriving a
pools syndicate of a #2.3m jackpot.
The case of Mr Cameron Baxter, 27, has been set down for the sitting
at the High Court in Edinburgh which begins on September 4.
It is alleged that Mr Baxter, of Wallace Street, Stirling, formed a
fraudulent scheme to obtain football pools stake money and to
appropriate it to his own use.
The Crown claims that, in pursuance of the alleged scheme, while
acting as a pools collector between July 24 and September 10 last year,
Mr Baxter pretended to various people in Stirling that he would forward
pools coupons and stake money on their behalf.
The coupons and stake money are said to have related to football
matches played between August 6 and September 10 last year.
The indictment against Mr Baxter states that he induced people to hand
over completed coupons and stake money totalling #242, embezzled the
cash, and failed to deliver the stakes and coupons to Littlewoods.
The result, according to the charge, was that he deprived Gordon
Turner, John Ferguson, Donald McVean, Richard Syme, and Owen Kelly of
winning #2,318,311 for matches played on September 10 for which they had
filled in a coupon.
The Crown has cited 22 witnesses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The voice of a saved life</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863360</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE fact that I am able to write these few lines can be directly
connected to the dropping of the atomic bombs on Japan.
I would ask everyone who disapproves to put themselves in my shoes --
just one of the many thousands of soldiers who had the journey to the
East cancelled after the bombs were dropped.
I was called up in 1941 and survived the journey from Alamein via
North Africa, Sicily, and the D-Day landings in France, then through
Belgium, Holland and Germany in the 73rd Anti-Tank Regiment attached to
30 Corps HQ.
Following VE Day, the preparations for the long journey East began
when I was sent back to Scarborough on a drill and duty course on jungle
warfare training, which led to promotion.
On my return to Germany, all my surviving colleagues had disappeared
-- they were on their way to the Far East and eventually reached Cairo
en route, for the second time since the call-up in 1941.
The sense of relief, for them and for me, when our travels were
cancelled was overwhelming to say the least.
Let there be no doubt that thousands, perhaps millions, of lives,
including mine, were saved when the bombs dropped, and in conclusion may
I remind those of you without warfare experience that self-preservation
and bravery are inseparable.
(Ex Sgt) Bill Young,
74 Beechwood Drive,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Misleading labels</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863361</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ACCORDING to your political reporters the Campaign for Socialism are
Labour's ''traditionalists'' (August 11). This is a description so at
odds with reality as to be Orwellian Newspeak. ''Traditionalist'' is a
strange way to describe a group aiming to equip Labour with radical
policies to move society forward.
A more flattering but equally misleading Newspeak term is also applied
to the Labour leadership -- they are ''modernisers.'' This despite Tony
Blair declaring in a speech to Rupert Murdoch that Labour is ''the
free-trade party''. This nineteenth century liberalism sounds more
''traditionalist'' than any policy being suggested by the left of the
party.
In fact the terms ''moderniser'' and ''traditionalist'' do not
describe political views inside the Labour Party. They are merely
insults which Originate from New Labour's New Right and are designed to
give a progressive gloss to their abandonment of socialist ideas.
Political journalists do their readers no favours by endorsing such
patronising and misleading labels.
Stephen Low,
15 Nimmo Drive,
Govan, Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Half-hearted devolution</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863362</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RUTH Wishart complains about the lack of awareness of the devolution
debate among people in England (August 14).
Devolution is a Labour Party policy -- indeed it is said to be one of
their flagship policies. The responsibility, therefore, for stimulating
debate about Scottish devolution in England surely lies with the Labour
Party and in particular with the Scottish Labour MPs.
It also lies with pelple like Ruth Wishart herself who, as a committed
devolutionist and a respected journalist, must know how to get the
message across.
That all these people have had some years to stimulate this debate and
yet have signally failed leads me to wonder whether this is due to
incompetence or laziness, or is it because those who espouse devolution
have yet to be convinced themselves that it will really work and not
lead to the break-up of the Union.
Whatever the answer, is it not reasonable to deduce that, for the
Labour Party, devolution is just a policy to use in Scotland to fend off
the SNP and in reality their heart is not in it?
Michael Ashmore,
Clydesdale Conservative
and Unionist Association,
129 Hyndford Road, Lanark.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000129</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No apologies</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863363</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS a former POW of the Japanese in South-east Asia who toiled on the
Burma railway I write simply to disassociate myself from the demands for
apology and claims for compensation from Japan by many of its former
PoWs.
It speaks ill for once-great Britain that today it is saying of
yesterday ''It wasn't fair'' while ignoring claims from our imperial
past from peoples marginalised and worse in their own native lands --
such as Maoris in New Zealand from whom the Treaty of Waitangi still
rankles, and Australia's Aborigines.
In life, I was told at my mother's knee, we lie upon ''the bed that we
make for ourselves'' and in the Far East that we did not make our bed
sufficiently well has not been the fault of our erstwhile foe -- an
enemy that, whatever other traits he may have had, proved himself in our
own jargon to be ''a bonny fighter'' as those who fought their way back
through Burma from Kohima, and our American Allies who took Okinawa and
hardly a prisoner in the taking of it will testify.
In Malaya and Singapore, unhappily, British troops without battle
experience found themselves up against battle-hardened troops to whom
the whole idea of surrender was anathema, and were bewildered and
outwitted, not because individual soldiers lacked courage but because
real leadership from Malayan Command was almost entirely absent.
David Rowan Henderson,
Choc-Ard, Ardfern,
Argyll.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Blades of helicopter killed piggy-back girl</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863364</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN picked up his four-year-old daughter to carry her on his
shoulders and lifted her into the still-revolving blades of his
helicopter, an inquest heard yesterday.
Businessman Nicholas Hawkings-Byass told the inquest into the girl's
death that the tragedy happened minutes after he landed the two-seater
helicopter at his family's weekend home in the Cotswolds.
Bristol coroner Paul Forrest recorded a verdict of accidental death on
the girl, Lydia. She died of head injuries.
Mr Hawkings-Byass, who was not at the hearing, said in a statement
read to the inquest that he landed and switched off the engine.
He went through the routine procedures for closing down the engine,
and as he collected his briefcase and business papers his daughter, who
had already been on a short flight with him, approached him and asked
him to carry her.
Mr Hawkings-Byass, 41, of Tregunter Road, Chelsea, west London, said
in his statement: ''I put my briefcase down to pick her up with both
hands to put her on my shoulders.
''What happened next is not totally clear. I am not sure if I got her
on to my shoulders. She then fell forwards on to the ground and, as she
lay there, the colour drained from her cheeks.
''I did not feel any impact, although I realised something awful had
happened.
''I was facing away from the helicopter. I was not aware of the rotors
revolving. There was no wind noise.''
He and Lydia were facing away from the helicopter, and were about six
feet from the fuselage.
He called to his wife, Clare, for help, and together they drove Lydia
to hospital at Bourton-on-the-Water. She was later transferred to
hospital in Cheltenham, where she died three days later on July 2.
No members of Mr Hawkings-Byass's family were at the hearing, which
consisted largely of witness statements read by a coroner's officer.
Mr Hawkings-Byass, managing director of NBH Ltd, an agriculture
aviation firm based in London, said in his statement that he had been a
qualified helicoptor pilot for seven years.
He had flown to his Cotswold home from Luton Airport.
</TEXT>
