<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000133</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000133</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Heroes who beat mine menace</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863367</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN an excellent article extolling the achievements of British
scientists in their contribution to the war effort, Sir Samuel Curran
detailed their skills in inventing some of the most advanced scientific
techniques (August 10).
By contrast he remarked on very simple devices which also proved
effective. One such was the coil carrying an electric current fitted to
ships, producing an opposing magnetic field which largely neutralised
the vertical field of the ship.
At the start of the war the menace of the German magnetic mine was
very real, ships being sunk in large numbers. However, the mechanism of
the mine was unknown.
By good fortune one was dropped, not as intended in the sea, but on
the mudflats at the mouth of the Thames estuary.
Two naval officers volunteered to dismantle it. They did so, step by
step, knowing that each subsequent step might mean certain death, but
they succeeded, and because of their effort it was revealed that the
mine was actuated by a vertical magnetic field.
Hence the simple expedient of fitting ships with the ''degaussing''
coil was put into practice.
Scientists played a magnificent role in the war, but the heroic action
of these two officers defeated the menace of the German mine -- once
mooted as Hitler's secret weapon.
W Jackson,
57 Nethercliffe Avenue,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000134</DOCID>
