<HEADLINE>English only at tourist office</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863368</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I HAVE just spent a few days driving around the north of our country,
exploring the vast area above Inverness for the first time. Of course,
the weather was very kind to us, and that helped, but the scenery and
the welcome we enjoyed are unforgettable.
At every town where we chose to stay overnight, we called at the local
tourist information office and within minutes we were fixed-up with
superb accommodation: so simple, so friendly, and so efficient.
However, I noticed that in all the tourist offices I visited our
friends from Europe were expected to communicate in English since there
was obviously no-one who could converse in German, French, Spanish,
Italian, or whatever, despite the fact that, from what I saw, a great
number of non-English speakers turned to the local tourist office for
help.
It seemed to me that some knowledge of German or Italian was more
vital than a knowledge of English.
We stayed in a hotel in Thurso and the barmaid made a very telling
remark: people from Glasgow and Edinburgh think Inverness is the north,
but Germans, French, and Italians know that's not true.
Iain McDougall,
16 Agnew Avenue,
Coatbridge.
</TEXT>
