<DOCNO>GH950816-000136</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000136</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tourist board aims to hit late-season gold</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863370</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S largest industry-wide promotion aimed at bringing visitors
north of the Border this autumn was launched nationwide yesterday.
The Autumn Gold initiative, which involves more than 500 businesses,
aims to increase late-season tourism by up to 7%, generating more than
#5m of income for the Scottish economy in its first year.
Mr Ian Grant, the Scottish Tourist Board chairman, was in London to
announce details of the initiative, which is aimed at stay-at-home Scots
as well as people in the south.
At the recently opened Stakis Edinburgh Airport Hotel, his colleague,
Mr Gordon Adams, director of planning and development, said it was a
great step forward.
Mr Adams said the campaign was a direct result of the national tourism
strategy launched last year, and added: ''There has not been as good
collaboration in the past as there might have been between the public
and private sectors.''
He said the Autumn Gold campaign, in which more tourist attractions
than ever will be open, fulfilled two objectives -- ''seasonability and
collaboration''.
A total of #1.25m is to be spent on promoting the campaign, including
leaflets and television and cinema advertisements.
The promotion gives discounts on air and rail travel, special car hire
rates, special offers on accommodation, deals on visitor attractions,
and special offers on Scottish crafts and giftware.
Autumn Gold offers will be valid from September 29 to November 30 and
a number -- 0345 511411 -- has been set up for people to order their
free Autumn Goldcard.
For those who are not convinced, little-known autumnal facts are
provided:
* Average rainfall in Edinburgh in October and November is
consistently lower than in July and August.
* Lerwick, Shetland, will have seven minutes more daylight than London
on October 1.
* Visitors will find agapanthus and watsonias, flowers native to South
Africa, in bloom in the West Highlands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000137</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000137</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SNP call for introduction of film tax incentives</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JONATHAN NORTHCROFT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863371</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TAX incentives for film makers to capitalise on the current spate of
Scottish blockbusters were demanded by the SNP yesterday.
At the launch of a party fact-finding initiative, arts and
broadcasting spokesperson Ms Roseanna Cunningham warned that unless tax
relief schemes are offered to the industry, big budget productions will
desert Scotland, causing ''real jobs and revenue'' to be lost.
The launch highlighted Braveheart, opening in the UK on September 8.
Shot initially in Scotland, the film relocated mid-production to
Ireland, which offers substantial tax breaks for film production.
Ms Cunningham said: ''Despite its Scottish subject and the great
enthusiasm for Scotland among its production team, substantial parts of
the production were based in Ireland.
''The reason for that was purely financial but it was the Irish film
industry that reaped the profit and the benefit of additional work and
training.''
Following the introduction of tax incentives in Ireland in June 1993,
the total Irish film budget increased by more than 400% to #47.1m over a
twelve-month period.
In 1994, filming brought Scotland a record #22.9m in direct spending
due to titles such as Rob Roy, Braveheart, and Mary Riley.
However, Ms Cunningham said Scottish film workers remained in ''a
variable and insecure environment''.
She added: ''We are not just talking about artists but ordinary people
in bread and butter supporting industries such as technicians and
hoteliers.''
SNP chief executive Michael Russell said current UK film policy was
geared towards supporting Pinewood, Shepperton, and Ealing in the south
of England.
The SNP consultation will involve gathering opinion from the industry
and attempting to quantify the number of workers involved in film and
spin-off industries.
However, the Scottish Film Production Fund, while welcoming the
proposal of tax breaks, said the decision to relocate Braveheart
mid-production had been one of planning and not finance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tackling a crisis</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863372</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE returned from dining out to find two fire engines parked beside wet
pavements in front of our hotel in London. A motley throng of foreigners
was assembled outside a hotel two doors away and chefs and kitchen staff
covered the pavement between.
No concern of ours, we thought, and made for our hotel front door only
to find it locked and the building in darkness. It was Bailey's Hotel
that had been on fire and their guests were being directed to the
Gloucester Hotel next door.
Chaos could have followed, but it didn't. Both hotels were prepared to
cope with such an emergency. It was found that the fire which had
started in the kitchen had only burnt the ground floor, with some smoke
and water damage to the first and second.
We were assembled in the Gloucester Hotel's large foyer where free
drinks and sandwiches were served and announcements made. A babel of
excited voices vied for attention in English, German, Spanish, and
Japanese but the manager made himself heard.
As the five floors of Bailey's Hotel were to be cleared one at a time
the management assembled all guests with rooms on the first floor. Staff
with torches helped guests up the darkened staircase and into their
rooms to pack their belongings, then helped them out of the hotel with
their luggage. Interpreters helped the foreigners overcome any
confusion.
Clearing all five floors took some time and as we waited we shared
settees and sympathy and communicated by sign language and the few
foreign words we knew.
All the Bailey Hotel's guests were suitably housed in the Gloucester,
Forum, or Forte hotels by the early hours of the morning.
From start to finish the management of all the hotels involved acted
with streamlined efficiency, and gave every possible assistance to their
multi-lingual guests. It was a good example of the legendary British
sang-froid when faced with an emergency.
Lilian Bernard Levi,
62 Castle Court,
Newton Mearns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000139</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000139</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Such a common orchid</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863373</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COMMON Spotted Orchid lives up to its name. It has spotted leaves and
is common. It is one of the most abundant orchids in Britain and in the
Glasgow area it grows in 76 out of 90 of the 4km squares (see Wild
Plants of Glasgow, Mercat Press, 1992).
It colonises a great variety of habitats including bings of both coal
and lime, disused railways and other undisturbed waste ground, roadsides
including motorway embankments, gardens, pasture, and marshy ground.
There is no surprise whatever that it colonised a roundabout at
Linwood (August 11). It is a pity it was obliterated there but its
weediness will ensure that it will invade other sites.
The picture you publish does not show this ''very rare'' species. It
does not show any orchid but Marsh Woundwort, a common member of the
Labiatae (Mint family).
Coralroot Orchid (not Coalroot Orchid) currently has 65 sites in
Britain and not merely two as you reported.
It is right that many orchids need to be conserved. No fewer than six
out of 15 species of orchid have gone extinct in the Glagow area in the
last 200 years because of habitat destruction.
However, Common Spotted Orchid is one of the most resilient.
Conservationists ultimately risk doing their just cause harm by
promulgating misleading, inaccurate information.
Dr J H Dickson,
Reader in Botany,
Glasgow University.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000140</DOCID>
