<HEADLINE>Parakeets</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863374</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I READ with interest John McMillan's letter regarding parakeets seen
in the Newlands area of Glasgow recently (August 11). Curiously, the
RSPB regional office in Glasgow has received quite a number of calls
regarding sightings of parakeets, mainly from the South Side of Glasgow
and Newton Mearns.
The sightings were of single birds, not a pair.
The birds are more likely to be escapees from a captive environment
rather than wild birds venturing further north.
From the description given, the birds are probably not the ring-necked
parakeets which escaped from captivity and are now surviving and
breeding in the wild around the London area.
It is very unlikely that Newlands parakeets will be able to breed this
far north; however with such glorious weather, who knows!
Parakeets are omnivorous and would be able to survive quite happily on
a diet of seeds, fruit, and the odd insect (I wonder if they're fond of
midges).
Jean Burns,
Regional Administrator,
Royal Society for the Protection of Birds,
Kelvin Campus,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
