<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Vision of a stagnant land to set alarm bells ringing</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALEX SALMOND</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863377</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN I was a lad I served a term for the Government Economic Service
in its northern-most outpost, the economic and statistic section of the
Department of Agriculture and Fisheries for Scotland.DAFS was located in
Chesser House, a building later to fall on hard times as Lothian
region's chief collection point for the poll tax.
Apart from devising a new forecasting technique for the Scottish sheep
flock by counting the number of 23 buses lumbering up Gorgie Road in any
half-hour period, I remember my spell in DAFS for giving me a first
opportunity to contribute to an HMSO publication. This was an estimable
and serious journal entitled Scottish Agricultural Economics. It was
published annually and well received by a dedicated student readership
in the agricultural colleges who saw within its pages useful information
to short-circuit their theory exams.
As a young economist I was somewhat in awe of this official digest
although sensible enough to realise that the rest of Scotland was not
necessarily queuing at the bookshops awaiting publication of Scottish
Agricultural Economics.
Government publications have changed somewhat over the intervening 15
years. The covers are glossier, the contents lighter and perhaps less
reliable. However, in the normal course of events publications such as
Social Trends or the Employment Gazette don't hold up too many front
pages.
Even in the silly season there are usually better news stories about.
Admittedly there might be the occasional tabloid flutter when Social
Trends finds that Scots actually drink less than the English or that
some quiet unsuspecting town has the highest illegitimacy rate in the
country.
However, the Employment Gazette normally has its thunder stolen by the
monthly jobs figures and is consulted rather than reported. Therefore it
took some nifty work by The Herald news desk to generate genuine
front-page news from last week's Gazette.
The article in question concerned projections of economic activity
rates across the nations and regions of the United Kingdom for the next
decade as well as some comparisons over the past 10 years.
The results make pretty dismal reading for Scotland. First the
retrospective analysis indicates that Scottish economic performance has
not been what it was cracked up to be.
In the years 1984-94 the Government statisticians found that the
growth in numbers of the labour force economically active in Scotland
was a full point behind the UK average of 4.6%.
Nothing too much to worry about there except when you remember that
these were the years when the growth in oil and gas output might have
been expected to power the Scottish economy forward to a new and higher
plain of activity.
In addition, this was a period which saw the Scottish unemployment
rate dip below that of the UK average for the first time in living
memory. What the Employment Gazette tells us is that this happened
because the number of available workers was lower not because economic
activity rates were higher.
However, it is the projections for the next 10 years which should
really set alarm bells ringing. Here the Scottish figures stand out like
a sore thumb by showing a modest decline while the UK average is set to
rise by a projected 6%.
No other region or nation is showing the same trend as Scotland while
East Anglia is forecast to spurt forward by a full 13%. In contrast, the
Government's own statisticians picture Scotland as an area of stagnant
economic activity.
Now, of course, there are cautionary notes to be made about such
projections. They are largely population-based and the Scottish
forecasts come from a different source than those for England and Wales.
They will also assume a constant policy framework throughout the
forecast period.
However, the fact that Scottish population growth continues to lag
behind the rest of the UK is, in itself, a symptom of relative economic
decline.
To argue therefore, as the Scottish Office Junior Minister Raymond
Robertson seemed to, that we should take no notice whatsoever of these
findings, is to raise complacency to an art form.
The Scottish economy has some massive strengths compared to the rest
of the UK. We have a better mix of industry, a higher rate of
productivity, and a much stronger export performance. We have both
natural and comparative advantages which other countries would give
their eye teeth for.
However, it is foolish to believe that we have been punching anything
near our economic weight within the straitjacket set by Westminster
rule. Since 1979 the overall Scottish growth rate has been a tad below
2%, identical to the UK average and simply pathetic by international
standards.
If the Employment Gazette is anything like correct, the next 10 years
might well be rougher with a long, slow relative decline chilling the
economic marrow of the nation.
When the Unionist parties warn of the supposed dire consequences of
Scottish independence, they omit to mention what will happen if we are
foolish enough to leave things as they are. Perhaps the Employment
Gazette has given us a clue about the economic consequences of the
Union.
The Scotland which is forecast is a stagnant land which will miss
every economic opportunity, duck every political challenge, until
finally there is nothing much left but shame to gnaw.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>'Unwanted' bone test available in Scotland</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863378</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAJOR advance in the detection of the bone disease osteoporosis is
now available in Scotland -- where it was discovered several years ago
by scientists at Rowett Research Institute, Aberdeen.
The test, which could make global screening of women feasible, has
been developed by an American company because of an initial lack of
interest in Britain.
The simple and cheap urine test will pinpoint those likely to suffer
from the disease, which affects 40% of women aged more than 50, and
could allow action to be taken to prevent the condition developing in
likely victims.
Osteoporosis mainly affects post-menopausal women and in sufferers the
structure of the bones becomes more fragile and prone to damage. Minor
injuries can cause bone fractures and the spine can be compressed
leading to a loss of height and eventually considerable pain.
The test costs #10 but demand and new technology is expected to cause
a price drop.
The Rowett holds the patent for the new assay method and it could
bring considerable revenue to the institute to help fund further
research.
Dr Simon Robins, head of the bone research group at the Rowett, said
the basic research was conducted 12 years ago when osteoporosis was not
on the agenda.
Their research into bone biochemistry to determine what gave bones
their strength revealed substances in bones which were not present
anywhere else and could provide good ''markers'' for testing.
The results of their work were published and the researchers went
around numerous British companies trying to persuade them to invest in
further research for the test.
''Sadly it was the same old story and no-one in Britain seemed
prepared to take the risk,'' said Dr Simon Robins, who made the
discovery.
However, a venture capital group in California saw details of their
work and the test has been developed by Metra Biosystems Inc of Mountain
View, California.
Dr Robins said a biochemical test developed in Denmark had recently
been highlighted on television but the Scottish test had the advantage
of being more specific.
Professor Philip James, director of the Rowett, said: ''Because it can
affect more than one third of women, osteoporosis is a major area for
international research at the moment.
''In economic terms, the effects of the disease cause a major drain on
the NHS resources in Britain but, even more importantly, it can have
major personal consequences for patients and their families. Obviously
we are delighted that such a significant step forward has come from
basic research at the Rowett Institute.''
Dr Robins said the Scottish researchers were now working on possible
treatment methods which would be more specific and would avoid the side
effects of hormone replacement therapy.
He said such a treatment was still a few years off.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000145</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000145</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Neighbours rally for drug brothers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863379</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEIGHBOURS on Mull have pleaded with a court to treat two middle-aged
brothers with leniency, after they admitted growing cannabis.
The High Court in Glasgow yesterday heard that Robert MacGillivray,
45, had 105 plants in a makeshift greenhouse made of car windscreens and
another 17 plants in his garden.
Over the hill, his brother Kenneth, 41, had 17 of the plants in his
walled garden.
The brothers, of Airds Croft, Pennyghael, have admitted producing
cannabis between January and July last year and Robert has admitted
possessing the drug with intent to supply it.
The court heard Robert used cannabis for health reasons and gave away
the surplus to friends.
His counsel, Mr Ian Sharpe, handed the judge a letter from islanders
asking for leniency.
Robert was highly regarded by the local community and his caravan door
was always open to his friends, Mr Sharpe said.
Mrs Fiona Reith, prosecuting, said a tip-off sent police after the
brothers on July 14.
Mr George Gebbie, for Kenneth, said that although the brothers'
caravans were separated by a hill, they seldom saw each other.
''Kenneth has a different life style and lives like a hermit,'' he
said.
Mr Gebbie said the plants were for Kenneth's own use and there was no
suggestion that anyone else received any.
Lord Cowie continued the case to the High Court in Edinburgh on
September 5 for reports. He also continued bail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000146</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000146</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stagg marries and hurries off to see Batman</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863380</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COLIN Stagg, the man cleared of murdering Rachel Nickell, married his
''angel from above'' yesterday -- then rushed home to watch Batman.
Almost a year after he was acquitted of the Wimbledon Common killing,
Mr Stagg tied the knot with 26-year-old care worker Diane Beddoes, who
started writing to him while he was in jail awaiting trial.
His best man and childhood friend Dave Butler, 30, from Twickenham,
south-west London, said: ''It meant a lot to him because no-one was on
his side. Everybody thought that he had done it. For someone to befriend
you when you're a man who's innocent was just like an angel from above
coming down.
''I think he deserves everything he gets because he's been through a
lot of hell. I just wish both of them a lot of happiness.''
Miss Beddoes, dressed in a flowing two-piece ivory dress, with a
silver medallion on a blue ribbon round her neck, said: ''I'm madly in
love and very happy.''
Lee Ashley, a friend who lives near their flat in Roehampton,
south-west London, said: ''Colin's not got a nerve in sight. I was with
him at seven in the morning. He was sitting in his shorts watching the
funnies on TV.''
Miss Beddoes added: ''He wants to get home for Batman.''
However, Mr Stagg, in an open-necked white shirt, dark waistcoat and
trousers, was less forthcoming.
Smiling as he led his bride through a barrage of photographers after
the register office ceremony in Wandsworth, he answered questions
tersely -- yes, it was the happiest day of his life and no, they had no
plans for a honeymoon or children at the moment.
Before the ceremony, Mr Stagg, 31, and his bride sat with their arms
around each other, joking with guests, while a parks police officer
guarded the waiting room door.
Despite Mr Stagg's acquittal, the murder of 23-year-old Rachel
Nickell, who was stabbed to death in front of her young son in July
1992, has haunted the couple's life together.
They were arrested on the common, a short walk from their south west
London home, in January this year after a fight with a man who was out
walking his dog.
Miss Beddoes admitted possessing a cosh which she used when her fiance
appeared to be to be getting the worst of the fight and Mr Stagg
admitted threatening the man with an axe.
Miss Beddoes received a six-month conditional discharge and Mr Stagg
was put on probation for 12 months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000147</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000147</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Partnership successes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863381</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SO far so good. When the Scottish Office announced partnership schemes
in four of Scotland's most deprived areas seven years ago the response
was cautious and coloured by the fact that the local authorities
involved were hardly on speaking terms with Government officials in
Edinburgh. Nor was there much enthusiasm over the framework set down for
the scheme, and particularly what was regarded as over-optimism about
the possibilities for co-operation between private and public bodies.
Many of these worries have been resolved at least partly, and an
interim report on the degree of regeneration within the four areas
reports successes in some respects. Partnership schemes were intended to
improve sectors such as housing and amenities, environment and image,
but also  to attack the problem of long-term unemployment. Much of the
housing stock in the chosen areas has been improved. This effect has
been enhanced by better amenities such as the long-awaited new shopping
centre in Castlemilk. For these and other reasons the image of the four
housing estates has been raised and, as the Scottish Office rightly
pointed out yesterday, the proportion of people happy to live in them
has risen and the proportion wishing to leave has fallen.   These are
excellent achievements and should not be underrated. They have been
possible because the private sector has been willing to be involved
positively in housing schemes and also, and perhaps more importantly,
because the local communities have been at the centre of matters, have
been listened to, and have been enabled to get on with much of the work
themselves. The researchers who compiled the interim report are surely
right when they say that getting so many organisations to work together
was an achievement in itself and that the benefits which have resulted
would not have come otherwise. Nevertheless, it would be wrong to ignore
the fact that evidence on the intractable problem of unemployment in the
four areas does not give a clear picture or much reason for hope.
Overall employment did not improve, and in the Whitfield estate in
Dundee the improvement could be ascribed to new owner-occupiers. The
simple fact is that tackling deep-seated unemployment requires
considerable financial investment and that, as the researchers found,
the cost is consistently underestimated. Partnership schemes are clearly
worthwhile and should be extended, but realistic financial support must
also be in place.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000148</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000148</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SAS link to double murder is ruled out</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863382</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLICE yesterday dismissed a claim by Sinn Fein that an SAS undercover
unit could have shot dead ramblers Peter and Gwenda Dixon, whose brutal
murders six years ago are still unsolved.
The couple's bodies were found on the isolated Pembrokeshire coastal
footpath in West Wales, in the same area where a big IRA arms cache was
hidden.
Although detectives believe robbery was the most likely motive, a
terrorist link has never been ruled out.
Speculation was revived on Monday after Sinn Fein's Belfast office
issued a statement in response to fresh inquiries by a newspaper.
A party official suggested that the Dixons may have been shot by
mistake by soldiers lying in wait for an IRA unit to pick up buried
weapons and explosives.
However, Dyfed-Powys police, who are still searching for the killer,
said not a single piece of evidence had been found to support such an
allegation.
''We would point out that the arms cache was not found until some four
months after the murders of Mr and Mrs Dixon,'' said a spokesman. ''The
file has never closed on this case and we still want to hear from anyone
with information.''
Since the clifftop killings at Little Haven, Dyfed, in June 1989,
Welsh detectives have liaised several times with RUC colleagues on
possible IRA connections.
Two IRA terrorists were arrested in December that year after they
attempted to remove buried explosives at Newgale, two miles from the
scene.
Although questioned about the Dixons' deaths, Damien McComb and Liam
O'Dhuibhir, now serving 30 year sentences for terrorism, were never
linked to the murders.
Mr Peter Dixon, 51, a businessman and former RAF officer, and his wife
Gwenda, 52, a secretary, were blasted at close range with a shotgun.
The couple, from Witney, Oxfordshire, had visited the Pembrokeshire
National Park every summer for 15 years to walk and watch birds.
A piece of fishing rope was used to tie Mr Dixon's hands behind his
back before he was shot in the face.
His wife was killed a few feet away and was probably near the edge of
cliffs when she was shot.
The bodies were then dragged behind a carefully made screen of bracken
and roots. The murder weapon was never found.
Detectives are still searching for their key suspect -- a scruffy
cyclist in shorts who they believe used Mr Dixon's bank card to withdraw
#300 from cash machines at three local banks.
Although an IRA or drugs smuggling link has never been ruled out,
senior officers remain convinced the couple were victims of a callous
and calculating armed robber who singled them out as they reached the
only secluded wooded area of that section of footpath.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000149</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000149</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Head of BBC2 defends 'drama of the 1990s'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863383</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BBC2 Controller Michael Jackson last night defended a #66m autumn
schedule featuring programmes which include violence, bad language, and
drug taking.
''This is drama that reflects modern life in the 1990s and I am very
proud of it,'' Mr Jackson said.
One production is Loved Up, a sensual drama starring Lena Headey, in
which she falls in love with actor Ian Hart and joins his night-time
world.
Screen Two dramas include Jimmy McGovern's award winning Priest, a
vivid, uncompromising journey into the soul of a tortured Catholic
priest.
The Performance series of studio drama features Zoe Wanamaker, Colin
Firth, and Stephen Dillane, in D H Lawrence's The Widowing of Mrs
Holroyd, exploring life in a mining community in 1914.
Factual programmes include My Secret Life, in which people describe
episodes of wife swapping and a gay priest talks about the pressures of
living a double life, and End of Innocence, which describes the onset of
the Aids epidemic.
Mr Jackson said: ''We are the only terrestrial channel to have
increased our viewer share and we are now equal with Channel 4.
''We are more accessible and the channel is working very well, with
72% of the population watching something on BBC2 each week.
''This is the channel which screened Middlemarch and Martin Chuzzlewit
and if we also screen drama which reflects modern life then I am very
proud of that.''
Comedy and light entertainment also feature in the 500 hours of new
programming, which Mr Jackson called a schedule of ''innovation and
breadth''.
Many stars are involved in the BBC2 launch, which includes many
one-off dramas to be screened on Saturday nights, featuring such as John
Hurt, Alfred Molina, Tom Wilkinson, Cathy Tyson, and Helen Mirren.
Mr Jackson said the Saturday night dramas, which feature writers of
the calibre of Jimmy McGovern, Howard Schuman, and Harold Pinter,
''emphasised BBC2's commitment to the single drama''.
The new schedule also includes comedy from Steve Coogan, Mrs Merton,
and Vic and Bob.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000150</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000150</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No end in sight for hill fires. Lord Lindsay sees need for cash help</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS HIGHLAND CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863384</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Office will consider any plea for extra resources for the
hard-pressed Highland and Islands Fire Brigade, which has spent the past
two-and-a-half weeks tackling one moorland fire south of Inverness which
the local fire chief believes will only be completely extinguished by
heavy snow.
The Environment Minister, Lord Lindsay, made this commitment yesterday
as he visited the scene of the fire near Daviot which has spread over an
area of 15 square miles, with peat burning to a depth of six feet and up
to #60,000 worth of trees destroyed.
It has already cost Highland Fire Brigade around #36,000, although the
landowners are having to bear the #700-an-hour costs of using
helicopters.
The Army has been alerted that the brigade might not be able to cope
if there were other forest fires as the good weather continues in the
Highlands. It is already making an all-terrain vehicle available to the
Highland brigade.
Lord Lindsay praised the efforts of the firefighters so far and said
that, in the first instance, the claim on resources would go to the
local fire authority then to its constituent authorities.
He added: ''When the fire services are resourced, the contingency is
always there for the unexpected but what is not known is to what extent
the unexpected is going to use resources.
''That is why there is a procedure for the local authorities to
approach the Scottish Office with an application and if such an
application was made we would consider it very carefully.''
The Minister would not speculate on how favourably the Government
would look on such an application, stressing instead that the immediate
priority was to get the fire out. The question of resources could be
examined later, he said.
Firemaster Robert Gordon said: ''I am serious that it will take a good
snowfall to finish this fire. Forty-eight hours of heavy rain would
certainly help but it looks as though there's going to be more hot
weather and wind. That is the problem. Every time we get it dampened
down, the wind fans it up again.''
Mr Gordon said the cost to the brigade was largely because of the
nature of its staffing.
''There is only one full-time station in the Highlands, at Inverness,
with 70 full-time staff. There are another 400 retained personnel in the
other larger towns plus 1000 volunteers.
''Every time we have been sending firefighters up here from Inverness,
we have had to call out retained men from Nairn to cover smaller fires
in Inverness. They get a call-out fee then an hourly rate. This has been
stretching the budget.''
He said Army back-up remained an option that the brigade could use if
demands increased. Already call-outs were running about 34 a day, an
increase of 50% on last year.
Mr Gordon said the question of extra resources would be raised at the
next meeting of the Fire Board next month.
The Fire Board chairman, Wester Ross Councillor Norman Cameron, said
he would back any call for extra resources given that the fire service
was having to deal with one of the worst droughts in 100 years.
He was not only looking to the Government for extra resources:''The
other thing is that the people who have the privilege of owning huge
tracts of land should do more financially and with manpower to reduce
demands on the brigade.
''These large fires cost an inordinate amount of public money and
there already is public money going in to regenerate woodland, etc. But
every case on its merits. We don't want small crofters having to foot
the bill.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000151</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000151</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Profile raised in fight to save pool</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863385</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CAMPAIGN to save North Berwick pool -- one of only three remaining
outdoor pools in Scotland -- intensified last night with the formation
of a group to co-ordinate opposition to closure.
The pool is due to close in two weeks but objectors have sought
outside sponsorship and have raised a petition with more than 1000
signatures.
Mrs Norma Loudon, one of the campaigners, said: ''My feeling is that
it would be extremely short-sighted to close the pool. It is a fantastic
tourist asset and impacts on the town's economy.''
She said campaigners wished to work with East Lothian District Council
to explore ways of keeping the pool open in summer. Because of the
recent hot spell, it was doing its best business as closure loomed.
''It has never been marketed as an attraction in any of the tourist
literature and there is nothing else to bring together youngsters of all
ages in North Berwick,'' she added.
Mrs Loudon said the pool could be retained and lessons learned from
the remaining outdoor pools at Gourock and Stonehaven.
According to the council, which plans to open an indoor pool and
upgrade the leisure centre in North Berwick next year, the outdoor pool
costs #72,000 a year to run.
A council spokesman said although visitor numbers rose modestly to
4000 last month, this contrasted with 3500 a week at a new indoor pool
at Musselburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000152</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000152</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>City is faced with soaring council tax</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH, LOCAL GOVERNMENT CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863386</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SERIOUS gap which could send council tax bills soaring next year has
emerged in the finances of the new City of Glasgow Council.
The grave implications of the #79m shortfall will be spelled out at a
seminar for all councillors to be held next week.
If this size of financial hole had to be filled entirely from council
tax payments, it would mean increases in bills of up to 70%.
This would clearly be unacceptable, as it would raise average bills
above #1100, and Glasgow's Labour leaders will now argue the city's case
strongly in the Cosla/Scottish Office working group, which deals with
local government finance.
The difficulties have been highlighted with the drawing up of notional
budgets for the current year for the 29 new unitary councils, along with
individual spending assessments on which the Government bases its
distribution of grant, and also its capping criteria.
The new Glasgow council's notional budget totals #805m, but the
council's spending assessment, on which grant is based, is just over
#726m.
Reorganisation has forced the ''disaggregation'' of regional council
budgets to the new unitary authorities, and the process has produced a
number of winners and losers.
If present mechanisms are allowed to operate, another loser is the new
Dundee City Council, which faces a budgetary gap of 12%, compared to
Glasgow's 11% (#79m).
The new Glasgow council's Labour leader, Councillor Bob Gould, said he
was ''seriously concerned'' about the financial picture which had
emerged.
He claimed the Government had pushed through reorganisation as quickly
as it could and had to recognise the difficulties this had produced.
Councils could not be blamed.
So far, the Government seems determined that it will not come up with
any new money.
Instead, a transitional scheme will be discussed between Cosla and
Scottish Office officials, which would redistribute available resources
for next year in a way which will help councils like Glasgow and Dundee.
The discussions will be difficult, as the scheme would mean some of
the winners -- like East Renfrewshire -- losing grant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000153</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000153</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Old Firm brings in betting kiosks</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863387</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SPECTATORS at Celtic Park and Ibrox Stadium will be able to place bets
on the outcome of matches and likely goal-scorers at special betting
facilities inside the grounds from early this season.
Track betting licences, allowing bookmakers to operate at various
points in the grounds, were yesterday granted by Glasgow District
Council's licensing committee to both teams.
The decision means the clubs will join several other top Scottish
clubs who have installed betting facilities at their grounds since
Scottish Football League rules were altered in May last year.
Bookmakers are now allowed to take bets on football matches inside
grounds with club approval.
This followed the success of similar betting facilities in England,
where 36 clubs have them installed.
The licensing board granted the licences to Celtic and Rangers under
the Betting, Gaming, and Lotteries Act (1963) following site visits last
week.
Yesterday they heard there had been no objections from building
control, environmental health, police or fire service officials.
The licensing committee also granted a licence to Queens Park Football
Club for the use of betting facilities at Hampden Park.
The betting facilities at Celtic and Rangers' grounds -- eight kiosks
in Celtic Park's two existing stands and 11 kiosks and four counters in
various parts of Ibrox Stadium -- are to be operated by Ladbroke, which
runs almost all betting facilities at Scottish grounds.
Those clubs which have them include Hearts, Hibernian, Aberdeen,
Motherwell, Partick Thistle, and St Johnstone.
The company, which is the world's biggest bookmakers, is responsible
for all costs regarding the setting up and running of the kiosks or
counters and pays the host club a commission based on turnover of the
betting facilities.
Ladbroke yesterday estimated that Old Firm betting facilities would
create extra work for about 56 employees, including supervisors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000154</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Protester's death 'may have been deliberate'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863388</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANIMAL rights protester Jill Phipps may have deliberately thrown
herself under the wheels of a truck carrying veal calves, police
yesterday told an inquest into her death.
Superintendent David Whitehouse, of Warwickshire Police, who
controlled the policing on February 1 when Miss Phipps died, told the
first day of the Coventry hearing that he could not be responsible for
her actions.
He said he had seen her run in front of the lorry ''perhaps with her
hands raised, then slip or possibly deliberately fall''.
Miss Phipps, 31, was crushed to death by the lorry as it carried
calves into Coventry Baginton airport to be flown to the continent.
The inquest jury was shown video film taken by police as a convoy of
two police vans and the truck drove at about 20mph towards the airport.
Miss Phipps and around eight other protesters were shown running
around in the road attempting to halt the truck by standing in front of
it and trying to chain themselves to it.
Police had been criticised for allowing the protesters to break
through a cordon of officers towards a moving vehicle and for failing to
stop the truck until they had been moved from the area.
Superintendent Whitehouse, who watched the video of the moments before
Miss Phipps's death and the final impact, said: ''I saw Miss Phipps run
up to the front of the lorry and appear to stand in front of it, perhaps
with her arms raised, and then slip or possibly deliberately fall.''
Miss Phipps, a lifelong animal rights campaigner and vegetarian, who
had received a two-year suspended prison sentence for her direct action
in the past, died almost instantly after her spine was severed by the
force of the lorry's wheel driving on to her chest.
Her mother, 70-year-old Nancy Phipps, another veteran campaigner,
broke down and wept as she told the court her daughter had been a
sacrifice made in the fight to stop live exports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000155</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000155</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shotts thrown out of football</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863389</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LEADING junior club Shotts have been thrown out of Scottish football.
The decision of the Central League to expel them was backed yesterday at
a special SFA appeal meeting.
The league had taken the decision over claims that they had filed
inaccurate medical reports showing that they did not have enough players
to take part in a game last season.
However, Shotts was given some slight relief, as the SFA has decided
that the Central League should decide on a set period of expulsion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000156</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000156</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rail vision and reality</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863390</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SAFETY on Railtrack is either inadequate and unlikely to be
satisfactory for at least 18 months, or a robust safety management
system is in place and the issue of safety is paramount. These
propositions are so contradictory that someone must be wrong. Our bet is
that Mr Jack Rose, Railtrack's track manager in charge of safety
assessment and the author of the leaked report warning of another
Clapham disaster, is likely to know more about safety than Transport
Minister Steven Norris, former Transport Secretary Dr Brian Mawhinney,
and sundry Railtrack loyalists all rolled together. The row over safety
has left the Government's privatisation plans hanging by a ragged
fingernail.
It is worth reminding ourselves of these plans for they encapsulate
the shambles of a privatisation policy which exposes the gulf between
the vision of ideologues and objective reality. The end of last month
saw the deadline for bids for the first three passenger franchises.
Formal, binding bids have to be submitted by October and the first
handover to the private sector will take place around Christmas. The
franchises, which vary from seven to 10 years, will begin on April 1
next year and by that time the Government hopes to have privatised some
51% of passenger services. The timetable sounds impressive but it is
unlikely to be any more accurate than one derived from an examination of
the entrails of a chicken. The City is full of experts who think that
rail privatisation is a horrendously risky venture, and the safety
debate has sharpened their anxieties. The leaked memo by Mr Rose appears
to refer to the problem of court appearances by Railtrack, presumably in
the aftermath of an accident. Legal liability is the last thing
investors want to hear about, especially when coupled with warnings of
inadequate safety procedures. The franchise bidding process is secret
but the number of groups interested in the original franchises is
certainly less than expected. Labour will publish its response to rail
privatisation in November and the possibility of a Labour Government has
heightened interest in this document. At the very least it must propose
substantially tougher regulation than that envisaged by the present
Government.  Better still, it should propose ways of restoring a
publicly owned and accountable rail network. Then we will have the
safety which the public deserves and the hope of an integrated network
which British industry so urgently needs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000157</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000157</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A Word . . .</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976863391</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
. . . in your ear, Michael. Again you made the right noises about
listening yesterday when you invited responses to your consultation
paper on giving parents an #1100 voucher to buy pre-school education for
their children. You said: ''We will work in partnership across the wide
range of interests because it is important to get the right framework
for Scotland's distinctive needs, while devolving choice right to
individual families.'' That D-word again. But let's talk about choice.
Now #1100 is #1100 in anybody's book. Choice is different: #1100 is a
tidy sum to top up your child's nursery fees -- which may be #4000 a
year -- if you and your husband hold down good jobs and live in a nice
area. But if you live in a housing scheme and you take your voucher to
the local authority nursery you'll find that it doesn't even meet the
cost of a basic full-time place. This playing field is not level,
Michael. In Lothian region's case the difference would be more than #100
per head, in Strathclyde's about #300. Of course authorities would not
turn you away. Michael, your paper says: ''In the public sector, local
authorities would not be able to charge more than the voucher value, but
could spend more per place if necessary.''
What's this? Councils spend more? If they do, would you cap them?
Please tell us, because this is not just about making up the difference
to protect the service and maintain quality. Michael, your paper hopes
that authorities -- which, let us remind ourselves, provide the lion's
share of pre-schooling -- will be able to increase their provision by
using the voucher to offset the cost of each additional place. How, when
each new place will cost perhaps #300? Are we being unimaginative in our
coverage when we ask if this (pious?) hope amounts to a tacit admission
that the value of the voucher is insufficient? When we wonder if you see
the dreaded EU words before you as you target those who may think the
most of your vouchers, and thank you for introducing them: Election,
Upcoming.
To be continued
</TEXT>
</DOC>
