<HEADLINE>Tribunal rejects women's race claims</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863392</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO women who charged a local authority with racial discrimination
because they failed to make a shortlist, had their claims rejected by an
industrial tribunal in Edinburgh, yesterday.
The tribunal said one of the women, Ms Neelam Bakshi, was not
considered for the position because she was a Strathclyde Regional
Councillor.
Ms Pramila Kaur, of Howth Terrace, and Ms Bakshi, of Broughton Road,
both Glasgow, applied to Falkirk District Council for a post as
women's/equal opportunities officer but neither was shortlisted and the
job went to a white woman.
The tribunal was told the district council, whose workforce is just
less than 1700, employs just two people from ethnic minorities and had
no specific target for improving the statistics.
Both Ms Kaur and Ms Bakshi suggested that, on racial grounds, they had
each been treated less favourably than the other candidates who had been
shortlisted.
A total of 38 applications were received for the job and all of the
candidates, with the exception of Ms Kaur and Ms Bakshi, were white. The
seven women shortlisted were of UK origin.
The tribunal was told the shortlisting process was carried out by Mr
Bernard McCallum, the council's assistant director of personnel. With
regard to Ms Kaur, he decided she did not meet one of the essential
criteria for the job -- degree standard or equivalent.
Mr McCallum said Ms Bakshi, a Strathclyde Regional Councillor
representing Glasgow's Maryhill/Summerston ward and with a Glasgow
University degree and strong inter-personal skills, met two of the
essential criteria.
However, he did not regard her as meeting the third criteria, which
was appropriate experience in the field of women's/equal opportunities'
issues.
In its findings, the tribunal said that, with regard to Ms Kaur, Mr
McCallum did not exclude her from the shortlist on racial grounds, and
added: ''She did not meet the first of the essential criteria, in that
she did not hold a degree or equivalent qualification.''
When it came to Ms Bakshi, the tribunal stated that the inference it
drew ''was that Mr McCallum rejected the applicant because of her status
as a Strathclyde Regional Councillor''.
The tribunal dismissed the complaints from both women that they had
been racially discriminated against.
</TEXT>
