<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No VJ-Day truce in the war of words</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863393</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE VJ anniversary was marked yesterday by a statement of remorse from
the Japanese prime minister, an angry reaction from Allied veterans, and
a virtual boycott of a ceremony on the River Kwai.
The ''Peace March'' over the Kwai was attended by only three Allied
veterans and their comrades at home were also outraged by the latest
apology from Japanese prime minister Tomiichi Murayama for his country's
wartime atrocities.
They reacted angrily to his insistence that there was no question of
paying compensation for their suffering.
Mr Murayama's VJ-Day statement had the weight of the Japanese
Government behind it as the wording was cleared by all three partners in
the ruling coalition.
For the first time in a public speech about the war, a Japanese prime
minister used the word ''apology''.
''I express here once again my feelings of deep remorse and state my
heartfelt apology,'' he said in a brief statement.
A spokesman for the Royal British Legion Scotland said members he had
spoken to yesterday regarded Mr Murayama's statement as ''words in the
wind'' and ''not from the heart''.
Mr Tom McGowran, secretary of the Scottish Far East Prisoners of War
Association, which has 600 members, said that no form of apology would
be regarded as recompense for the appalling things that had happened to
inmates in the Japanese prison camps.
Mr Tom Wright, chairman of the Scottish area of the Burma Star
Association, said Mr Murayama was probably sincere in apologising but
''this doesn't represent the views of his cabinet or the nation''.
Mr Alex Bain, secretary of the Edinburgh branch of the Burma Star and
former chairman of its Scottish area, gave his personal view that
insistence on receiving an apology should be dropped.
''It has become a bit of a farce. If you have suffered serious
maltreatment, I don't think an apology 50 years later would make any
difference.''
Pressed about compensation for victims of prison camps, Japan's
ambassador to London, Mr Hiroki Fuji, said, ''We apologise for what we
have done to them during the war,'' but added that the legal question of
prisoners of war had been settled by the San Francisco peace treaty of
1951.
Royal British Legion veterans and relatives held a VJ- Day service
outside the Japanese-owned County Hall in London yesterday.
Wreaths were also laid at a service at Britain's highest war memorial,
a cairn of stones on the summit of Ben Nevis.
</TEXT>
