<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sting in the tail of hot weather</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863394</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WASPS are lurking in every crack and corner, nesting in lofts, in
garages, under eaves, down holes. They have been tempted to breed at a
frenetic rate in the hot sun, and driven to snatch a bite at normally
covered Scottish flesh.
Environmental health officers yesterday reported an unprecedented
number of complaints about wasp bikes. In Edinburgh, Aberdeen, Glasgow,
and Dundee, calls are more than double that of last year and many
district councils have been forced to draft in additional staff.
Maintenance officers in Edinburgh, where there are 350 calls coming in
every day, have been taken from cemeteries and parks to don protective
clothing and hound the wasps from their papery lairs.
The district's environmental health director, Mr Richard Carson, said:
''In 30 years, I've never come across anything like it. You see wasps in
the weirdest places. I've been chased up the Royal Mile wearing a floral
tie. You could say there was a group of people in Edinburgh who have
been secretly praying for freezing weather.''
In Glasgow, teams of pest control officers and eight additional staff
are blitzing a different area of the city each day. Council pest control
officer James Prescott admitted that the strategy meant some people were
waiting for up to 10 days before a nest was destroyed. His department
had taken 6000 calls this summer -- around 300 calls every day.
He proffered one theory for the wasp explosion. ''There's a chap who
worked here for over 30 years who said he rarely recalled seeing wasps
in the 1950s. Since then, the city's been smokeless and the wasps have
appeared in cycles. He thought there are more wasps now because the air
is cleaner.''
Worrying news then for those breathing clean North Sea air in
Aberdeen. With the discovery of nests prompting more than 80 calls a
day, the real sting for Aberdonians is that a visit from the city
council pest control unit will cost private householders #29 plus VAT.
</TEXT>
