<DOCNO>GH950816-000161</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000161</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Monklands on Tory chairman's 'loony' list</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER, POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863395</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DR Brian Mawhinney, Tory Party chairman, said yesterday that he
planned to include a visit to Monklands in his summer tour of ''loony
left'' Labour controlled councils.
He intends to ''listen personally to what people on the ground think
about the sort of treatment that is being handed out to them by those
who are claiming to be renewed and reborn, but who are in practice
following exactly the same old policies with the same old ideology in
the real world that we have always associated with the Labour Party''.
At a news conference, he listed huge debts run up by Labour councils
before heading today for North-east England, where he will try to
contrast the ''new Labour'' image presented by Mr Tony Blair with what
he calls the reality of Labour rule on the ground.
His catalogue of debts run up by seven leading Labour councils,
including Liverpool and Bristol and some London boroughs, showed that
many were deeper in the red than some Third World countries.
He said the councils evidently hoped that, if Labour came to power, it
would allow them to write off this debt. He challenged Shadow Chancellor
Gordon Brown to say whether he would permit this or not.
Birmingham's debt is #1280m, more than that of Malawi. Greater
Manchester's debt is #1170m, about the same as Paraguay, and costing the
city taxpayers #196 a minute to service the interest.
Lambeth has a debt of around #900m, more than Lebanon which has
emerged from years of civil war. It also has the country's worst council
tax collection record, taking in only 56% by March of this year.
Islington has debt of #880m, more than Sierra Leone, costing the
equivalent of #1212 in annual interest payments for all the borough's
householders, who include the Blairs.
Liverpool's debt of #800m is as much as that of Haiti and Barbados
combined.
Newcastle has debts of #440m, as much as Algeria which has a hundred
times as big a population. South Tyneside's debt of #355m, more than
that of Cambodia, costs #60 a minute in interest payments.
Dr Mawhinney said: ''These figures are startling evidence of the price
which has to be paid for real Labour government. Real Labour comes with
a hefty price tag attached.''
</TEXT>
