<DOCNO>GH950816-000162</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000162</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sacked matron settles before tribunal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863396</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE board of directors at the troubled East Park Home and School for
profoundly handicapped children in Glasgow has agreed an undisclosed
''financial settlement'' with the former matron, who was dismissed
earlier this year.
An agreed joint statement, issued yesterday, confirmed the settlement
on the eve of an industrial tribunal in Glasgow into the circumstances
of the sacking of Mrs Eleanor McCreadie, 55, who was matron of the home
for eight years.
Evidence was expected to have been heard in Glasgow today and
tomorrow.
The statement, on the home's headed notepaper, said: ''Mrs Eleanor
'Lynn' McCreadie left the employment of East Park on March 22, 1995, in
circumstances which East Park have recognised constituted unfair
dismissal.
''There was, and is, no doubt that Mrs McCreadie has at all times
acted in the best interest of the children entrusted to her care.''
The statement added that both parties had agreed that no further
comment should be made on the matter.
Mrs McCreadie's sudden dismissal, for no apparent reason, from her
post at the charity-run home in Maryhill, where she earned an estimated
#25,000 a year, provoked an angry response from politicians, doctors,
and unions. The home declined to go into detail about the sacking,
although it conceded professional misconduct was not involved.
Later it emerged that the new general manager, Mrs May Henderson, was
involved in a relationship with the man who carried out a staff review
at the home -- Dr Kenneth McAlpine, a geriatrician at Paisley's Royal
Alexandra Hospital.
</TEXT>
