<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Muted response to mining plan details</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863398</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN open-cast coal company that wants to develop a site close to the
villages of Ormiston and Elphinstone in East Lothian was given a muted
reception at a public meeting held last night to discuss the plans.
As The Herald revealed earlier this week, an application to mine 202
acres by Slamannan-based William Grant (Mining) Ltd, has been lodged
with East Lothian District Council.
Another company has submitted plans to work another area close by --
and more than 200 people gathered for an information meeting.
A spokesman for Grant outlined plans which, he said, would include
working a 12-hour shift from 7am on weekdays, with no heavy lorries
passing through either village.
There would be no loss of rights of way, and after five years the land
would be restored to agricultural use, he said.
The meeting was told that even if the council rejected the
applications, the companies could appeal to the Secretary of State.
Mr David Carlisle, chairman of Campaign for the Ormiston Environment
(COE), warned that a number of issues had to be addressed.
Local people would have to consider the impacts of noise, dust, visual
intrusion on the landscape -- and the economy, Mr Carlisle said.
</TEXT>
