<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000165</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000165</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Eight years for youth who killed woman on crossing</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863399</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TEENAGER James McGregor, who hit a 79-year-old grandmother on a
pelican crossing while driving a stolen car, was given eight years
detention and banned from driving for life yesterday.
The Shogun Landcruiser hurled widow Jean McGillvary almost 50ft and,
as she lay dying from her injuries, l8-year-old McGregor raced away
pursued by angry motorists.
The High Court in Glasgow heard that McGregor, a youth ''with a
fascination for joyriding'' shook off his pursuers, jumped out of the
Landcruiser, scrambled over a barbed wire fence, and fled over fields.
Witnesses identified him from photographs and, when he was arrested at
his home at Downfield Street, Tollcross, Glasgow, police found the
jacket he had torn on the fence.
McGregor admitted the reset of the stolen vehicle, driving it
dangerously, and causing the Mrs McGillvary's death in Mill Street,
Rutherglen, and failing to stop.
Temporary Judge John Horsburgh was told that, two-and-a-half months
before the accident, McGregor had been released on licence from another
sentence involving reckless driving and car theft.
He ordered McGregor to serve the two-and-a-half months before the
eight-year sentence starts and told him: ''Your record clearly shows
that your fascination for cars is a very dangerous one which reached its
climax in this tragic accident.
''There is a need to protect the public from people like you who not
only steal vehicles but drive them in a way which is reckless or
dangerous.''
Mr James Scott, prosecuting, said that Mrs McGillvary, of Croftend
Avenue, Croftfoot, Glasgow, lived with her son, and she also had two
daughters. She had good health and eyesight.
About 9.30am that day, a taxi driver had to brake suddenly when
McGregor shot out of Johnstone Drive, in Rutherglen, and across a dual
carriageway in Mill Street.
He then drove up to a pelican crossing, where another vehicle was
stopped with the lights at red, and struck Mrs McGillvary.
Witnesses said he seemed to slow down momentarily before driving away
chased by other motorists.
Mrs McGillvary died from multiple injuries in hospital shortly
afterwards.
Mr Scott said that, during a taped interview with police, McGregor
described how he went for a run to Rutherglen.
McGregor said: ''I suppose I tried to go through a red light. There
was a motor sitting there but I never saw the old lady. When I looked
back, I saw there was someone lying on the ground.''
Mr Gerald Carroll, defending, said the accused's parents had separated
three years ago and, in the past, McGregor had been put under the
supervision of the children's panel for truancy and other offences.
Mr Carroll said: ''He has an absolute fascination for cars coupled
with an irresistible urge to drive them.''
Mr Carroll said he had never known any accused to show such genuine
anguish and remorse and he was so stricken while on remand that the
authorities considered calling in a psychologist for him.
* An eight-year-old girl is recovering in hospital from serious injury
after being struck by a stolen car in Uphall, West Lothian.
Samantha Maxwell was walking along Middleton Road with her 11-year-old
brother when the girl was struck after the car skidded, pushing her
against a tree, and causing serious leg and pelvic injuries.
The occupants of the car then ran from the scene.
Lothian and Borders Police said last night that two men had been
arrested in connection with the incident. They were expected to appear
at Linlithgow Sheriff Court today.
</TEXT>
