<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000166</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000166</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Yarrow's bid for frigate contract fails to save jobs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863400</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW warship yard Yarrow yesterday lodged a multi-million pound bid
to build three frigates for the Royal Navy -- and at the same time
warned its workforce to prepare for redundancies.
A delay in the Ministry of Defence's timetable for ordering the
frigates has meant that even if the Clyde yard is successful, workers
will have to be laid off before then because of a gap in the work at the
yard.
Yarrow Shipbuilders Limited is in a straight fight for the three new
Type 23 frigates with Vosper Thorneycroft from Southampton. Its previous
competitor was Swan Hunter on Tyneside, which has since closed. Now
Vosper, which has experience in building minehunters and Type 42
frigates, is keen to become Yarrow's main competitor.
Yarrow's ability to build the frigates is not in doubt after it
successfully completed six of the ships -- all named after dukes -- for
the Royal Navy, and is currently working on a further three. The fear,
however, is that Vosper will bid an unrealistically low figure for the
work simply to keep its yard busy.
YSL management has warned in the past that there would be redundancies
if it did not win orders, but frequently was successful, thus avoiding
any significant job losses.
However, in the past, the MoD ordered the frigates on a fairly regular
timetable. Now, with the Treasury trying to limit defence spending, the
timetable has slipped, meaning job losses are inevitable.
Ironically, YSL's yard at Scotstoun has rarely looked busier. Two
ships for the Malaysian Navy, plus frigates Somerset and Grafton, have
been launched and are either tied up alongside the yard or are in dry
dock being fitted out.
As weapons systems and electronic systems become more sophisticated,
increasing amounts of work are done on the ship after the basic shell
has been launched.
That means only one frigate, Sutherland, is still being built inside
the yard. Thus workers involved in steelwork and other heavy jobs
concentrated at the start of construction are more at risk from job
losses.
Some may be transferred to fitting-out work but that can only have
limited application.
No figure has yet been put on the job losses as management is still in
discussions with the unions but, with 3000 workers, large orders have to
be found on a regular basis if such a payroll is to be financed.
The unions are unlikely to oppose some job losses as they realise
people will not be kept on if there is no work. However, they will want
to be convinced that management has explored all avenues for
transferring workers to other tasks.
* Meanwhile, Glasgow Development Agency has stepped in with a #100,000
grant to help avoid redundancies at the Upper Clyde's only other major
shipbuilders, Kvaerner Govan.
The money will help retrain 250 employees to give them skills more
appropriate to the requirements of modern shipbuilding.
The GDA initially became involved when it emerged that Kvaerner would
have to sack staff and then re-employ them, if they were going to
qualify for Government training funds.
The GDA can be more flexible in its approach and came up with the cash
to avoid redundancies. The agency feared that if the workers were sacked
then some of them would leave the shipbuilding industry.
Mr Dave Donald, GDA's head of training, said yesterday: ''Our
contribution will allow the company to stabilise its workforce during a
period when it normally has to lay off a large number of its
highly-skilled men, with the risk of losing some of them.''
</TEXT>
