<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000167</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950816-000167</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man sees whole family die in blaze. Chip-pan fire tragedy as father prepares meal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863401</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DISTRAUGHT father was being consoled last night after a chip-pan
fire caused a blaze which claimed the lives of his entire family.
Taxi driver Alun James was preparing an early-morning meal when the
fire started at his terraced house in Workington, Cumbria.
His wife Andrea, 30, died along with her four children -- Andrew, 11,
Graeme, five, and Katrina Bottrell, three, all from Mrs James's previous
marriage, and the couple's 16-month-old daughter Glynis.
Hours after yesterday's fire, Mr James returned to the scene of the
tragedy and wept when he discovered a child's shoe in the charred
remains of his house.
He had steeled himself to enter the remains of his house in Church
Road in the coastal suburb of Harrington.
Leaning against a wall, he stared at the house as friends tried to
comfort him.
Neighbours walking by stopped to give a few words of comfort. An
elderly woman patted him on the arm as he shook his head in disbelief.
He then walked slowly into the house, which had blackened outer walls
and windows. Ten minutes later, Mr James came out, his face twisted in
grief.
In a joint statement last night, Cumbria police and fire service said:
''An initial investigation of the fire indicates that it started in the
kitchen of the house near the cooker.
''The fire was discovered by Mr James, who was in the house at the
time and had started to prepare a meal on the cooker. Mrs James and the
four children were all in bed at the time.''
A fire service spokesman said it had been a chip-pan fire.
Mr James rushed out of the house through the front door as the fire
spread, and neighbours raised the alarm.
Firemen wearing breathing apparatus recovered the bodies, said
Assistant Divisional Fire Office John Threapleton.
Last night, Mr James was being comforted at the home nearby of local
parish priest, Father Dyfrig Harris.
Prayers were said for the dead at a morning mass at St Mary's Roman
Catholic Church.
The service had been scheduled because of VJ-Day. A celebration to
mark the event 50 years ago, planned for last night, was cancelled as a
mark of respect.
Mr Threapleton later describing Mr James' visit to his said: ''He was
very distressed. He saw the child's shoe, picked it up and wept.
''All our sympathies go out to him. To lose one member of your family
is bad enough but to lose five is appalling.''
He said Mr James did not look around the house but stayed on the
ground floor ''out of the public view''.
Mr Threapleton, who was among the first officers to arrive at the
scene, said: ''There was very little we could do.''
The house did not have a smoke alarm but he added: ''In the
circumstances of this particular incident, I don't think it would have
made a lot of difference.''
Neighbours said the family had lived at the house for three years.
Widow Eileen Crowe, who lives opposite the house, said: ''They were a
lovely family. The children were always very well dressed.
''I will always treasure the memory of the little girls in their
bright summer frocks in the hot weather,'' Mrs Crowe added.
She described seeing the two little blonde girls being carried out of
the house in the arms of firemen. She also saw Mrs James being brought
out.
Another neighbour spoke of seeing flames shooting out of windows at
the back of the house.
''I hope I never see anything like it again,'' he said.
''There was a mass of flames. There was nothing anyone could have done
because of the fierceness of the blaze.''
An inquest will be opened today at Whitehaven.
* A woman died when her clothes caught fire as she stood beside a gas
cooker yesterday. The elderly woman, who has not been named, was
engulfed in flames in the kitchen of her home in Glastonbury, Somerset.
</TEXT>
