<HEADLINE>Tourism tries touch of lingua franca</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863403</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE traditional Glasgow greetings of hullawrerr and howsitgaun will
soon be available in five languages, thanks to an innovative training
course which has been launched in the city.
The course has been developed to give people involved with tourists a
basic grounding in French, German, Italian, Spanish, and Japanese and
give them an interest in learning more.
Already a wide range of companies, including Marks and Spencer, Arnold
Clark, and Stakis Hotels, have sent people to the one-day courses held
by Glasgow Tourism Training Unit.
The course offers key phrases in the five languages spoken by the
majority of tourists visiting Scotland and also gives a guide to the
cultural minefield which is involved in dealing with people from other
countries.
The unit's Stella Callaghan said: ''There is nothing that makes a
foreign tourist feel more welcome than a few words of greeting in their
own language. It may be a simple good morning and how are you before
making it clear you are not fluent, but often that is enough.''
She added: ''It was an idea we had been kicking around for quite some
time but the established language trainers said it would not work. So
with the help of some multi-lingual trainers that we brought in, we have
got the courses under way. They have been very popular and we have many
more planned.''
The unit was particularly pleased to attract Marks and Spencer, which
normally keeps all its training in-house, and noted that Post Office
Counters had sent staff along as part of the general improvement in its
image.
A whole range of people, from bus and taxi drivers to those in the
retail trade and hotels, are taking an interest.
The courses are funded by Glasgow Development Agency.
</TEXT>
