<HEADLINE>Nurseries reject voucher plan</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY MCBAIN, EDUCATION CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863404</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDUCATION groups reacted with anger last night after the Government
set out its stall for creating a marketplace in pre-five schooling in
Scotland.
It envisages local authorities, private nurseries, and the voluntary
sector competing for vouchers worth #1100, which the parents of mainly
four year olds will use to ''buy'' pre-schooling for their children at
the place of their choice.
In addition, in a Scottish Office consultation paper published
yesterday, it floated the possibility of giving the vouchers varying
values, with more going to parents in areas where provision is more
expensive -- such as the big cities -- and less to those in smaller
communities.
However, authorities, and independent nursery and playgroup
representatives, expressed concern about the voucher scheme being
bureaucratic, and divisive when the pre-five sector should be working
together.
Mrs Moira Ferguson, national executive officer of the Scottish
Pre-School Play Association, said: ''Introducing vouchers means there is
competition rather than integration.
''It could be that groups will vie with one another for four year olds
clutching vouchers but, if this is the way ahead, we will do our best to
make it work.''
Mrs Valerie Fotheringham, West of Scotland secretary of the Scottish
Independent Nurseries Association, said: ''The Government knows nursery
education is an election issue and it is trying to do something about
it.
''The three sectors should work in partnership on education and
training and sharing ideas because there is so much to offer in child
care. Vouchers could encourage the wrong kind of competition.''
Mrs Judith Gillespie, convener of the Scottish Parent Teacher Council,
said: ''The market does not work in education for supplying services.
Parents want local authority provision and the money should go straight
to authorities to help them develop proper provision.''
Strathclyde region's director of education, Mr Frank Pignatelli, said:
''We have developed a high-quality service which is quite expensive to
run. There is a question about whether we could maintain that. We would
also worry about the increased bureaucracy involved in the scheme.''
The Government has invited private companies to tender bids for
administering the scheme, which will involve issuing and redeeming the
vouchers.
It is not clear if the bureaucratic costs will come out of the annual
cost of the vouchers, which will be about #70m.
In 1997, the Government plans to send vouchers through the post to
parents of eligible children. They would exchange the vouchers for
places at an establishment of their choice.
It believes #1100 is enough to meet the cost of three terms of
high-quality pre-schooling in the year before a child would start
primary education.
It expects the value of the voucher to ''buy'' a part-time place in a
nursery and up to a full-time place in a playgroup with ''suitable''
education.
Parents would be able to top up the value if they used the voucher in
the private or voluntary sector but local authorities would not be able
to charge more than #1100. The nursery or playgroup would accept
vouchers and redeem them for cash.
About 64,000 children a year are likely to be eligible for a voucher.
According to the latest data, more than 35,000 four year olds, or about
56% of the total, were in local authority nurseries last year.
Authorities spend about #39m a year on pre-five education and the
favoured funding option put forward in the paper is to take the sum from
local government, with authorities getting it back as parents produce
their vouchers at their establishments.
The remaining #31m will meet the cost of vouchers for the other 44% of
four year olds, many of whom do not receive any pre-schooling.
The #1100 has been criticised as insufficient not only in relation to
the cost of pre-school education but also to the capital costs of
providing new facilities for the anticipated upsurge in demand.
The Government hopes authorities will offer more places by using
surplus school accommodation.
</TEXT>
