<HEADLINE>After 50 years the wounds fail to heal as a terrible episode is marked by a boycott and words of remorse. A bridge too far for all but three veterans</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW CHANT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863405</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Kanchanaburi, Thailand.
It's very natural for
the former PoWs
not to come. I know
their hardships, I
witnessed them. I
also did some very
inhumane things.
Takashi Nagase,
ex-military police
ATTEMPTS to forge a final reconciliation between Allied prisoners of
war and their former Japanese enemies ended in farce yesterday as all
but three Allied veterans boycotted a ''Peace March'' over the River
Kwai.
Organisers were expecting hundreds of British, Australian, and Dutch
former PoWs to march across the bridge over the River Kwai. They were to
be greeted by an equal number of Japanese to shake hands in the middle.
At the stroke of midday, two British and one Australian veteran were
greeted by only five former Japanese Imperial Army soldiers who were
willing to atone for their past brutality.
The veterans quickly shook hands and some hugged each other. The
event, watched by more than 30 journalists, was over.
One of the British veterans, Mr Trevor Dakin, a former corporal from
the 5th Battalion of the Bedfordshire and Hertfordshire Regiment, has
lived in Kanchanaburi for the last eight years and has long forgiven his
former enemies.
He said: ''If other veterans object to this event that's their
problem. If they'd met the Japanese that I have, they would understand.
It's not the Japanese people, it's their government.''
According to Mr Dakin, 75, yesterday's apology from Japan's Prime
Minister Tomiichi Murayama did not go far enough: ''If the whole
government would make a formal and comprehensive apology and pay us
compensation for the days we worked for them, they could end the hatred.
The Germans paid trillions after the war but the Japanese -- not a
penny.''
The other Briton, Mr Dudley Cave, a Unitarian Church minister from
Golders Green, London, said he had not been tortured by the Japanese and
had no ill feeling towards them.
''I'm very much in favour of reconciliation. I've come to Thailand 22
times since the war ended and began to lay my ghosts to rest about 10
years ago. The bitter PoWs shout a lot and receive a lot of publicity
but I think there are many who do want to reconcile with the Japanese.''
The Japanese delegation was led by Takashi Nagase, a former
interpreter for the Kempetai (Japan's military police), who recently
admitted to the BBC that he had taken part in torture sessions.
Takashi said: ''It's very natural for the former PoWs not to come. I
know their hardships, I witnessed them. I also did some very inhumane
things. I was forced to take part and do wrong.
''Many of the PoWs cannot forgive. It's OK. I understand, but I hope
they will accept my apologies. I have already given up on my government,
they are heartless. Our government must apologise with compensation but
I'm very pessimistic.''
Earlier yesterday, a commemoration service was held in the grounds of
Kanchanaburi's allied war cemetery, home to the ashes of around 7000
Allied PoWs who perished making the ''Death Railway''.
Mr Christian Adams, Britain's ambassador to Thailand, made a short
speech, although an embassy source said even he was there largely
because of the high-level Thai representation.
General Chavalit Yongchayudh, Thailand's Defence Minister, presided
over the ceremony which was also for the first time attended by Japan's
ambassador to Thailand, Takashi Onda.
Mr Adams said: ''The approach of reconciliation is clearly a
controversial one but this is a unique moment in history, 50 years after
the end of the war. It is understandable that people have mixed
feelings. Our decision to come was made at the last moment.''
Mr Adams also pointed out during a short speech that a separate
British Christian service of remembrance would be held on Sunday with a
strong emphasis on those who died on the railway.
All Allied PoWs have been invited but the Japanese have not.
Thirty thousand Britons were brought to Kanchanaburi by the Japanese
after the fall of Singapore in 1942. They were forced to work in
appalling conditions forging a link for Japanese war supplies between
Thailand and Burma.
The line began construction in July 1942 and was finished with the
help of 300,000 Asian forced labourers, one year and three months later
in October 1943.
The track, more than 280 kilometres long, was said to have claimed a
life for every sleeper. Around 16,000 allies including 6500 Britons died
of malaria, dysentery, and other tropical diseases during its
construction. As many as 80,000 Asians, mainly from Indonesia, Malaysia,
and the Philippines also died.
In Manila, Philippine President Fidel Ramos and Senate leaders have
hailed Japan's apology for its actions but it was dismissed by survivors
who were used as sex slaves. About 20 women, staging a protest outside
the Japanese embassy in Manila, said they were not satisfied with it.
The group is demanding #150,000 compensation for each victim.
In Seoul, South Korea said yesterday it would wait and see what Japan
does following the apology. An official statement added: ''We want the
Japanese Government to make serious efforts to thoroughly reveal the
truth of history and have a proper understanding of history.''
* Lord Slim, whose father, the late Field Marshal Viscount Slim, led
the British Army in Burma, spoke yesterday of his disappointment at
Japan's apology.
Lord Slim, who fought in Burma, said he would rather the Japanese had
not tried to apologise at all than to fall short of clear remorse.
''Our Prime Minister has worked jolly hard for some time now to get
the Japanese to make some gesture of apology,'' he said. ''But whether
the apology we have had so far is enough is for the British Government
to say. But the one word that is always missing is 'sorry'.''
</TEXT>
