<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour MP says party is copying Thatcher. Blair accused of 'conning' electorate</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER, POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863406</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MR Tony Blair was accused yesterday by a Labour MP of attempting to
''con'' the electorate as the tide of discontent with his style of
leadership threatened to swamp the carefully constructed image of a
united party.
Blyth Valley MP Ronnie Campbell told Radio Newcastle that Mr Blair was
trying to con the south of England electorate by stealing Margaret
Thatcher's ideas.
He accused Labour of ''taking Thatcher's ideas to try to con the
people in the south that we are an electable party.''
The tough 52-year-old Geordie ex-miner said: ''I could not care less
if the Shadow Cabinet turn around and kick us in the teeth for what we
are saying, they are power mad.
''They have got it into their bloody heads that Labour is unelectable
unless it goes down this social democratic road. That is absolutely
rubbish.''
This further onslaught, following criticism from a stream of other
party members, was seized on gleefully by Tory party chairman Dr Brian
Mawhinney, who said it painted a picture of the Labour party and its
leadership ''which becomes less attractive but more accurate week by
week, indeed day by day''.
Mr Blair's office is unwilling to get into a slanging match with
critics, several of whom have always been opponents of the changes Mr
Blair, and before him Mr Kinnock, introduced.
None the less a considerable volume of dissent has surfaced in the
past week, ranging from general condemnation to opposition to particular
policies as in the case of former deputy leader Roy Hattersley.
Various forms of dissent have been registered by former Shadow Cabinet
member Bryan Gould, GMB leader John Edmonds, backbench MP Richard
Burden, Transport and General Workers Union leader Bill Morris, and a
number of left wing Labour MPs including Mr George Galloway (Hillhead)
and Mr Dennis Canavan (Falkirk West).
Dr Mawhinney smilingly declared: ''You haven't actually heard me use
such violent language against Mr Blair as is being used by his own
Members of Parliament.''
Mr Blair, who interrupts his holiday this weekend to take part in the
VJ-Day ceremonies, took sufficient notice of the criticism to issue a
statement saying that, while he had no wish to ''pick a fight'' with his
critics, he would press ahead with his crusade to modernise Labour and
make it fit to govern.
Mr Campbell attacked the way policy making has been developed in the
Labour party giving the leadership more control of what is debated at
the annual party conference.
Interviewed on BBC Radio 4's World At One he said: ''We now have a
national policy forum which is deciding policy for us. The Labour party
membership on the ground is just fodder.
''In the past, the conference used to decide policy. But it looks as
though there is a policy forum set up by people who have been educated
at university, Oxford and Cambridge, and they sit round the table and
decide what Tony Blair's next policy will be.
''We are becoming more like the Tory party, where the membership just
turns up at a little meeting and elects an MP now and then, whereas, in
the past, we used to passionately debate issues. We don't do that any
more.''
Dr Mawhinney said Mr Campbell's views came on the back of overnight
criticism from senior and respected Labour figures in local government.
''We have now learned a little more about Mr Blair's management style.
When he sees something or hears something that he doesn't like he has
some youth in his office ring up and slag off local Labour leaders
around the country.''
Mr Peter Greenwood, chairman of the Association of District Councils
and leader of Blackburn council, has accused Mr Blair of a series of
one-man U-turns on education, health, and regional government. Mr Derek
Bidman, leader of the Labour group on the Association of County
Councils, accused Mr Blair of seeing local government as Labour's
Achilles heel and wanting to move away from a regional approach to a
national system.
</TEXT>
