<HEADLINE>Beds for elderly to go</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863407</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HEALTH board officials confirmed yesterday that 60 beds for the frail
elderly at Stobhill hospital, Glasgow, are to be phased out by April
1998.
Greater Glasgow Health Board said the move was necessary following the
decision in March to retain 60 continuing care beds for the elderly at
Lenzie hospital, which were saved after a local community campaign.
A health union official said he believed it was part of a board plan
to switch provision for elderly patients from NHS hospitals to private
nursing homes.
GGHB chairman Sir Robert Calderwood said the decision followed a
three-month consultation exercise which showed the strength of support
for the retention of Lenzie hospital as part of the complement of 180
beds required for continuing care in the north of the board's area.
He said the consultation showed there was a general view that frail
elderly people should be cared for at home or in a community setting
wherever possible.
GGHB acting general manager Tom Divers said: ''The phased closure of
the beds at Stobhill will release resources for community- based,
long-term care and domiciliary services, including respite care,
additional community health services, paramedical, and nursing care.''
Mr Dave Watson, Glasgow regional officer for health with the public
service union Unison, said: ''The board has more or less admitted that
the decision has been taken with the longer-term view to switch
provision for elderly care from NHS hospitals to private nursing care.''
The board says that, in addition to 60 beds at Lenzie hospital, 120
continuing care beds will be provided at Fourhills nursing home, near
Stobhill.
</TEXT>
