<HEADLINE>Schoolgirl in a class of her own</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863408</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SUTHERLAND schoolgirl enjoys one of the most expensive educations in
Britain.
While sections of the middle class struggle to raise private school
fees, Eileen Grant, six, is in a class of her own. The head gamekeeper's
daughter is the only pupil of teacher Mary Harris at the school at Loch
Coire.
It costs council taxpayers in the Highlands more than twice as much to
educate Eileen near her home than it would to send her to the most
expensive fee-paying boarding school in the land.
Yesterday, education official John Metcalfe, of Golspie, Sutherland,
estimated that it costs up to #30,000 a year for Eileen's schooling.
By comparison, Eton, Harrow, Fettes College, and Gordonstoun charge
annual fees of between #11,000 to #12,000 for boarders.
Mr Metcalfe said Eileen was taught locally ''because of the commitment
of Highland region to education in remote rural areas''.
He added: ''It would have been harmful to the youngster's development
to have taken her away from home at that age.''
Eileen lives with mother Isobel and father Albert in a cottage near
the school. There are just two inhabited houses on the 33,500-acre Loch
Coire Estate.
Mrs Harris makes a daily round trip of 70 miles to the school from her
home in Helmsdale. The last twelve miles of her journey is on a dirt
road.
Eileen, who will be seven in October, yesterday started primary three
as the new session began.
She has been the only pupil for more than a year since another family
of estate workers moved away.
At the school, which is owned by Loch Coire Estate, the teacher and
pupil have a computer and a TV with video facilities.
1 Mrs Harris moved to Sutherland from England when her husband retired
and has been teaching at Loch Coire since the school re-opened in 1989.
She said: ''The little girl works hard at her schooling and I enjoy
teaching there. It makes a change from the schools of between 300 and
400 pupils I was used to working in before I came here.''
</TEXT>
