<HEADLINE>Aid workers crash on mountain road. Scot dies under fire in Bosnia. Scot aid worker dies in Bosnia</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863409</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOT was one of two aid workers killed on the road to Sarajevo
yesterday when their truck crashd after the convoy it was travelling in
came under fire.
UNICEF officials said the convoy had accelerated sharply to try to
avoid the gunfire and that one of the trucks which had been carrying
food parcels into the besieged Bosnian capital had gone out of control
and crashed.
Mr Neil Golightly, 34, a bachelor from Broomhill, Glasgow, and Mr Tony
Ritchards, from London, were killed in the crash which occurred on a
dangerous mountain road early yesterday on Mount Igman.
It is the only high ground around Sarajevo under Bosnian government
control and is used as the only access to the Bosnian capital.
The two men, who worked for UNICEF previously, were part of a convoy
organised by the UK-based charity, Phoenix Aid, which Mr Golightly was
instrumental in establishing.
Last night friends were comforting Mr Golightly's mother, Helen, 56,
and his father, Harry, 69, in the family home in Broomhill. His sister,
Karen, 32, lives in Aberdeen.
Mrs Golightly spoke of the family's sadness and shock on learning of
her son's death from police yesterday.
She said her son, who celebrated his birthday last Friday, had visited
home three weeks ago.
''He phoned us on Thursday and said he was off to Bosnia. He had first
gone there in October 1993, although he had holidayed in the former
Yugoslavia some years ago.''
She said her son had given up his job as a manager with Black and
Decker in London to return to Bosnia.
Although always aware of the dangers, she said: ''Youknow where they
are and what they are doing. But you never think it will happen until it
comes to your own doorstep.
''He was very involved and felt very strongly about what he was doing.
I am sure the good work he did will continue.''
She said her son, a former pupil of Glasgow Academy and student at
Strathclyde University, had spent virtually the past two years in the
former Yugoslavia.
Mrs Golightly said a member of Phoenix Aid had told her that the
convoy had come under fire. ''As far as I am aware the convoy
accelerated to escape the danger. But I am told the roads are just
dreadful. One of the vehicles keeled over and crashed and Neil and his
friend were killed.
''I feel very proud of him. We supported him totally in what he was
doing. He was a good son to us.''
Mr Golightly, a retired police inspector, said: ''We knew the dangers,
but we had to accept that. But with relatively few of the aid workers
and UN personnel being killed, it seems so shocking that Neil has become
a victim.''
Neil had taken the Duke of Edinburgh's award as a youngster and helped
train other young people to pass the award. His great passion was rugby
and he ran the Strathclyde University rugby club while he was there.
He had also helped with Riding for the Disabled. When he came back to
Scotland, his greatest joy was to travel north to Aberdeen and visit his
sister, Karen, 32, and her two children, Jennifer, 10, and Christine,
eight.
A Foreign Office spokesman in London said last night: ''We do not know
for sure what caused the crash. Possibly they were driving without
lights to avoid attracting gun fire. It had also been raining and it was
wet.
''We understand there had been some firing on the road, but not at
them, as far as we are aware.''
Heavy rain had turned the normally dusty road into a slippery track.
The truck the men were driving rolled over several times and crashed
down a ravine late on Monday night.
French UN troops recovered the bodies.
Mr Simon Ashmore, co-founder of Phoenix Aid along with Mr Golightly,
said last night: ''We are all absolutely devastated by this. I spent
more than a year living and working with Neil in Bosnia, he was more
than just an acquaintance.
''We all think we lead charmed lives and then this happens to show us
the reality of the situation. You never really understand the situation
you are in until something like this happens.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
