<DOCID>GH950816-000176</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863410</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HERALD reporter Craig Watson, who returned from a trip to Bosnia with
Phoenix Aid two weeks ago, writes:
The volunteers in Phoenix Aid were all aware of the risks they faced
delivering supplies to the victims of war. But, driven by a sense of
frustration and anger that ordinary civilians were suffering in their
hundreds of thousands, they had left the UK to try and make a
difference.
The aid workers -- the number involved fluctuates from just a handful
to enough for a small convoy -- set up bases in Bosnia and Croatia after
arriving in the former Yugoslavia around 18 months ago.
I joined them in Split after a chance meeting at the airport three
weeks ago. The commitment of the volunteers I met was absolute. Neil
Golightly, a co-founder of the organisation, was in the UK at the time
but I spent several days with Tony Ritchards and the other workers.
The group often discussed the dangers inherent in their task, but the
conversations inevitably turned to the politics of war and the horrors
individuals had encountered in the past.
No-one I met dwelled on the dangers; the opposite in fact.
</TEXT>
