<DOCID>GH950816-000177</DOCID>
<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Income up at City Centre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863411</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE current hot spell is proving a mixed blessing for City Centre
Restaurants.
While it is helping keep the British at home, it is attracting large
numbers of foreign tourists, but they are all spending less once they
get inside. There was also a decline in cinema attendances which
affected sales of Deep Pan Pizzas.
Nevetheless, half-time taxable profits rose 7.7% to #6.26m on turnover
6.3% greater at #51.8m. City Centre writes off the cost of all new
openings as they occur so profits are currently depressed by the 34
planned for 1995, of which 23 will be in the second half.
These include the now up-graded Garfunkels as well as Chiquito and
Nachos Mexican restaurants and roadside diners selling burgers and
salads. Pizza is essentially ex-growth due to saturation and, dare one
say it, sheer boredom, so City Centre is pushing the Caffe Uno
pasta-oriented concept with its black and metallic surroundings.
As usual, the interim dividend is being maintained at 0.45p. Full-year
profits could improve from #14.1m to perhaps #15.8m, which points to a
2.25p dividend total.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950816-000178</DOCNO>
