<DATE>950816</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Construction slump hits civil engineers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863412</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEW orders in the construction industry fell sharply in the second
quarter of this year but Scottish housebuilders suffered less than their
counterparts elswhere in the UK.
Scottish civil engineering contractors, on the other hand, were hit
every bit as hard as firms south of the Border.
Besides suffering cutbacks in central government spending, they faced
a dearth of new orders from the regional and district councils which
will be swept away next year to make way for 33 new single-tier
authorities.
''We are really standing on the brink of a sharp decline in activity
and employment,'' said Donald MacKenzie, Scottish representative of the
Federation of Civil Engineering Contractors.
UK construction orders fell by a seasonally adjusted 11% in the second
quarter compared to the first three months of this year, and by 14%
compared to the second quarter of 1994, the Department of the
Environment said yesterday.
The figures prompted renewed calls from the building industry for
measures to give the sector a boost. Suggestions include the restoration
of full mortgage tax relief for first-time home buyers and a cut in VAT
on house repairs from the present rate of 17.5% in the November Budget.
Mr MacKenzie urged the Government to simplify the rules of the Private
Finance Initiative to make it easier for construction firms to obtain
private finance for public works projects.
The Department of the Environment said private housing orders were
down 12% on the first quarter in the UK as a whole, but in Scotland they
rose by 3%.
Meanwhile, public housing and housing association orders showed a 12%
rise at a UK level, but in Scotland they soared 18%.
A separate trends survey carried out by the Scottish Building
Contractors' Association confirmed this brighter picture for house
builders north of the Border. It showed that Scottish housing starts
rose 7% in the second quarter despite a 15% fall in completions.
''We are either holding our own or going in the opposite direction (to
the rest of the UK),'' said Bob Campbell, the association's director.
He said Scotland had fared better than England and Wales because its
housing market was less volatile and was relatively free of negative
equity.
Alan Downie, managing director of Cala Homes, which builds houses in
both England and Scotland, added a third reason. He noted that only 55%
of Scots owned their homes, compared to about 75% of Englishmen. As a
result, there was still strong demand from first-time buyers on this
side of the Border.
''We are about to start seven new sites in the next six months which
total 800 houses and #80m. That is a statement of our confidence in the
Scottish economy,'' he said.
However, the Scottish trend in industrial and commercial building is
more downbeat and in line with the rest of the UK.
The Scottish Building Contractors' Association survey of more than 100
building firms showed ''a fair reduction of industrial building work''
in the second quarter, Mr Campbell said.
Commercial construction was boosted though by a number of shopping
centre developments and ''just about held its own'', he added.
The Department of the Environment said UK infrastructure orders
slumped 26% in the second quarter and Mr MacKenzie of the Federation of
Civil Engineering Contractors said this gloomy scenario applied fully to
Scotland.
Not only was the Government holding back on major road and rail
investment projects but local authorities were failing to carry out
routine maintenance of secondary roads because of spending limits
imposed by Whitehall, he said.
He added that, if the Government continued its spending cuts into
1996, Scottish civil engineering contractors would lose #100m of new
business.
''The planned cuts in spending are very, very worrying,'' he said,
noting that some Scottish firms had pulled out of contracting work
altogether. He said one company, which he refused to name, laid off 100
employees last month as it abandoned contracting work to concentrate on
quarrying.
He maintained the situation was particularly difficult in Scotland
since the out-going regional and district councils had postponed the
award of many new contracts.
There was little chance the incoming single-tier local authorities
would start placing these orders until the autumn of 1996, he added.
