<HEADLINE>Franc has little to celebrate</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863413</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE French franc, the world's first decimal coinage, had a subdued
200th birthday on Tuesday overshadowed by plans for its demise by the
end of the century.
''The forgotten bicentenary of the franc,'' said the daily newspaper
Le Parisien of a lack of official fanfare for the currency introduced in
the wake of the 1789 revolution.
In a drive to rationalise weights and measures, France voted on August
15, 1795, to introduce the franc, made up of 10 decimes or 100 centimes.
It replaced the royal livre, awkwardly split into 20 sous, which in turn
each comprised 12 deniers.
Now France wants to replace the franc with a single European currency
from 1999 as part of European Union moves for closer integration.
A few dedicated numismatists hailed the anniversary of the first
decimal coinage, saying it inspired similar systems around the world and
was a landmark in the history of modern France.
''By identifying the people, the nation, and the currency with the
same name, you have the cement of national unity,'' said Laurent
Schmitt, co-author of a book about the currency.
The original franc was worth 4.4 grams of silver and its value was
later pegged to gold under Napoleon.
After great stability during the nineteenth century, it suffered a
string of devaluations in the 20th, starting during the First World War
and the 1929 world economic crisis. -- Reuter
