<HEADLINE>A #1200m theme park based on comic heroes will be built around five Florida islands. Rank plans a rival to Disneyworld</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976863414</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RANK Organisation, which recently realised #620m from the sale of its
40% stake in Rank Xerox, and MCA, the entertainment subsidiary of the
Canadian-based Seagram company, are planning to build a second theme
park in Florida which could rival Disneyworld when it opens in 1999.
The projected $2000m (#1200m) ''destination resort'', to be known as
Universal City Florida (UCF), will be built on the land in Orlando which
already contains Universal Studios Florida (USF), the existing theme
park jointly owned by Rank and MCA.
A second theme park will be built with five individually themed
islands involving ideas such as Jurassic Park, Seuss Landing based on
the globally popular world of Doctor Seuss, Marvel Comics Superheroes
including Spiderman and X-Men, and Popeye and his fellow Sweethaven
cartoon residents. Each island will contain state of the art fun and
thrill rides and shows, live entertainment, restaurants, and retail
outlets.
On top of this, the project will have a 12-acre day and night
entertainment zone consisting of themed restaurants, nightclubs, a
16-screen, 5000-seat cinema, and retail outlets, open to both visitors
at the theme parks and the public.
There will be parking facilities, moving walkways, and infrastructure
to support the existing USF park, Universal's Island of Adventure, and
the entertainment zone, and it is also planned to build two hotels with
another two to follow later.
The financing for the project, which Rank shareholders are being asked
to approve at an EGM on October 3, is partly through a $1200m (#770m)
bank facility with the balance of $800m being provided jointly by Rank
and MCA. Rank's share of the joint financing is estimated at
approximately #256m over the period to opening and Rank will provide the
banking syndicate with a completion guarantee of #385m up to the opening
of the park.
In addition to this, the two partners will be seeking to raise $600m
for building the two hotels and discussions are in progress with
possible hotel equity investors to provide finance although Rank and MCA
plan to participate in the equity.
There is a buy/sell agreement which means that, if either partner
wishes to sell its interest, it must be offered to the other at a fair
price and not to a third party.
The existing Universal Studios Florida, in which Rank invested $273m
in December 1990, is now the third most visited attraction in North
America after the two Disney theme parks. The success of USF, whose paid
attendances have increased annually to a figure of around 6.4 million in
1994, with revenues of $317m and an operating profit of $51m, have
encouraged Rank and MCA to develop plans for expansion.
Rank said the development plans will continue to benefit from the
creative talents of Steven Spielberg, a special creative consultant to
the UCF project. MCA will continue to act as manager of USF and will
also manage the new theme park.
</TEXT>
