<HEADLINE>NVM issues prospectus for #15m venture capital trust</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976863415</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NORTHERN Venture Managers has released the prospectus for its #15m
venture capital trust, one of the first to get underway since the new
kind of investment companies were announced in the last Budget.
Investors putting money into the trust can obtain tax relief and
receive tax-free dividends and capital gains. They are designed to plug
the ''equity gap'' for companies seeking to raise finance of up to #1m.
Sponsored by stockbroker Wise Speke, Northern Venture Trust will
invest in about 20 small companies, primarily in Scotland and the north
of England. It will have a full stock market listing and the board
includes Primrose McCabe, immediate past president of the Institute of
Chartered Accountants of Scotland, and Ian Ritchie, who is involved in
the Scottish Business Forum.
Northern Venture Managers' investment director Tim Levett said few
venture capital trusts had been announced to date because only a handful
of fund managers had extensive experience of the relevant type and size
of investment.
The rules state 70% of the funds have to be invested within three
years in unquoted firms which must be trading and have gross assets of
not more than #10m. No single investment can exceed #1m.
His company, on the other hand, is an established specialist which can
point to a 10-year track record of similar investments. Between 1984 and
1995, its two venture capital funds made more than 60 unquoted
investments and an overall return of 12.8%. Northern Investors managed
23%.
There will be a placing and offer for sale of shares in Northern
Venture Trust.
* Abtrust High Income Trust, which invests in high-yielding shares in
other UK investment trusts, yesterday announced a third interim dividend
of 1.6p. This takes the payout for the nine months to end-June to 4.6p.
The #24m fund, launched in April 1994, suffered a 12.4% fall in nav to
78.14p during the nine months. This was attributed to the poor
performance of high-yielding, split-level income shares.
Abtrust High Income made earnings per share of 4.6p during the nine
months.
